<DOCNO> APW20000202.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High-Interest Lender Regs Nixed  </HEADLINE>
   By MARCY GORDON AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Partisan clashes over gun makers and anti-abortion
protesters is marking Senate debate on legislation that would make it tougher
for people to sweep away their debts through bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
	   An amendment proposed by Sens. Carl Levin, D-Mich., and Richard Durbin,
D-Ill., would prohibit gun makers and dealers from erasing debts in bankruptcy
that arose from successful lawsuits against them.
</P>
<P>
	   Conservative GOP lawmakers have protested the amendment as anti-business.
</P>
<P>
	   The proposal ``is designed to encourage lawsuits ... and put the firearms
industry in this country out of business,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman
of the Senate Judiciary Committee, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Noting that some two dozen U.S. cities and towns have sued gun makers and
distributors, Levin said the firearms industry ``should not be able to evade
judgments by going bankrupt.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Senate was voting today on the proposed amendment and on a provision,
sponsored by Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., that would require bankrupt people
found to have violated laws protecting abortion clinics to pay their penalties.
</P>
<P>
	   Schumer has cited the case of Operation Rescue founder Randall Terry, who
filed for bankruptcy court protection in November 1998, blaming heavy debts owed
to women's groups and abortion clinics that have sued him.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., denounced the proposal as an attempt ``to silence
the free speech of abortion opponents.''
</P>
<P>
	   Also Tuesday, the Senate rebuffed an attempt by some Democrats to make it
harder for high-interest, storefront lenders to collect debts from people who
have filed for bankruptcy relief.
</P>
<P>
	   Senators voted, 53-44, to reject an amendment proposed by Sen. Paul
Wellstone, D-Minn., that would have prohibited lending businesses charging more
than 100 percent annual interest in recovering debts from consumers in
bankruptcy proceedings.
</P>
<P>
	   A partisan dispute over a minimum wage increase and tax breaks for small
businesses, meanwhile, threatened to delay final Senate passage of the
legislation to overhaul the bankruptcy laws.
</P>
<P>
	   Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said a $1 increase in the $5.15 hourly
minimum over three years was insufficient. In addition, the White House and
Democratic lawmakers oppose $18.4 billion in small-business tax breaks proposed
by the GOP that are tied to the minimum wage increase.
</P>
<P>
	   If changes are not made, Daschle told reporters, ``I'm concerned that the
bankruptcy bill could be in some jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
	   The current bill, which appeared headed toward Senate passage today, has
been pushed by banks, credit card companies and retail-business groups.
Proponents say the bankruptcy overhaul is needed to stem abuse by people who can
afford to repay their debts.
</P>
<P>
	   Consumer groups and other opponents maintain the legislation favors
corporate profits over the needs of families struggling with debt. They insist
that the credit card companies share the blame by flooding consumers with mailed
solicitations to entice them into easy credit.
</P>
<P>
	   The House approved bankruptcy overhaul legislation last May by a veto-proof
margin, 313-108.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton administration, which supports overhauling the bankruptcy laws
in principle, has criticized the House and Senate versions as being too hard on
debtors.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to the minimum wage-tax breaks provision, the Senate bill
contains several other provisions unrelated to bankruptcy: tightened penalties
for selling illegal drugs to minors, a narrowing of the disparity in sentences
for sales of powder and crack cocaine, and stiffer penalties for makers of the
illegal drug methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
	   Wellstone's defeated proposal opened a debate on so-called payday loans --
small, short-term cash advances against a borrower's paycheck that carry
triple-digit interest rates. Wellstone called the businesses making them
``unscrupulous loan sharks.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Hatch insisted that payday loans are ``a legitimate service that many
honest consumers use.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 0016 </TRAILER>
