<HEADLINE> Trail Blazers 92, Bulls 81  </HEADLINE>
    By LANDON HALL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Brian Grant scored 19 points as the Portland Trail
Blazers moved atop the NBA overall standings by beating the Chicago Bulls 92-81
on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
	   The Blazers moved a half-game ahead of the Los Angeles Lakers, who lost to
San Antonio 105-81.
</P>
<P>
	   Rasheed Wallace, who earlier in the day was selected to the All-Star team
for the first time in his five-year career, added 14 points and nine rebounds
for Portland.
</P>
<P>
	   The last time the Blazers were all alone in first place in the Pacific
Division was Dec. 7, when they were 15-4 and the Lakers 14-4. Two days later,
Los Angeles pulled into a tie at 15-5 and held onto first until its recent
slide.
</P>
<P>
	   Elton Brand led the Bulls with 22 points and eight rebounds. Toni Kukoc
added 12 points but shot just 2-of-10 after the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   The Blazers, who have won six in a row and 10 straight at home, never
trailed against the Bulls, but Portland coach Mike Dunleavy was constantly
yelling at his team for giving up easy baskets and trying too many
highlight-reel dunk attempts.
</P>
<P>
	   Neither team seemed interested in playing much interior defense in the first
half, as Portland gave up 15 offensive rebounds and 24 points in the paint. The
Blazers, meanwhile, scored 36 inside points -- 16 on dunks.
</P>
<P>
	   A put-back by Brand ended an 8-0 run and cut the lead to 43-40 with 4:44
left in the first half, but the Bulls didn't hit a field goal for the next nine
minutes, and Portland pushed the lead back to 12 three minutes into the third.
</P>
</TEXT>
