night with a 5-4 victory over the Calgary Flames.
</P>
<P>
	   A pass from Michal Handzus sent Demitra in on a breakaway and he beat Fred
Brathwaite on a shot through the pads at 2:02 to win it.
</P>
<P>
	   The victory moved St. Louis past the Detroit Red Wings into first place in
the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
	   St. Louis had a 4-2 lead entering the final five minutes of the game but
goals 3:37 apart by Valeri Bure and Andrei Nazarov tied it.
</P>
<P>
	   The extra period featured the NHL's top two overtime teams. St. Louis
improved to 5-0-6 while Calgary dropped to 10-2-5.
</P>
<P>
	   The late-game excitement overshadowed a solid performance from St. Louis
center Marty Reasoner, who scored twice in his first game filling in for the
injured Pierre Turgeon.
</P>
<P>
	   Reasoner was recalled Monday from Worcester of the AHL. Scott Pellerin also
scored for St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
	   Demitra extended his point-scoring streak to seven games (4-5-9).
</P>
<P>
	   Jeff Shantz and Clarke Wilm also scored for the Flames.
</P>
<P>
	   The loss, Calgary's fourth in a row, snapped a seven-game home winning
streak. It was just the Flames second loss at the Canadian Airlines Saddledome
since Nov. 13 (13-2-1).
</P>
<P>
	   Trailing 4-2, Calgary pulled within one when Bure scored his 27th goal from
a scramble at 15:12.
</P>
<P>
	   Nazarov then tied it at 18:49, firing Marc Savard's pass past Roman Turek.
</P>
<P>
	   Bure's 27 goals are a career-high, surpassing the 26 he scored last season.
</P>
