<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Ready for Interest Rate Boost  </HEADLINE>
    By JEANNINE AVERSA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve is ready to bump up interest rates
for a fourth time since June in an effort to rein in the nation's economy, which
has been growing at a breakneck pace, private economists believe.
</P>
<P>
	   Ever since the Fed took a pass on raising rates in December to avoid stress
during the Y2K computer date change, most economists -- citing continuing strong
economic growth -- have been predicting that the central bank would boost rates
to help keep inflation under control. Most expect a quarter of a percentage
point.
</P>
<P>
	   When Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan raised new worries about inflation in a
speech last month, many economists took that as yet another signal that a rate
increase would be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
	   The Federal Open Market Committee, comprising members of the Fed board in
Washington and the presidents of the Fed's 12 regional banks, began a two-day
meeting Tuesday to review interest rate policy. A midafternoon announcement of
their decision was expected today, with financial markets eagerly awaiting the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks rose Tuesday amid a growing sense that despite rising interest rates,
which can cut into corporate profits, most U.S. companies will post strong
earnings growth throughout the year. The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed up
100.52 points at 11,041.05.
</P>
<P>
	   "The story that the Fed has been telling over the last month is that we
think growth is too strong and could produce inflation. We don't see a
likelihood that it will slow on its own, so we need to raise rates," said Tim
O'Neill, chief economist for the Bank of Montreal and Harris Bank. "That message
is coming across loud and clear."
</P>
<P>
	   The economy grew at a sizzling 5.8 percent annual rate in the last three
months of the year and by 4 percent for all of 1999. That growth has pushed down
the nation's unemployment rate to 4.1 percent, the lowest level in 30 years.
Many analysts believe a further dip to 4 percent will be reflected in January's
employment report Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   With the economy growing so fast, employers are having trouble finding
scarce workers to fill job openings. Thus, they are wooing them with higher
wages and benefits, increasing the costs of doing business to the point that
economists and members of the Fed fear a sharp run-up in prices.
</P>
<P>
	   Consumer prices have remained well-behaved so far, but wages and benefits,
as measured by the Labor Department's closely watched employment cost index,
surged in the fourth quarter, touching off fear about inflation and causing the
stock market to plunge when the report was released last week.
</P>
<P>
	   Some economists believe there could be a total of four rate increases,
beginning at today's meeting, of a quarter-point apiece by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it will be pretty clear that the Fed will view inflation as a
serious risk going forward," said William Cheney, chief economist for John
Hancock, referring to the Fed's new policy, starting today, of communicating its
outlook for the economy after every market committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed raised crucial interest rates three times last year by a
quarter-point each in June, August and November. A fourth quarter-point increase
would push the central bank's target for the federal funds rate -- the interest
banks charge on overnight loans -- to 5.75 percent from 5.50.
</P>
<P>
	   Commercial banks would follow suit, boosting the prime lending rate, the
benchmark for millions of business and consumer loans, to 8.75 percent from
8.50, raising Americans' borrowing costs.
</P>
<P>
	   A few economists see a chance that the Fed could increase the funds rate by
a more aggressive half a percentage point today, given the economy's robust
growth. Such a move would raise the funds rate to 6 percent and prompt banks to
raise their prime rate to 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In December, the Fed decided not to raise rates, not wanting to create more
uncertainties given the Y2K changeover. In the end, the century date change went
smoothly and caused no disruptions to the nation's banking system or financial
markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 0128 </TRAILER>
