<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghans Take Shelter in Embassy  </HEADLINE>
   By KATHY GANNON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KABUL, Afghanistan (AP)-- The tiny trembling hand of a 5-year-old girl
reached from beneath a tattered blue wool shawl to take a blackened piece of
carrot from a gnarled old man selling vegetables.
</P>
<P>
	   They are Afghan refugees in their own capital, driven by fighting to live in
squalor in the sprawling war-ruined embassy that was once home to Soviet
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
	   They are children, old men and women -- 15,000 souls, by U.N. count.
</P>
<P>
	   Plastic sheeting covers gaping holes in the rocket-shattered, four-story
buildings, wounds from the factional fighting that destroyed 70 percent of Kabul
in the mid 1990s when Islamic factions that drove the Soviets from Afghanistan
were in control. They in turn were ousted by the Taliban religious army in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   But the fighting persists.
</P>
<P>
	   Last summer, tens of thousands of Afghans were driven from their homes on
the Shomali Plains north of Kabul by fierce fighting between the Taliban, who
rule about 90 percent of the country and the opposition, which rules the other
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Some found refuge in opposition-ruled areas on the Panjshir Valley. In
Kabul, refugees were shepherded into the former Soviet Embassy compound. There,
the buildings were ravaged by rocket fire, pockmarked by bullet holes and
streaked in black soot.
</P>
<P>
	   The United Nations and other humanitarian aid organizations moved to help
the refugees, trucking in bricks and patching some holes.
</P>
<P>
	   Balconies were put up to protect wandering children, said Qari Mohammed
Daoud, the Taliban leader in charge of the compound.
</P>
<P>
	   The Taliban, beset by fighting and with few resources, daily send truckloads
of bread into the compound each day.
</P>
<P>
	   Aid agencies, including the World Food Program, also help out with food. One
group sends wood, the only source of heat in subzero temperatures. Another group
donated an ambulance and another built latrines. Garbage is trucked away by
still another aid group.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's like a small town,'' said Stephanie Bunker, the U.N. spokeswoman in
neighboring Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
	   In his fourth floor office-cum-residence, Daoud takes a seat on the floor:
His only furniture is a squeaky steel-frame bed with a thin cushion.
</P>
<P>
	   He sips sweet green tea from a chipped glass and says ``we have tried to
provide for them.''
</P>
<P>
	   In keeping with strict Taliban rules, two apartment buildings in the former
embassy compound have been set aside for women -- widows or women whose husbands
have gone north to escape. They must stay indoors, and the small children live
with them.
</P>
<P>
	   Only old men and young boys are allowed into the women's buildings, Daoud
said. Even a female reporter was barred.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.N. says the number of refugees in the former embassy total about
15,000, but no breakdown is available on the number of men, women and children.
</P>
<P>
	   From his balcony, Daoud points at the women's living quarters and says ``we
are their protection. We don't allow anyone to bother them.''
</P>
<P>
	   Life on the compound is hard.
</P>
<P>
	   Sitting on the cold ground, Abdul Hazim sells a grim collection of
vegetables, discards from city markets. He hunches over his vegetables,
occasionally glancing up at a passer-by.
</P>
<P>
	   A small child hidden beneath her shawl stood over his vegetables, just
looking. He picked up a small piece of a carrot, blackened from the cold, but
red within. The little hand reached out, trembling, and took it.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I had a home in Qaribagh. Now I have nothing,'' said Hazim, remembering a
time before the fighting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 0133 </TRAILER>
