<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diet May Influence Groundhog  </HEADLINE>
   By P. SOLOMON BANDA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DENVER (AP) -- Punxsutawney Phil and his kin may be predicting the length of
winter instead of hibernating because of their diet.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If they are feeding naturally out in the wild, in general they wouldn't be
coming above ground,'' said Greg Florant, a biology professor at Colorado State
University.
</P>
<P>
	   Florant and researchers from Temple University identified two fatty acids in
marmots that, in abundance, keep the mammals active. The fatty acids, linoleic
and linolenic acid, are found in seeds, nuts and leafy plants.
</P>
<P>
	   Because marmots are close cousins to groundhogs, the findings apply to
groundhogs too, Florant said.
</P>
<P>
	   Punxsutawney Phil, the groundhog who helps predict the length of winter each
year, gets a steady diet of vegetables, fruits, grasses and protein-rich
vegetarian dog food, said William Deeley, a member of the Punxsutawney Groundhog
Club and Phil's handler.
</P>
<P>
	   Punxsutawney Phil's diet is not designed to keep him awake, Deeley said.
Instead, a climate- and light-controlled cage in the town's library prevents him
from going into hibernation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He does sleep an awful lot but he doesn't go into the true coma type of
sleep,'' Deeley said. ``He is probably 25 percent active of what he would be
during the spring and summer.''
</P>
<P>
	   As legend goes, if a groundhog emerges from its burrow Feb. 2 and sees its
shadow, winter will linger six more weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Punxsutawney Phil was the guest of honor at several celebrations Tuesday in
Punxsutawney, home of the 114-year tradition based on a German superstition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
