<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Limitations Statute Eyed for Skakel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) -- Attorneys are questioning whether it's too late to
prosecute a nephew of Robert F. Kennedy for the 1975 slaying of a teen-age
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
	   Michael Skakel, 39, was arrested Jan. 19 for the slaying of Martha Moxley,
who was found beaten to death with a golf club more than 24 years earlier on her
family's estate.
</P>
<P>
	   When the slaying was committed, there was a 5-year statute of limitations on
murder prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutor Jonathan Benedict said the Connecticut Supreme Court has since
ruled that murder is a crime that is always subject to prosecution, but other
legal experts say it's not that simple.
</P>
<P>
	   The question was reported in Monday's edition of The Connecticut Law
Tribune.
</P>
<P>
	   David Moraghan, president of the Connecticut Criminal Defense Lawyers
Association, said he believes it is too late to prosecute Skakel.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think there's an argument that could be made that the case should be
dismissed,'' Moraghan said.
</P>
<P>
	   He and Benedict both cite case law that they say proves their points, and
Moraghan said it could take years for the issue to be decided.
</P>
<P>
	   The state law was changed in 1976 to eliminate any time limits for
prosecuting serious felonies, including murder.
</P>
<P>
	   Because Skakel was 15 at the time of the crime, he will be arraigned in
juvenile court. The hearing is scheduled for Feb. 8. Skakel has denied any
involvement in Moxley's death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
