<HEADLINE> Haider Fights for Political Power  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AP Photo NY107
By ROLAND PRINZ Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- The path to success for Joerg Haider has contained a
few pitfalls -- some of his own making. But they have not deterred Europe's most
popular rightist from his goal of political power.
</P>
<P>
	   Most recently, Haider has had to deal with massive foreign pressure against
his party's participation in Austria's next government. Predictably, Haider is
unfazed as he and his negotiating partners reached agreement on a coalition
government made up of his Freedom Party and the conservative Austrian People's
Party.
</P>
<P>
	   Typically, the 50-year-old lawyer attacks his attackers. It's not his party
that is undemocratic, he alleges, but the European Union, which is ignoring the
wishes of Austria's voters in threatening sanctions if his party shares
government power.
</P>
<P>
	   Austrians traditionally reject foreign criticism of their politicians --
including President Kurt Waldheim, who was widely supported in the 1980s despite
accusations that he hid a Nazi past.
</P>
<P>
	   Sometimes Haider's outspokenness has gotten him into trouble in a 30-year
political career that began as the head of the youth section of the Freedom
Party.
</P>
<P>
	   From there, the trim, youthful-looking Haider moved up the ladder until he
ousted his predecessor as head of the national party in 1986. He steered the
party away from liberalism and toward the populist-nationalist mix many
Austrians have responded to.
</P>
<P>
	   Haider, the child of well-to-do parents born in Upper Austria province, is
best known abroad for his past praise of Hitler and the Nazis -- statements he
has long since withdrawn -- and his party's public suspicion of foreigners,
manifested in last year's Vienna election posters warning in Nazi-era jargon of
``overforeignization.''
</P>
<P>
	   But deep-rooted Austrian suspicion of foreigners is only part of the formula
that made his party the second most popular in October elections and gave it the
chance to become part of the next government.
</P>
<P>
	   Haider and other party officials have also attacked the traditional parties:
the conservative People's Party and the Social Democrats who had governed
Austria for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Charges of corruption, cronyism and inertia hit home with an electorate that
-- while enjoying one of Europe's highest living standards -- was ready for
change.
</P>
<P>
	   Negotiations with the People's Party, which have ledto a proposed government
coalition, have been marked by professionalism and levelheadedness, according to
reports from those talks.
</P>
<P>
	   Even before the Oct. 3 elections, the trim lawyer with a perpetual tan,
whose accomplishments include bungee-jumping and who changes from jeans to suits
with chameleon-like ease, appeared to have learned from the past.
</P>
<P>
	   The married father of two children has blunted his sharp rhetoric. He has
avoided bad company since his 1996 meeting with Waffen SS veterans. And he
attended Harvard for a few weeks a few years ago, as much to improve his image
as his knowledge of economics.
</P>
<P>
	   In November last year, Haider distanced himself from ``misleading comments''
and apologized to his country's Jewish community for his past praise of the Nazi
era.
</P>
<P>
	   Still concern from the European Union, the United States and other
democracies remains. Haider has spoken out against EU expansion, saying it would
threaten jobs in Austria, and he has predicted that the new government would
impose a nearly complete ban on immigration.
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement Monday, the EU said it would curtail bilateral contacts with
Austria, oppose appointments of Austrian candidates to international
organizations and limit contacts with Vienna's ambassadors in EU capitals if
Haider's party shares power. State Department spokesman James Foley said the
United States is ``continuing to keep the situation under review.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
