<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Karen Rebels Ready To Talk  </HEADLINE>
   By THAKSINA KHAIKAEW Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MAE SOT, Thailand (AP) -- When Ba Thin joined up in 1949, the ethnic Karen
minority's war for freedom from the country then known as Burma looked like it
would be short.
</P>
<P>
	   Battle-hardened Karen fighters, who had helped colonial ruler Britain fight
Japanese troops in World War II, had pushed the post-independence Burmese army
to the capital, Rangoon, and looked set to carve out an independent state.
</P>
<P>
	   More than half-a-century later, only the dwindling numbers of Ba Thin's
generation can remember the scent of victory.
</P>
<P>
	   With Karen forces facing annihilation from the ever-more powerful government
army, the situation has become so desperate that perhaps 200 fighters have
turned for leadership to twin 12-year-old boys leading a faction called God's
Army.
</P>
<P>
	   The future of the Karens -- who account for 7 percent of Myanmar's 48
million people -- may rest in the hands of Ba Thin, 73, who was elected
president of the main rebel group, the Karen National Union, in a congress last
week.
</P>
<P>
	   Ba Thin's accession amounted to a tacit admission of the obvious -- the war
is all but lost. He replaced Bo Mya, also 73, a bearish general who had led the
KNU since 1976 and stubbornly presided over defeat after defeat in the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking to reporters during Monday's celebration of Karen Revolution Day,
Ba Thin took pains to say that his elevation would not affect KNU policy, which
is to rally world pressure on the military to allow democratic rule and greater
autonomy for ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
	   But he stressed the need for negotiation and voiced less of the
fight-to-the-end rhetoric that became Bo Mya's hallmark.
</P>
<P>
	   Educated in missionary Baptist high schools in the 1940s, Ba Thin joined the
KNU at its inception in 1949 and rose through rebel ranks to colonel. He then
shifted to the political wing, becoming secretary-general in 1982.
</P>
<P>
	   ``When I started serving my people, I had to carry a gun. There have been so
many killings in my life,'' Ba Thin told The Associated Press in an interview.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our problems can only be solved at the negotiating table, not in battle.
But surrender is also out of the question to pursue our goal.''
</P>
<P>
	   The KNU, however, has increasingly little bargaining leverage. A decade ago,
it was the strongest of a score of ethnic armies fighting the government and
controlled vast swaths of territory in eastern Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
	   Gems and teak traded through Thailand enabled it to hire foreign mercenaries
and line the pockets of corrupt Thai and Karen officials.
</P>
<P>
	   Since then, the government has made peace with nearly all the other factions
and practically only a rump of the KNU is left fighting.
</P>
<P>
	   In the early 1990s, the government orchestrated a split in the group,
bringing Buddhist Karens disaffected with the mostly Christian leaders under its
control.
</P>
<P>
	   The pro-government Democratic Karen Buddhist Army has been an instrument of
terror, raiding refugee camps in Thailand sheltering more than 100,000 refugees
from Myanmar, mostly Karen civilians.
</P>
<P>
	   Under annual government offensives since then, the KNU lost all but a few
toe-holds in Myanmar. Fighting strength is down to an estimated 4,000 troops --
from a one-time high of more than 20,000 -- and many new recruits are only in
their early teens.
</P>
<P>
	   The KNU depends on Thailand for a safe rear area, but the Thai government
increasingly views Myanmar's dissidents as more of a security threat than as a
buffer against Myanmar's army.
</P>
<P>
	   The feeling of defeat has been so pervasive as to send some KNU veterans
into God's Army, which siezed a hospital with hundreds of hostages last week in
an attempt to secure retreat into Thailand. The hostage-takers were killed, and
the operation deepened Thai distrust of the Karens.
</P>
<P>
	   Bo Mya has held cease-fire negotiations with the government on several
occasions in the past five years. Each time, they failed, once over the regime's
insistence that the KNU give up its arms.
</P>
<P>
	   Some other rebel groups that have reached cease-fires have kept their
weapons -- including the 20,000-strong United Wa State Army, considered by
Washington to be the world's biggest armed drug-trafficking group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
