<HEADLINE> Report Says IRA Hasn't Disarmed  </HEADLINE>
   By SHAWN POGATCHNIK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Northern Ireland's joint
Protestant-Catholic administration, launched in such high hopes two months ago,
is in danger of unraveling over the Irish Republican Army's continued
unwillingness to disarm.
</P>
<P>
	   But Britain's minister for Northern Ireland, Peter Mandelson, is hoping to
resurrect the American-mediated pact that spurred the Cabinet's formation --
and, crucially, expected that the IRA would scrap its stockpiled weapons in
response.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We still have a small breathing space to see whether it's possible to find
a solution to the crisis we're now facing,'' said Mandelson, who planned
separate meetings starting today with all four parties in the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
	   This week's report by Canadian Gen. John de Chastelain, chairman of a
disarmament commission, confirmed that his two months of discussions involving
IRA representatives produced no commitment from the outlawed group.
</P>
<P>
	   The major Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists, accused its Cabinet
colleagues in the IRA-linked Sinn Fein party of welching on their end of the
deal mediated by American diplomat George Mitchell in November.
</P>
<P>
	   Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble warned that the only way now to keep
the Cabinet intact at all was for the British government to suspend its powers,
resume ``direct rule'' from London, and hope fresh negotiations would deliver
either a start to disarmament or political penalties against Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
	   Trimble, who until now has outmaneuvered Protestants opposed to the 1998
peace accord, is scheduled to meet Prime Minister Tony Blair in London today to
press his case for what he called ``putting the administration on ice.''
</P>
<P>
	   He insisted that November's negotiations produced ``an understanding''
between Sinn Fein and the Ulster Unionists that the Cabinet could only survive
for a matter of weeks if the IRA balked on disarmament.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was made clear to Sinn Fein again and again and again that this
experiment, this risk that we were taking, would be time-limited and would not
run beyond the end of January,'' Trimble said.
</P>
<P>
	   But Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams described as ``nonsense'' the idea that the
IRA would begin discussing disarmament ``in return for six or seven weeks of
government.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said the Good Friday accord's hope of achieving total IRA disarmament by
May 2000 also presumed that the Cabinet would have been formed by late 1998, so
any notion of disarmament deadlines looked increasingly unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Unionists break deadlines whenever it suits them,'' Adams said. ``It's our
job as politicians to demonstrate to those in control of weapons that politics
works. Because of Ulster Unionist demands we are ... failing to do that.''
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement issued Tuesday, the IRA emphasized the value of its 1997
cease-fire, which followed a 27-year effort to destabilize Northern Ireland that
claimed 1,800 lives.
</P>
<P>
	   The IRA said its representatives had stressed in its talks with the
disarmament commission ``that the IRA's guns are silent and that there is no
threat to the peace process from the IRA.''
</P>
<P>
	   De Chastelain's commission has also been discussing disarmament prospects
with representatives of two major outlawed pro-British groups, the Ulster
Defense Association and Ulster Volunteer Force.
</P>
<P>
	   Those groups, responsible for slaying several hundred Catholic civilians,
called a cease-fire in 1994 but have vowed not to get rid of their own weapons
stocks unless the IRA moves first.
</P>
<P>
	   The IRA has a network of hidden arms caches in the neighboring Irish
Republic. The bulk was supplied by Libya in the mid-1980s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
