<DOCNO> APW20000202.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Nun Holed Up in Monastery  </HEADLINE>
   By DINA KRAFT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JERICHO, West Bank -- An American nun holed up in a monastery for 17 days to
keep out Palestinian police says she spends her days huddled around a small
heater, reading the Gospels and collecting food packages through a locked gate.
</P>
<P>
	   Maria Stephanopoulos, a sister of former White House spokesman George
Stephanopoulos, said that her faith and conviction keep her strong behind the
stone walls and iron gates of the Jericho Garden Monastery.
</P>
<P>
	   She and another American nun, Sister Xenia from San Francisco, both of the
``White'' church founded by Russian exiles, barricaded themselves in the
compound during a raid by Palestinian police on Jan. 15. They have since refused
to leave.
</P>
<P>
	   The police evicted most of the ``White'' clerics and said they had documents
showing the monastery belonged to their rival Moscow-based ``Red'' Russian
Orthodox Church.
</P>
<P>
	   Church property in east Jerusalem and the West Bank has been under ``White''
control since the 1917 Russian Revolution, when it split from the ``Red'' and
went into exile to avoid Communist control.
</P>
<P>
	   Now the Moscow-based Church is pressing the Palestinians, who are eager for
strong ties with Russia, to recognize their claims.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking to an Associated Press reporter through the gate of the compound,
Sister Maria described her days in an abandoned room on the property with a
leaky roof, peeling paint and only an outdoor spigot for washing.
</P>
<P>
	   Clutching rosary beads, she said her struggle is in the tradition of martyrs
of her church persecuted under communism.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They were truly Orthodox and truly loved the Russian Orthodox faith.
That's what I'm inspired by, and they were in far worse conditions than we
are,'' said the 40-year old nun, originally from New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   Palestinian officials met Tuesday with members of the Moscow Patriarchy
including Metropolitan Kirill, a top ranking figure in the Russian Orthodox
Church, to discuss the monastery standoff.
</P>
<P>
	   Representatives from the ``White'' church were not invited.
</P>
<P>
	   Mitri Abu Aitta, the Palestinian tourism minister, said that at the meeting,
the Palestinian Authority proposed providing the ``Whites'' with a plot of land
near the compound while handing the monastery itself over to the ``Reds.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are simply returning the property to (its) rightful owners,'' Abu Aitta
said.
</P>
<P>
	   However, Archbishop Mark, the highest ranking ``Red'' Church official in the
Holy Land, rejected the compromise.
</P>
<P>
	   New York City Congresswoman Carolyn Maloney wrote to Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat on Monday blasting him for the eviction attempt and demanding that
the matter be turned over to a court.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has also asked Arafat to resolve
the issue, Palestinian officials say.
</P>
<P>
	   Sister Maria compared a suggestion that the two churches share the property
to the biblical story of Solomon suggesting to two women who claimed to be
mother to the same child that the infant be cut in two and shared.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The true mother could not bear such a thought,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
