<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congressman: Reduce Runway Incidents  </HEADLINE>
   By DEB RIECHMANN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In Chicago, quick action by the pilot of a passenger jet
averts a collision with another aircraft on takeoff. In Los Angeles, two jets
nearly collide on a runway after a pilot misunderstands a controller's command.
In Rhode Island, a pilot refuses to take off until the location of a passenger
plane is confirmed.
</P>
<P>
	   Incidents that occur at airports as planes taxi, take off and land have
increased from 204 in 1994 to 327 last year, according to the Federal Aviation
Administration.
</P>
<P>
	   Saying the FAA needs to do more, Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., on Tuesday called
on the agency to convene a summit to find ways to reverse the trend. To
underscore the problem, Wolf played a tape recording of a USAir pilot in
Providence, R.I., who ignored his clearance for takeoff on Dec. 6, 1999 until he
was sure there was no other plane in his path.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Until we figure out what's going on down there, we're just going to stay
clear of all runways,'' the USAir pilot told the air traffic controller.
</P>
<P>
	   Wolf, chairman of the House Appropriations Committee's transportation
subcommittee, said he will ask the FAA to provide details of a more aggressive
effort to reduce runway incidents at his subcommittee's March 22 hearing on
aviation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Statistics show that the American public continues to be at unnecessary
risk of an aviation disaster, but as bad as the situation is, the problem will
only get worse if more is not done,'' Wolf said. ``The volume and complexity of
air traffic is expected to rise significantly over the next few years.''
</P>
<P>
	   Called runway ``incursions'' by federal aviation officials, they range from
two planes nearly colliding to a vehicle or person getting too close to a plane
taxiing to a gate.
</P>
<P>
	   John Mayrhofer, FAA director of runway safety, said the problem is complex
because it involves thousands of controllers, pilots and people authorized to
operate vehicles and equipment at airports nationwide.
</P>
<P>
	   He said FAA Administrator Jane Garvey has given the problem a higher level
of management focus in recent months, and that there have been fewer runway
incursions recorded in five of the past six months as compared to the same
periods a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   The FAA is working on a lower-cost alternative to costly ground radar
systems used at the nation's busiest airports, he said. For larger airports, a
new system designed to prevent runway collisions has been delayed until 2002. In
addition, Mayrhofer said the FAA has training, education and awareness programs
addressing the problem.
</P>
<P>
	   Among runway incursions reported last year:
</P>
<P>
	   -- On April 1 in Chicago, a Korean Air jet taking off with more than 350
people on board averted a collision with a cargo plane that had taxied into its
path.
</P>
<P>
	   -- On Nov. 22 in Los Angeles, a United Airlines Boeing 757 carrying more
than 130 people was forced on takeoff to pull up and fly over an Aeromexico
MD-80 on the runway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 0209 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
