<HEADLINE> Documents Link Chiefs To Drug Probe  </HEADLINE>
    By CRAIG HORST AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Tamarick Vanover and Bam Morris, members of the
1999 Kansas City Chiefs, are being investigated for a possible link to drug
trafficking from Missouri to California.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal authorities emphasized that neither man has been charged. But
charges were filed against Greg Burns, who is described as the personal
assistant to Vanover, a return specialist whose 80-yard punt return sparked the
Chiefs to victory against Denver this season.
</P>
<P>
	   An affidavit naming Vanover and Morris was filed in federal court Jan. 25 in
connection with the case against Burns. The affidavit also linked Vanover to a
stolen car.
</P>
<P>
	   Burns was charged last week with conspiracy to distribute marijuana. He was
said to be "a significant cocaine and marijuana supplier in the Kansas City
metropolitan area."
</P>
<P>
	   The affidavit, signed by FBI agent Larry G. Tongate, says Vanover's house
was under surveillance since April.
</P>
<P>
	   Two other men mentioned in the affidavit also were charged early last month
with drug trafficking. Chad Pollard and Logan Gearheart, both of Kansas City,
Kan., each pleaded not guilty at hearings. Gearheart soon was released on bond.
</P>
<P>
	   But the Kansas City Star reported that a federal magistrate judge denied
bond for Pollard after testimony from an FBI agent that "he has supplied members
of the Kansas University football team with drugs since 1996 as well as various
Kansas University fraternities."
</P>
<P>
	   Doug Vance, Kansas' assistant athletic director for media relations, said
the reference to the program came as a surprise.
</P>
<P>
	   "No one has any knowledge of this person or any contact with any
investigation related to this issue," Vance told the Star. "We have a
comprehensive drug-testing program here, so if any of that is going on, it's
going on in spite of that."
</P>
<P>
	   Morris, a sixth-year running back who unexpectedly retired from the NFL less
than two weeks ago, twice was suspended by the NFL for substance abuse while
with the Pittsburgh Steelers. He spent 89 days in jail in Texas for violating
terms of the probation he was given in 1996 after pleading guilty to marijuana
possession. He was arrested near Rockwall, Texas, with six pounds of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
	   Tongate said in the affidavit that he received information about "the drug
distribution activities" of Vanover and two people not associated with the
Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
	   The affidavit noted that on April 23, a car driven by a friend of Morris,
DeWayne Bryant, was seen leaving Vanover's house with Morris as a passenger. The
car was stopped in the Kansas City suburb of Leawood, Kan., and marijuana
residue was found in the car, according to the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
	   Morris was not charged.
</P>
<P>
	   The car had been stolen in Dallas, according to the affidavits.
</P>
<P>
	   The affidavit also said Vanover sold a car stolen from a Kansas City
dealership to a man in Florida for $10,000.
</P>
<P>
	   Morris' agent, Terry Lavenstein, did not return phone calls to The
Associated Press. He earlier told Kansas City radio station WHB, "Bam Morris, as
far as we know, is not involved in any activity in this ridiculous story."
</P>
<P>
	   The affidavit said the investigation was centered on a "large scale,
organized, and structured organization" involved in the distribution of
marijuana and cocaine.
</P>
<P>
	   "This organization has been distributing marijuana and cocaine in numerous
states," the affidavit said. "Members of the organization obtain marijuana and
cocaine from sources in Mexico, California, and Texas for distribution in
Missouri and Kansas."
</P>
<P>
	   Chiefs fullback Tony Richardson said he was shocked to hear that Morris
might be involved in another drug investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   "We had a lot of time to talk and reflect on a lot of things," Richardson
said. "He never gave me any indication something like this was going on. He
probably wouldn't tell me anyway because I'd wring his neck."
</P>
<P>
	   A spokesman for the Chiefs said club officials hadn't been contacted.
</P>
<P>
	   "All we know is that Bam Morris sent a letter to the NFL declaring that he
was retiring as of 4 p.m. on Jan. 18," team spokesman Bob Moore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 0213 </TRAILER>
