<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Denies Lewis Accusations  </HEADLINE>
    By JAMES PILCHER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- Ray Lewis' attorney proclaimed the innocence of the Pro Bowl
linebacker and expressed confidence he will be cleared of murder charges in the
stabbing deaths of two men following a post-Super Bowl party.
</P>
<P>
	   "Ray is doing fine," defense lawyer Max Richardson Jr. said Tuesday after
Lewis was ordered held without bond pending another court date Feb. 24. "He
believes the system will ultimately show that he is innocent of these heinous
crimes."
</P>
<P>
	   Lewis is charged with two counts of murder in the deaths of Richard Lollar,
24, and Jacinth "Shorty" Baker, 21, early Monday in Atlanta's Buckhead
entertainment district.
</P>
<P>
	   The Baltimore Ravens linebacker faces a possible sentence of life in prison
or the death penalty if convicted.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're taking the position that he was in the wrong place at the wrong
time," Richardson said outside the courtroom where Lewis appeared briefly,
wearing handcuffs and a red jail uniform. "From what I've gathered from law
enforcement officers, they know Ray didn't kill these unfortunate victims.
</P>
<P>
	   "They don't know where the other two men who were involved are, so they
arrested Ray," Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution reported today that police were holding
Lewis' limousine driver under guard in a hotel room while they hunted for others
who were with Lewis' entourage early Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Detectives said they were gathering information for murder warrants on at
least two more men who were with Lewis in his limousine, but they would not
identify the men, the paper said. It said one officer believed that they were
not active NFL players.
</P>
<P>
	   In Baltimore, The Sun reported that the owner of the limousine, Tony Toscov,
said the driver, Duanne Fassett, told him that Lewis did not stab the men.
</P>
<P>
	   The pretrial hearing was continued at the request of prosecutors, who said
they needed more time to interview witnesses.
</P>
<P>
	   Atlanta Solicitor General Raines Carter, who handles the early phases of
cases for the city before they are transferred to Superior Court, said that
Atlanta police made the decision to file murder charges.
</P>
<P>
	   He added that police officials had yet to provide him any details of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   Atlanta police spokeswoman Marion Lee would not comment on why murder
charges were filed or whether a search is on for other suspects, saying only
that the investigation was ongoing.
</P>
<P>
	   Baker and Lollar were stabbed repeatedly, according to the Fulton County
medical examiner's office. According to Lollar's grandmother, both men moved to
the Atlanta area from Ohio about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   "Richard was very good at cutting hair, and could make anyone look good,"
Joyce Lollar of Akron said, adding that he and his girlfriend were expecting a
baby next month. "He was really into being fashionable and always wanted to look
good himself.
</P>
<P>
	   "He would cut everyone's hair starting when he was 11 years old, and Shorty
was one of the guys who would come around," she said, adding that her grandson's
funeral would be held in Akron as soon as the body was released and flown north.
"He would have made a good daddy."
</P>
<P>
	   Lollar's cousin, Teresa Lollar, said Tuesday from their grandmother's home:
"To know that an NFL player is involved just goes to show you that regardless of
your status, you can just be an ordinary person when it comes to the law."
</P>
<P>
	   Police said officers responding to a call about a fight in Buckhead found
the two men lying in the street.
</P>
<P>
	   Joyce Lollar said several of Lollar's friends told her he was trying to
break up a fight between Baker and an unidentified man when a group of men
ambushed them.
</P>
<P>
	   "That was just what he was all about, trying to be the peacemaker," she
said. "Then these guys got away in some limo. To watch CNN and ESPN and see his
body being carted away, that really just hurts deeply."
</P>
<P>
	   Kevin Byrne of the Ravens, who moved from Cleveland and changed their name
in 1996, said the team has taken no action against the 24-year-old Lewis.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have not had the opportunity to speak to Ray Lewis about this matter,
and we can only hope that the charges against Ray are false." Byrne said. "This
is a very serious matter to the Baltimore Ravens. Two young men died in Atlanta,
and we offer our sympathies to their families and friends."
</P>
<P>
	   Gene Washington, director of player development for the NFL, told the
One-on-One sports radio network in Chicago: "This kind of news is almost
devastating. We certainly, for his own good, hope that it's not true, and for
the good of the NFL."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
