<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Arms Smugglers Sentenced  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALCUTTA, India (AP) -- A British arms dealer and five Latvians were
sentenced to life in prison today for smuggling arms intended for a revolution
against India.
</P>
<P>
	   Peter Bleach, the arms trader, and the Latvian crewmen who parachuted crates
of weapons into eastern India five years ago, said they would appeal their
conviction to a higher court.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am very disappointed, but not surprised,'' Bleach said outside the
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
	   The men were convicted of aiding insurgents who intended to wage war against
India.
</P>
<P>
	   The case was closely watched because it touched on the international arms
market and involved some of the most serious charges brought against Western
defendants.
</P>
<P>
	   The six have spent four years in jail since they were arrested.
</P>
<P>
	   The prosecution claimed the assault rifles, rocket launchers, grenades and
missiles were intended for an anti-communist religious group in West Bengal, a
state with a communist government.
</P>
<P>
	   Bleach argued that he had secretly kept the British intelligence services
informed of the plan to fly arms to India.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
