<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 02:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Fire Departments Need Volunteers  </HEADLINE>
   By KRISTEN HAYS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MOUNT PLEASANT, Pa. (AP) -- Walter ``Frosty'' Forys may not be able to hoist
a 100-pound ladder anymore, but he can still throw on a fireman's hat and hook a
hose to a hydrant.
</P>
<P>
	   At 88, the retired coal miner is the oldest volunteer firefighter in Mount
Pleasant, a community that still needs his more than 50 years of experience
battling blazes.
</P>
<P>
	   Mount Pleasant isn't alone. The state has lost about half of its volunteer
firefighters in the past five years, part of a nationwide decline.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It used to be we always had plenty of firefighters in the hopper,'' Forys
said. ``But now there are a lot of volunteer companies thinking of folding up.
Nobody wants to do this anymore.''
</P>
<P>
	   According to the National Fire Protection Association, the nation's
volunteer force dropped 13 percent from 1983 to 1991, to 771,800 firefighters.
That increased to 838,000 in 1995, but dropped again to 804,200 by 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Smaller communities have been hard hit, forced to depend on a grayer
population for jobs that increasingly entail more fund raising than
firefighting. As of 1998, about 13 percent of firefighters in cities of 10,000
or more were 50 or older; the association said the figure in towns with fewer
than 2,500 people was even greater, at 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Many blame the booming economy for thinning out the ranks of volunteer
firefighters.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're in a low point, because with the good economy and low unemployment
like we have now, people are just unable to be as active as we want them to
be,'' said Jerry Lucia, Mount Pleasant's mayor and chief of the volunteer fire
department.
</P>
<P>
	   About 90 percent of Pennsylvania's 2,464 fire departments are run by
volunteers, the highest percentage of any state, said Heather Schafer, executive
director of the National Volunteer Fire Council. By comparison, Texas has 1,600
volunteer departments, and New York has 1,400.
</P>
<P>
	   Since 1985, Pennsylvania has lost thousands of volunteer firefighters while
emergency response calls increased 48 percent, said John Brenner, executive
director of the Pennsylvania Fire and Emergency Services Institute in
Harrisburg.
</P>
<P>
	   Diane Bailey's husband, Bernard, dropped out of Mount Pleasant's force three
years ago after 12 years of service. She worries whether enough firefighters
will be around when it counts.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It does become a concern for people in the area only because we know the
ranks are down,'' she said. ``Our fire department does good work, but you never
know when it might be your place that gets involved in a disaster and you always
hope the best possible people are there.''
</P>
<P>
	   A key hurdle for volunteers is that fire protection isn't cheap. State law
allows municipal fire taxes to be used only for equipment, maintenance and
buildings -- not for salaries, pensions or other perks.
</P>
<P>
	   Lucia said the $37,000 in local fire taxes pays a portion of the cost to
maintain Mount Pleasant's two-story red brick firehouse, a storage building and
seven trucks.
</P>
<P>
	   Department volunteers run bingo games every Tuesday night and a week-long
street fair every June to raise the lion's share to operate. Firefighters go
door-to-door to raise money to buy or repair pumpers and ladder trucks, which
cost $350,000 to $500,000.
</P>
<P>
	   It takes several years to raise that much cash, Lucia said, so the
door-knocking never stops in this southwestern Pennsylvania town of 4,800
people. Fund raising is mandatory in Mount Pleasant's department, and most of
its 46 members are either single or retired.
</P>
<P>
	   No one, it seems, is standing in line to sign up.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Most people don't join the fire house to sell hoagies and run bingo. They
join to answer calls,'' said Brenner, himself a firefighter at the Lincolnway
Volunteer Fire Company in Manchester Township.
</P>
<P>
	   The constant need to find money played a big part in why Ms. Bailey's
husband called it quits, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He did as much as he possibly could, but he couldn't meet the extra
demands of the bingos,'' said Mrs. Bailey. ``We even paid someone $20 to do it
each time my husband was due to handle a bingo night when he couldn't be there.
The time commitment was just too much.''
</P>
<P>
	   State Rep. Victor Lescovitz of Washington said if something isn't done, some
volunteer departments will dry up -- and taxpayers eventually will feel the
bite. He plans to introduce legislation to allow for state or municipal tax
dollars to be used for incentives, such as pensions or tuition reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If we don't resolve it, we're going to end up with a big problem here in
the next 10 to 15 years when we have no volunteers,'' he said. ``Volunteer fire
departments save hundreds of millions of dollars each year to taxpayers. If we
have paid departments, they will pay much more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 0255 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
