<DOCNO> APW20000202.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 02:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Graf on board for AmericaOne Win  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD ULMAN-
AP Sports Writer-
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) -- Steffi Graf took a wild ride on AmericaOne. When
it was over and the U.S. boat was tied with Italy in the the America's Cup
challenger finals, skipper Paul Cayard and his famous guest were thrilled.
</P>
<P>
	The best-of-9 series is 3-3, but it appears to be advantage, Cayard.
</P>
<P>
	Once, AmericaOne trailed Prada of Italy 3-1. But after winning by 34 seconds
Tuesday and 9 seconds Wednesday in the closest race of the round, Cayard had the
momentum going into today's seventh race.
</P>
<P>
	The winner of the series advances to the best-of-9 America's Cup finals against
defending champion New Zealand starting Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
	``Things happen in sailboat races, and we got to a score that wasn't exactly
the score we were hoping for,'' Cayard said, ``but it didn't mean we're out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
	His 16-man crew might have had its best performance today. Graf, filling the
role of ''17th man,'' took it all in. Each boat is allowed to take a non-sailing
passenger on board as a spectator.
</P>
<P>
	Graf, in Auckland for a tennis exhibition, visited the AmericaOne compound
Tuesday and asked to tag along. It wasn't center court at Wimbledon, but she was
watching two boats seeking the top prize in sailing.
</P>
<P>
	``It's as thrilling as can be,'' Graf said. ``That race was incredible.''
</P>
<P>
	``She's a very competitive person and we gave her the best that this sport has
to offer to see from a front-row seat,'' Cayard said. ``She was just very
ecstatic. She was just as she would have been had she won the fifth set of a
very tight tennis match.''
</P>
<P>
	Prada's 17th man, as it has been for much of the trials, was 73-year-old Renzo
Guidi, a long-time friend of syndicate head Patrizio Bertelli and a hotel
operator near Prada's summer base in Punta Ala, Italy.
</P>
<P>
	Prada skipper Francesco de Angelis smiled as he deflected a question about
whether the Italians have a policy barring women from the role of ''17th man.''
</P>
<P>
	``We have a gentleman that stays with us. We are pleased with his company,'' de
Angelis said. ``We'd like to take girls when we go cruising, give them a better
time.''
</P>
<P>
	Prada trailed for almost all of the last four legs of the six-leg, 18 1/2-mile
race, with three legs going downwind and the other three upwind. Winds were a
relatively strong 16-20 knots.
</P>
<P>
	The boats crossed the starting line simultaneously, and Prada led by 20 and 17
seconds after each of the first two legs. Then it tripped on the kind of sail
that had been so sturdy for it throughout the campaign.
</P>
<P>
	As it lowered its spinnaker after the first downwind run, the sail dragged
through the water. Some of the cloth got caught on the rudder and keel. A crew
member leaned over the port side, held by a teammate, and tried to free the
material with a long pole.
</P>
<P>
	``This stuff's bad when it gets on the rudder, isn't it, Francesco?'' Cayard
joked. ``Our stuff just goes away, like toilet paper.''
</P>
<P>
	Prada has lost just two spinnakers in its 45 races so far, while AmericaOne has
ripped four in this series alone and a total of nine.
</P>
<P>
	``The boat was not giving the best performance and I think we survived until
the bottom mark,'' de Angelis said, ``but then we had to go upwind. It was
painful. The boat was going sideways.
</P>
<P>
	``Apart from that problem, we kept the race tight until the end.''
</P>
<P>
	Prada's spinnaker trouble helped AmericaOne gain 33 seconds on the third leg
and take a 17-second lead. That dwindled to seven seconds after the fourth leg
and remained the same after the fifth.
</P>
<P>
	On the final leg, with the wind blowing from behind, de Angelis tried several
maneuvers ``to force the boat ahead into making a mistake.'' But AmericaOne
never did.
</P>
<P>
	``So far I think the Italians have felt like they probably operate the boat a
little smoother than we do,'' Cayard said, ``but I think we might have turned
the cards on that today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 0258 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 02:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain, Gore Win in N.H. Primary  </HEADLINE>
   By WALTER R. MEARS AP Special Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Sen. John McCain opened the Southern front in his battle for the Republican
presidential nomination today, boosted by the momentum of a startling landslide
over George W. Bush in New Hampshire. He called it ``a powerful message'' of
change to come.
</P>
<P>
	   Vice President Al Gore edged Bill Bradley to win the Democratic primary, and
claimed to have dealt ``a devastating blow'' to his challenger. But Bradley
declared himself a smarter, tougher candidate for the national battle still
ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   That struggle began Tuesday night even before all of New Hampshire's votes
had been counted, as candidates deployed south and west for the primaries ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   ``On to South Carolina,'' said McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I like my chances in Delaware,'' Bush said. ``And South Carolina is Bush
country.''
</P>
<P>
	   Democrats get a five-week pause in primary voting, but not in campaigning.
Gore heads for crucial California later today; Bradley is due Thursday.
California is the biggest of the 14 state prizes at stake in the Super Bowl of
the primary campaign March 7. Both also were campaigning in New York, which
votes the same day, on their way west.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Republican side, Delaware is next on Feb. 8. Bush is campaigning
there, although briefly. McCain is not; his strategy hinges on South Carolina,
which he has said he must win. Steve Forbes, a fading third in New Hampshire, is
competing in Delaware, too.
</P>
<P>
	   Conservative Alan Keyes ran fourth in New Hampshire; Gary Bauer, who
finished last, went home to consider his next step, which may be withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
	   With 98 percent of precincts reporting, McCain got 114,047 votes or 49
percent; Bush had 71,492 votes or 31 percent; Forbes, 29,945 votes or 13
percent; Keyes, 15,078 votes or 6 percent; and Bauer, 1,653 votes or 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   An AP analysis showed McCain was winning 10 out of the total 17 delegates at
stake Tuesday. Bush was winning five and Forbes two.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Democratic side, Gore had 75,449 votes or 53 percent, and Bradley had
68,800 votes or 47 percent. Gore was winning 13 of the 22 delegates at stake
Tuesday and Bradley was winning nine, the AP analysis showed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have made a remarkable turnaround but there is still a tough fight
ahead,'' the former senator told supporters in Manchester, N.H. ''... We're
smarter and better prepared and we're ready to continue the fight.''
</P>
<P>
	   At his Manchester victory rally, Gore said, ``This Tennessean is in the end
zone and it feels great, and let me tell you, we have just begun to fight.'' He
promised to ``crisscross this continent again and again'' for the nomination and
as the nominee.
</P>
<P>
	   Upon his before-dawn arrival at New York's LaGuardia Airport, approximately
200 cheering fans -- including actor Billy Baldwin -- braved cold winds to greet
Gore, who hopped up and down, looking like a boxer in the ring, as worked down a
ropeline shaking hands.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We've just begun to fight!'' he shouted into a bullhorn before a limousine
whisked him to a Manhattan hotel for an abbreviated night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush called the outcome a bump in the road in a state known for placing them
in the path of front-runners. But it was a jolting one for a campaign that had
expected no worse than a narrow defeat. McCain's wipeout -- only presidents
running for renomination had gained margins that wide in prior primaries --
struck at Bush's greatest advantage, the image of inevitability, given his
towering lead from the beginning in national polls.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think electability is a big factor,'' said Gov. Paul Celluci of
neighboring Massachusetts, campaigning for Bush, the governor of Texas.
``Republicans think Bush can win in the fall.'' But to keep them thinking so,
he's got to win in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
	   And while Bush suffered in New Hampshire, he still has advantages over
McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   Money is one, with more than $31 million in Bush's campaign treasury to
begin the election year, four times the amount that McCain, the Arizona senator,
had.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush also leads in polls for South Carolina's primary, but New Hampshire
will have an impact there. ``The comparison shopping has just begun,'' said Rep.
Lindsay Graham, a McCain ally in South Carolina who came north to shiver with
his candidate on election eve.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's endorsements -- including from his famous parents -- didn't help in
New Hampshire, but could prove a bigger boost in later states. All but four
Republican governors favor his nomination, and their organizations will be at
his service.
</P>
<P>
	   Arizona and Michigan hold GOP primaries Feb. 22, followed by Virginia on
Feb. 29, and Bush should have the advantage in the latter two contests.
</P>
<P>
	   But the March 7 primaries are pivotal to Republicans, too. McCain spokesman
Dan Schnur said California will be ``the single most important decision-maker in
the primary campaign.''
</P>
<P>
	   That goes for the Democrats, too. Gore swamped Bradley nearly 2-to-1 in the
Iowa caucuses, but beat him only narrowly in New Hampshire. Bradley climbed to
the lead in the New Hampshire opinion polls, then slumped, then edged back up.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said he has the money and determination to wage the national contest
that begins March 7, when six of the 10 biggest states vote in a single day.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're no longer in a single state, we're in the national phase of the
campaign,'' he said. Gore agreed. ``It's a national primary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   While Bradley claimed satisfaction in New Hampshire, it prompted him to one
change -- he challenged Gore to weekly debates through March 7.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore had started the debate challenges four months ago, when he pronounced
himself the underdog and remodeled his campaign. Bradley rebuffed him, but they
eventually met in eight forums. The vice president then demanded two debates a
week, to supplant campaign TV ads. Bradley called it a gimmick and said he'd
keep advertising.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said he's willing to debate, but renewed his demand that the ads be
dropped. He and Bradley are booked to debate March 1 in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 0259 </TRAILER>
