<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 03:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Wednesday, Feb 2, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Gains Momentum With Win
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Sen. John McCain opened the Southern front in his
battle for the Republican presidential nomination today, boosted by the momentum
of a startling landslide over George W. Bush in New Hampshire. He called it "a
powerful message" of change to come. Vice President Al Gore edged Bill Bradley
to win the Democratic primary, and claimed to have dealt "a devastating blow" to
his challenger. But Bradley declared himself a smarter, tougher candidate for
the national battle still ahead.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
India Arms Smugglers Sentenced
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CALCUTTA, India (AP) -- A British arms dealer and five Latvians were
sentenced to life in prison today for smuggling arms intended for a revolution
against India. Peter Bleach, the arms trader, and the Latvian crewmen who
parachuted crates of weapons into eastern India five years ago, said they would
appeal their conviction to a higher court. "I am very disappointed, but not
surprised," Bleach said outside the courtroom. The men were convicted of aiding
insurgents who intended to wage war against India.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Expert Gives Microsoft Judge Advice
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An expert on applying laws in cyberspace is advising the
judge in the Microsoft trial that an appeals court victory for the software
company in a related case may not protect it from similar claims by the
government in its current lawsuit. The arguments put forth by Lawrence Lessig, a
law professor at Harvard University, are an important indicator of how U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson may decide the landmark antitrust case
brought by the Justice Department and 19 states.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Slim Hope for Alaska Air Survivors
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PORT HUENEME, Calif. (AP) -- Hopes are increasingly slim for finding any
survivors from the crash of Alaska Airlines Flight 261. Searchers have pulled
four bodies -- one man, two women and an infant-- from the calm sea, which is
300 to 750 feet deep in the area. Investigators said Tuesday that the pilots of
the jet struggled with a sudden control problem for at least six minutes before
the jetliner plummeted into the ocean with 88 people aboard. The last minutes of
the MD-83's flight Monday may have been witnessed by pilots aboard four other
aircraft, and the National Transportation Safety Board was seeking to interview
them.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Alaska Avalanche Victims Rescued
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Nine motorists were rescued by a police helicopter
Tuesday after spending the night trapped by a series of avalanches south of
Anchorage that killed a maintenance worker. The travelers, who had kept in touch
with rescuers by cellular phone as they waited along the Seward Highway, were
flown out in three groups and taken to a diner for breakfast. They were in good
condition. Ten other motorists trapped by another avalanche elsewhere along the
highway were rescued late Monday by a construction crew that used a front-end
loader to clear away snow.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report Says IRA Hasn't Disarmed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Northern Ireland's joint
Protestant-Catholic administration, launched in such high hopes two months ago,
is in danger of unraveling over the Irish Republican Army's continued
unwillingness to disarm. But Britain's minister for Northern Ireland, Peter
Mandelson, is hoping to resurrect the American-mediated pact that spurred the
Cabinet's formation -- and, crucially, expected that the IRA would scrap its
stockpiled weapons in response.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Haider Strikes Power Share Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Outspoken populist Joerg Haider on Tuesday
negotiated a deal to allow his far-right party to share power in Austria's
government -- despite warnings from the United States and the European Union
that such a move could lead to Austria's diplomatic isolation. Haider, leader of
the rightist Freedom Party, and Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel reached the
agreement late Tuesday on a proposed coalition government between Haider's party
and the conservative People's Party.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise Sharply
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) --On the Tokyo Stock Exchange Wednesday, the Nikkei closed up
155.53 points to finish at 19,578.91. On Wall Street Tuesday, the Dow Jones
industrial average rose 100.52 to close at 11,041.05.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Spurs Defeat Lakers 105-81
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- The San Antonio Spurs made the Lakers look lazy and
lousy in a dominating 105-81 victory that helped knock Los Angeles out of first
place in the overall NBA standings. Tim Duncan had 29 points and 18 rebounds,
Avery Johnson tied his season-high with 22 points, Terry Porter scored 15 and
David Robinson had 14 points and 12 rebounds for the Spurs, who sent the
once-mighty Lakers to their fourth loss in five games.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 0303 </TRAILER>
