<DOCNO> APW20000202.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 03:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> College Basketball Roundup  </HEADLINE>
    By TIM WHITMIRE AP Sports Writer No. 14 Kentucky 81, No. 6 Tennessee 68
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Once upon a time -- say, seven weeks ago -- Kentucky
was 4-4 and unranked for the first time in nine years.
</P>
<P>
	   Coach Tubby Smith doesn't remember it.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's too long ago for me," Smith said Tuesday night, after his
14th-ranked Wildcats once again took over first place in the Southeastern
Conference with an 81-68 victory over No. 6 Tennessee. "That's too long and too
far back. We're in conference play now, and we're much older."
</P>
<P>
	   Keith Bogans is one of the Wildcats (16-5, 6-1) who has grown up fast.
</P>
<P>
	   The freshman guard notched a career-high 25 points against the Volunteers
(18-3, 6-2), scoring 16 of Kentucky's first 23 points. Bogans made four
3-pointers and added two steals and two assists in the best game of his brief
college career.
</P>
<P>
	   "It felt good," Bogans said. "It felt like I couldn't miss, so I kept
shooting. That's what a guy dreams of, that every shot he shoots is falling."
</P>
<P>
	   In other games involving ranked teams Tuesday, No. 8 Michigan State beat
Michigan 82-62 and No. 21 Temple defeated Massachusetts 75-48.
</P>
<P>
	   In winning 11 of 12 going into the Tennessee game, the Wildcats had depended
largely on consistent scoring from center Jamaal Magloire, who had reached
double figures in 15 straight games.
</P>
<P>
	   Though Magloire's matchup with Tennessee center C.J. Black -- who labeled
him a "dirty player" in the preseason -- was the focus of pregame attention,
neither big man was much of a factor Tuesday. Each had to sit long stretches
because of foul trouble, and each finished with just two points.
</P>
<P>
	   With Bogans stepping up, Tayshaun Prince scoring 17 and grabbing six
rebounds and point guard Saul Smith contributing 12 points, six rebounds and
five assists, Kentucky didn't need Magloire.
</P>
<P>
	   "All our guys are growing, maturing, they're feeling more comfortable with
each other," Tubby Smith said. "(Bogans) was open because of the other players
doing other things for him to get his shots."
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a real confidence-booster," Bogans said. "We know we can't just
depend on Jamaal. We all have to play our role."
</P>
<P>
	   Vincent Yarbrough scored 17 points and Tony Harris added 16 for Tennessee,
while Isiah Victor had 12 points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
	   "I feel they had a little more emotion tonight," Yarbrough said. "We beat
this team twice last year. That is incentive, so they were ready."
</P>
<P>
	   "Our spirit is going to be fine," Tennessee coach Jerry Green said. "This is
a setback, but we understand Kentucky played a fine game tonight."
</P>
<P>
	   With the win, Kentucky took over first place in the SEC East and snapped
Tennessee's six-game conference road winning streak.
</P>
<P>
	   Kentucky has won 15 straight games at Rupp Arena, dating to last season's
47-46 loss to the Volunteers.
</P>
<P>
	   Bogans' big first half helped the Wildcats take a 36-31 halftime lead. In
the second half, Tennessee scrapped to stay in the game, getting within 58-54
with 9:46 remaining.
</P>
<P>
	   Five 3-pointers by Yarbrough and three by Harris helped keep Kentucky from
turning the game into a blowout.
</P>
<P>
	   Prince, however, scored 14 points in the second half, including two
3-pointers. One of those effectively locked the game away, 74-63, with 3:59
remaining.
</P>
<P>
	   "Tayshaun came through in the late game and led us through," Tubby Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The game ended with SEC statistics turned upside-down. The league's worst
3-point shooting team, Kentucky, went 10-of-21 from beyond the arc, while the
top long distance team, Tennessee, went just 10-of-27.
</P>
<P>
	   The Wildcats, who were outrebounded in both losses to Tennessee last season,
held a clear advantage on the boards, 40-33.
</P>
<P>
	   And they got an assist from a raucous Rupp Arena crowd, which chanted
"over-rated" as the clock ran down on the Kentucky win.
</P>
<P>
	   Morris Peterson had 32 points and 10 rebounds to lead the visiting Spartans
(16-5, 7-1 Big Ten) to their fourth straight win. Freshman LaVell Blanchard had
16 points for the Wolverines (12-6, 3-4), who lost their third straight. They
found out just before warmups that freshman and leading scorer Jamal Crawford
that the NCAA was investigating his living arrangements before enrolling at
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
	   Mark Karcher scored 17 points for the Owls (15-4, 8-1 Atlantic 10), who came
into the game No. 1 in the nation in defense at 53.5 points per game. Monty Mack
had 14 points for the Minutemen (11-9, 5-3), who were held to their lowest
output of the season and suffered their worst loss in the Mullins Center, which
opened in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
