<DOCNO> APW20000202.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 03:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Takes Votes From Bush  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURA MECKLER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Romping across New Hampshire, John McCain won among men
and women, young and old, rich, poor and middle-class. He even won among
registered Republicans, beating a front-runner, George W. Bush, who came into
the nation's first presidential primary with the backing of the GOP
establishment.
</P>
<P>
	   Independents played a key role in both the Democratic and Republican
primaries, making up about 30 percent of voters in each contest Tuesday. And
both McCain and Democrat Bill Bradley won decisively with voters who were not
tied to either party.
</P>
<P>
	   But McCain also won among registered Republicans, taking 43 percent of the
votes to 37 percent for Bush, according to exit polls of voters.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley, by contrast, clearly lost registered Democrats to the party's
favorite, Vice President Al Gore, who eked out victory in the nation's leadoff
primary.
</P>
<P>
	   On virtually every issue -- from moral values to Social Security to world
affairs -- Republican voters preferred McCain. Sixty-three percent of them said
he says what he really believes and not just what people want to hear. Just 31
percent said the same of Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   ``McCain is more of a straight talker,'' said Lisa Schechtman, 38, a
registered Republican from Manchester who voted for the Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's his moxie and no-nonsense attitude,'' agreed Mike Kania, 47, also a
Manchester Republican.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked what quality mattered most in a candidate, Republicans were most
likely to say standing up for beliefs, and those voters overwhelmingly picked
McCain. And while Bush is campaigning as a ``compassionate conservative,''
McCain took 56 percent of votes among those who said it was most important to
care ``about the average American.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain also did well on his defining issues. Most Republican voters said
campaign finance reform was a good idea, and they backed McCain. More than six
in 10 Republicans said McCain's military experience was important, and he took
most of those votes too.
</P>
<P>
	   By contrast, Bush found less support in his strongest points. Asked who was
more likely to beat a Democrat this fall, voters were divided between McCain and
Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   And while Bush has campaigned on his plan for a large tax cut, GOP voters
were split as to whether it was more important to cut taxes or strengthen Social
Security. McCain and Bush evenly shared those who favored tax cuts, but McCain
soared among those worried about the retirement program, beating Bush by some 40
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
	   There was more bad news for the Texas governor. One-third of Republican
voters said he does not have the knowledge needed to serve effectively as
president.
</P>
<P>
	   ``My impression was that he was a lot of window dressing and not much
depth,'' said McCain voter Charles Baron, 51.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Democratic side, Gore enjoyed the benefits of an incumbent, taking a
solid majority of the many voters who are feeling good about the economy's
future and their personal finances.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I want the economy to continue in the same direction it's been,'' said
Richard St. Hilaire, 70, of Manchester, who voted for Gore. ``Clinton and his
administration have done a lot of bad things, but Clinton's done a good job with
the economy.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore also got a big push from the unions he assiduously courted. While
Bradley and Gore split votes of non-union households, the vice president took
twice as many of the union votes -- a good sign for the vice president as the
race moves to states where unions are more prevalent.
</P>
<P>
	   More good news for Gore: Two in three Democratic voters say he has a better
chance of winning in the fall.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley was hurt by several factors. His campaign has been distracted with
news of his irregular heart beat, and one in five Democratic voters said they
were concerned that his health would interfere with his ability to serve as
president. Those voters preferred Gore overwhelmingly.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley made health care reform the centerpiece of his campaign, but
Democrats marginally preferred the Gore health plan.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, those who thought health care was the single most important issue
preferred Bradley to Gore. But an equal number of Democratic voters cared most
about education, and they preferred Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley did do well in the closing days of the New Hampshire campaign.
Fifty-five percent of those who made up their minds in the last week picked
Bradley, compared with 44 percent for Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   To some extent, Bradley and McCain were going after the same pool of
independent voters, but there's no evidence that McCain's strong showing hurt
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   The exit polls were conducted by Voter News Service, a consortium of The
Associated Press and the television networks. VNS surveyed 2,240 voters in the
GOP primary and 1,711 voters in the Democratic primary as they came out of
precincts Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The poll had an error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points for the
overall Democratic sample and 2.5 percentage points for Republicans, larger for
subgroups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 0319 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
