<DOCNO> APW20000202.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 9.61; Nasdaq Up17.89  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened narrowly mixed today as investors expected
the Federal Reserve to increase interest rates only modestly at its meeting
today.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 9.61 at 11,031.44.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were slightly higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 3.32 at 1,412.60, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 17.89 at
4,069.87.
</P>
<P>
	   Fears that interest rates are headed sharply higher have roiled the market
recently, sending most stocks tumbling last week. On Monday and Tuesday,
however, stocks rebounded as investors proved unwilling to get out of the market
that has rewarded them so richly in the past several years.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, trading was fairly volatile, suggesting investors remain wary of the
Fed's decision, expected to be announced at 2:15 p.m. EST. Most analysts expect
the Fed to raise rates by a quarter-percentage point, although some believe an
increase of a half-percentage point would be no surprise as the Fed works to
slow the pace of U.S. economic growth.
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed imposed three quarter-percentage point increases in 1999 in its bid
to keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, General Motors rose 1/4 to 85 1/2 after the company named president
and chief operating officer G. Richard Wagoner as chief executive officer,
preparing GM for the retirement of chairman and CEO John F. Smith Jr.
</P>
<P>
	   Discount broker Charles Schwab fell 7/16 to 35 3/16 after the company said
it would reduce fees for its most active online trading customers.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 133.04 million shares, well ahead of
Tuesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.21 to 505.96.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.8 percent. In afternoon
trading, Germany's Xetra DAX index was up 0.8 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
up 0.4 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 2.4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1026 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Presidential hopeful makes stops in Hartford  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A day after narrowly losing the New Hampshire
primary, Bill Bradley promised a full-court press against Al Gore in the race
for the Democratic nomination for president.
<P>
	   "The ball is bouncing on," Bradley said, bouncing a basketball on the podium
as he addressed a crowd of supporters today at Trinity College. "The warm-ups
are over. The national campaign has begun. We have five weeks to get our message
across the country."
</P>
<P>
	   Connecticut and the remaining New England states hold their primaries March
7, along with delegate-rich California, Ohio and New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite his loss Tuesday night, the former New Jersey senator said the close
result reinvigorated his campaign. Gore received just 6 percent more votes.
</P>
<P>
	   "Last night in New Hampshire, people sent a powerful message that they want
new politics," Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said his new politics include campaign finance reform, restoring the
public's trust in the government and fighting poverty.
</P>
<P>
	   He touched on the latter issue in an appearance earlier in the day at a
Hartford nursing home. Addressing about 50 union members who walked a picket
line outside Avery Heights, Bradley spoke out in support of better wages,
benefits and training.
</P>
<P>
	   "I believe your fight is just," he called out through a megaphone. "The
lowest-paid workers in America are the people who take care of our children and
the elderly."
</P>
<P>
	   Deborah Chernoff, a spokeswoman for New England Health Care Employees Union,
District 1199, said Bradley's appearance will give the union's cause more
attention.
</P>
<P>
	   "On the issues of workers rights both Gore and Bradley feel strongly. We may
be hearing from Gore on the issue," said Chernoff.
</P>
<P>
	   Shaka Tafari, a striking worker, said Bradley's appearance made him walk the
picket line on his birthday.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is welcome visit," he said. "We need to shake up the establishment."
</P>
<P>
	   Last month District 1199, the state's largest union of health care workers,
had agreed to end the strike at Avery Heights in response to an offer from
management the union had rejected two weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal allowed workers to return, but only to positions that had not been
filled by permanent replacements, and at the same wages and benefits they had
when they went on strike Nov. 17.
</P>
<P>
	   Avery Heights had hired more than 100 permanent replacements for the 180
nurse's aides, food service workers and housekeepers on the picket line.
</P>
<P>
	   Union officials said they would continue to picket until every striker
returned to work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-02-00 1031 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0104 </DOCNO>
