<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Special election for state Assembly seat is too close to call  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   CANANDAIGUA, N.Y. (AP) - A special election to fill the vacant 129th
District state Assembly seat was too close to call, with Democrat Samuel Casella
leading Republican Brian Kolb by just 14 votes.
<P>
	   With all precincts reporting Tuesday, Casella had 8,163 votes or 49.3
percent and Kolb had 8,149 or 49.2 percent. Right-to-Life candidate Edward
Tracey had the remaining 1.5 percent with 252 votes.
</P>
<P>
	   The race will be determined by absentee ballots, which could take up to a
week to count.
</P>
<P>
	   The seat was left vacant when Republican incumbent Craig Doran was elected
in November to a judgeship in Ontario County. The district, in which Republicans
hold a better than 3-2 enrollment advantage over Democrats, covers all of
Livingston and Yates counties and part of Ontario County.
</P>
<P>
	   Kolb, 47, is a business executive from Canandaigua. He has served as
president and chief operating officer of Refraction Technologies Corp. since
1994.
</P>
<P>
	   Casella, 46, is a Canandaigua farmer who unsuccessfully ran against Doran
for the Assembly seat in 1994.
</P>
<P>
	   In the two weeks before the election, the state Assembly's Democratic
majority began pumping money into the race, allowing Casella to launch
television advertising promoting himself. Kolb answered with ads warning voters
against "Casella and New York City liberals."
</P>
<P>
	   The winner of the race will face voters again in November, when the seat's
current term expires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
