<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opening statements in Diallo trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The prosecutor in the Amadou Diallo case opened the
trial this morning by telling jurors that the four cops accused of murdering the
unarmed African immigrant made "a conscious decision" to shoot without any
justification.
<P>
	   But defense attorneys painted a far different picture of police confronted
with a suspicious man who failed to stop on their command and appeared to be
holding a dark object. They thought it was a gun; it turned out to be his
wallet.
</P>
<P>
	   "In the 1990s, in Bronx County, in Albany County or anywhere else, a human
being should have been able to stand in the vestibule of his own home and not be
shot to death," said Assistant District Attorney Eric Warner. "Especially when
those doing the shooting are police officers sworn to protect innocent people."
</P>
<P>
	   He added: "We do not believe that these four defendants came on duty that
night with the intent to kill Amadou Diallo or anybody else. But when they got
out of the car in front of Amadou Diallo's home in the early morning of Feb. 4,
1999, they made the conscious decision to shoot him."
</P>
<P>
	   Warner said the officers "acted recklessly and with depraved indifference to
Amadou Diallo's life. ... For that, they are guilty of murder."
</P>
<P>
	   The officers, Sean Carroll, 36, Edward McMellon, 27, Kenneth Boss, 28, and
Richard Murphy, 27, are on trial in Albany, 150 miles away from the shooting
scene, and almost exactly a year after it took place.
</P>
<P>
	   Bennett Epstein, the lawyer for Carroll, told jurors that an hour before the
shooting, the officers stopped another man nearby. "They required him to
identify himself, which he did," Epstein said. "Turned out they had the wrong
person, they apologized to him, he walked away."
</P>
<P>
	   The same thing did not happen to Diallo because although "the officers
identified themselves with their shields out, as they are trained to, Mr. Diallo
doesn't listen to their orders to stop, which they are trained to give," Epstein
said. "More orders to stop and to show his hands - again Mr. Diallo does not
comply."
</P>
<P>
	   Epstein said Diallo - who had caught the officers' eye by repeatedly peering
out of his building, then going back inside - first turned away from them, then
turned back holding a dark object.
</P>
<P>
	   Epstein and the other defense attorneys said one officer shouted "Gun!" and
another fell back, leading all of them to believe Diallo was armed. The dark
object was later determined to be his wallet.
</P>
<P>
	   But the account differed sharply from the prosecutor's, who had insisted
that the officers did "not yell out any commands like stop, don't move."
</P>
<P>
	   Defense attorney Stephen Worth, who represents McMellon, told the jurors to
focus on the "total absence of any motive in this case other than self-defense.
... They felt themselves in immediate danger of being shot."
</P>
<P>
	   Worth also asserted that the officers - all white - were only on trial
"because there was a furor created by people who have their own agendas," an
allusion to activists who say the case exemplifies racism and police brutality.
Diallo was black.
</P>
<P>
	   Worth said the notion that the officers behaved in a racist fashion is
false. "Today as we begin this case, that lie begins to die," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   But he acknowledged: "Amadou Diallo did not deserve to die. ... There is no
doubt it is a tragedy."
</P>
<P>
	   Opening statements were completed in about an hour and the first witness, a
police investigator, was called before noon.
</P>
<P>
	   The officers - who plan to testify in their own defense before the jury of
six men and six women - have pleaded innocent to second-degree murder and
reckless endangerment charges in the slaying of Diallo. If convicted, they face
a maximum sentence of 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   The defendants were part of a plainclothes unit trying to catch violent
criminals in the Bronx when, shortly after midnight on Feb. 4, 1999, they
approached Diallo in the vestibule of his apartment building. They claim they
fired a total of 41 bullets from their rapid-fire pistols only after the
22-year-old street vendor made a sudden move as though to reach for a gun; 19
shots hit him.
</P>
<P>
	   The slaying of Diallo has been cited by critics of the New York Police
Department as a glaring example of police brutality toward minorities. It
triggered a wave of pretrial publicity and civil unrest, and prompted an appeals
court to rule the officers could not get a fair trial in New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   The case was moved to Albany, where State Supreme Court Justice Joseph
Teresi decided the trial could be televised. Testimony is expected to last about
a month.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury, which includes four black women, was picked in just two days. It
includes a middle school teacher, a Korean War veteran and the wife of a former
FBI agent. Three jurors said they have family or other ties to the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
	   Prospective jurors are not required to provide their ethnic backgrounds to
the court; their names weren't released.
</P>
<P>
	   According to 1990 census figures, the white population of the Bronx was
about 39 percent, compared with an 89 percent white population in Albany County.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-02-00 1120 </TRAILER>
