<HEADLINE> Dow Up 42.74; Nasdaq Up 37.74  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved moderately higher today as investors expected
the Federal Reserve to increase interest rates only modestly at its meeting
today.
</P>
<P>
	   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
42.74 at 11,083.79.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators also advanced. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
up 3.51 at 1,412.79, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 37.74 at 4,089.72.
</P>
<P>
	   Fears that interest rates are headed sharply higher have roiled the market
recently, sending most stocks tumbling last week. On Monday and Tuesday,
however, stocks rebounded as investors proved unwilling to get out of the market
that has rewarded them so richly the past several years.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, trading was fairly volatile, suggesting investors remain wary of the
Fed's decision, expected to be announced at 2:15 p.m. EST. Most analysts expect
the Fed to raise rates by a quarter-percentage point, although some believe an
increase of a half-percentage point would be no surprise as the Fed works to
slow the pace of U.S. economic growth.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors will also be closely attuned to the statement the Fed releases
with its decision, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
	   "For today, the important part of the announcement probably won't be the
amount of the rate hike, because the markets will be looking for hints about
future rate increases and the temperament of the Fed," said Paul Cherney, market
analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's.
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed imposed three quarter-percentage point increases in 1999 in its bid
to keep inflation under control, and has suggested it will continue raising
rates until it sees tangible evidence of a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, General Motors fell 2 5/8 to 82 5/8 after the company named president
and chief operating officer G. Richard Wagoner as chief executive officer,
preparing GM for the retirement of chairman and CEO John F. Smith Jr.
</P>
<P>
	   Discount broker Charles Schwab fell 1 3/8 to 34 1/4 after the company said
it would reduce fees for its most active online trading customers. Rival online
brokers also fell as investors anticipated a wave of price-cutting that could
slice into corporate profits. Ameritrade fell 3/16 to 15 13/16 and DLJ Direct
fell 1/4 to 10 3/4.
</P>
