<HEADLINE> UPDATES throughout with second injury, fire official comment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   MILFORD, Conn. (AP) - One person was killed and at least two others
injured when a crane collapsed at a power plant construction site this morning.
<P>
	   The crane was involved in building a natural gas-fired power plant on Bic
Drive. It collapsed around 10:30 a.m., Milford fire Capt. Robin Tummins said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bridgeport Hospital spokesman John Cappiello said the hospital had received
one dead victim.
</P>
<P>
	   Another injured worker was taken the Hospital of Saint Raphael in New Haven
where he was in fair condition, spokeswoman Bonnie Lukacs said. The man's
injuries did not appear life-threatening, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The crane operator, who was injured, was still trapped in the rubble of the
collapsed building and the crane, Tummins said.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's pretty bad," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   It was not clear whether the crane or the building collapsed first, he said.
The structure was about 45 feet high at the point of the collapse, Tummins said.
</P>
<P>
	   Other cranes at the job site were being positioned to help remove the
wreckage. Some workers were ordered home for the day while others were kept at
the site in the hope their expertise could assist rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
	   Identifies of the dead and injured were not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
	   State records show Houston-based El Paso Energy Co. and Power Development
Corp. of Boston started work on the plant last year. An El Paso official said
the company was unaware of the accident and had no immediate comment. No listing
could be located for Power Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   Police, firefighters and building inspectors were called to the scene.
</P>
<P>
	   Milford is on the Connecticut shoreline, about 10 miles west of New Haven
and some 60 miles northeast of New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
