<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amtrak rejects builder's call for delay of high-speed train  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - A request by the builder of the 150-mile-an-hour
Acela Express trains on the Northeast Corridor to delay the trains' introduction
has been denied by Amtrak, which instead is proposing ways to speed up tests on
the new service.
<P>
	   The consortium building the trains - Canada's Bombardier Transportation and
France's Alstom Ltd. - had said service between Boston and Washington would
begin by Christmas, but pushed back the first run until spring after wheel-wear
problems were found in tests in August at the Colorado test site.
</P>
<P>
	   The consortium last week asked to delay the first train until mid-July, the
company has rejected that idea, Richard R. Sarles, Amtrak's vice president for
high-speed rail, said Tuesday. The Amtrak board "took great exception" to the
request and "told them to come back with a better schedule," Sarles said.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead, Amtrak is now proposing that more people be added to allow more
than one test at a time, as is now being done. The company has also agreed to
add a second window - between morning and evening rush hours - for test runs on
the busy Northeast Corridor, which Amtrak administers from Philadelphia. The
test train now runs only late at night, Sarles said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Launching the new service this spring ... and having all 20 trains in
service by year's end, is still very much our goal," Sarles said. He said the
consortium had promised a response to Amtrak's suggestions by the end of the
month.
</P>
<P>
	   Representatives of the consortium could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Three trains have been delivered for testing and a fourth is due this month,
with others in various stages of construction. The first train is undergoing a
20,000-mile endurance run in Colorado, the second is making nightly test runs
out of Philadelphia, and the third is undergoing systems testing at a shop near
Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   Sarles said the wheel-wear problem has been fixed by reshaping the wheels to
conform to the shape of U.S. track. Initially, the trains used wheels designed
for French high-speed trains.
</P>
<P>
	   About 10 days ago, technicians discovered a new problem - sideways movement,
or yaw, of the wheels at very high speeds.
</P>
<P>
	   Sarles said engineers often find such problems during tests and fix them
with minor design changes. So far, he said, the tests have uncovered no
fundamental design problems or safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
	   The new trains will replace Amtrak's aging premium-class Metroliners between
Boston and Washington, through New York and Philadelphia. On Monday, two new
daily trains called Acela Regionals began running between Boston and Washington
with features developed for the high-speed Acela Express trains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-02-00 1318 </TRAILER>
