<DOCNO> APW20000202.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Status Urged for China  </HEADLINE>
   By TERENCE HUNT AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration today urged Congress to give
up its politically charged annual review of trade benefits for China and instead
grant Beijing normal, permanent trade status.
</P>
<P>
	   National Security Adviser Sandy Berger said that giving China permanent
trade relations would ``get us out of the cycle we are now in, where the future
of Chinese trade comes up every single year for a divisive and not very
effective vote.''
</P>
<P>
	   After the collapse of global trade talks in Seattle and a determined
campaign by organized labor and environmental groups, President Clinton faces a
tough sell in persuading Congress to grant permanent trade benefits to China.
The election year heightens political pressures, as well, prompting Clinton and
his allies to push for a vote as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
	   Permanent trade benefits are part of the trade-opening agreement negotiated
by China and the United States as the price for China's entry into the
135-nation World Trade Organization, which sets the rules for global commerce.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The annual China trade vote has not been an effective instrument,'' Berger
said. ``It simply has affirmed our trading relationship with China for 20 years
in a row now.'' Each year, the vote has been caught up in emotional arguments
about China's human rights abuses and its huge trade surpluses with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
	   Berger was to present the administration's case in a speech to the Woodrow
Wilson Center, a foreign policy group. An advance text of his remarks was
released by the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the trade-opening agreement will dramatically reduce Chinese tariffs
on everything from agricultural and industrial products to computers and
semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Denying China (permanent trade status) would deprive American companies
and workers of the full benefits of China's concessions -- the favorable market
access and dispute settlement that our European, Japanese and other competitors
will have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Berger said that bringing China into the WTO ``will obligate China to deepen
its market reforms and open its economy to the world. It will increase the pace
of change in China.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said China's leaders understand that economic change is ``both essential
and risky.'' It is risky because opening China's protected markets to global
competition could cause more short-term unemployment and social unrest, Berger
said. But he said the leaders also understand that China cannot advance without
world-class industries and products that can compete in the global economy.
</P>
<P>
	   Further, Berger said the WTO agreement ``will help bring the information
revolution to cities and towns across China'' -- making people more aware of
alternative ways of life and prompting them to seek a stronger voice in shaping
their destiny.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Of course, just last week, Beijing announced that it was cracking down on
the Internet,'' Berger said. ``It's outrageous. But it's also futile. In this
information age, cracking down on the Internet is like King Canute trying to
still the waters.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Indeed, the fact that the Chinese government is pushing back against the
increasing flow of information to the Chinese people only proves that the
changes China is undergoing are real and threatening to the status quo,'' Berger
said. ``This kind of repression is not an argument for slowing down the effort
to bring China into the world. It's an argument for accelerating it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1324 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Le Cirque 2000 Is Tres Chic  </HEADLINE>
    By SAMANTHA CRITCHELL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Le Cirque 2000 is arguably Manhattan's favorite dining room
of the rich and famous.
</P>
<P>
	   "We were sold out from the first day with famous names," said Sirio
Maccioni, an Italian restaurateur who opened the celebrated French restaurant Le
Cirque in 1974 in the Mayfair Hotel on the Upper East Side. "We weren't really
prepared, but the rest is history. We were the first 'place to be seen' that
also had good food."
</P>
<P>
	   With an eye toward the 21st century, he shut the restaurant's doors in 1996
and moved to the New York Palace Hotel in midtown Manhattan. The restaurant
reopened as Le Cirque 2000 in the landmark Villard Houses in the spring of 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is New York, we have to change with the times," Maccioni explained.
</P>
<P>
	   But, he added, "I know what good food is, and I know how to personalize it."
</P>
<P>
	   To emphasize its lighthearted circus theme, Le Cirque 2000 features a monkey
statue in the main entrance. The interior is filled with brightly colored neon
light sculptures.
</P>
<P>
	   Henry Kissinger, Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, Bill Cosby, Sophia Loren and
Barbara Walters are among the 100 celebrities who are depicted in a portrait
that hangs in the restaurant's entrance.
</P>
<P>
	   "Le Cirque used to be filled with 'the ladies who lunch.' But they don't
like to be called that anymore. So now we have 'the women who talk charity over
lunch,"' Maccioni said.
</P>
<P>
	   Catering to the ladies is a smart business decision, he said. "If a
beautiful lady wants to go to a restaurant and she likes it, she'll bring her
husband, her friends, her lovers."
</P>
<P>
	   The 68-year-old Maccioni has been described in "America's Elite 1000: The
Ultimate List" (Cadogan Publications, $90) as "a global status symbol on a par
with Belgian chocolate and Italian motorcars."
</P>
<P>
	   "I consider myself a working restaurateur, but I'm proud to be called
elite," Maccioni responded. "I encourage all my people to be elite; be an elite
dishwasher. Being elite means being the best."
</P>
<P>
	   Manhattan's most celebrated and powerful residents dine on lobster salad,
consomme with foie gras, ravioli and roasted rack of lamb. Lunch is served
Monday through Saturday; dinner is served seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
	   A prix fixe lunch is available for $42. On the dinner menu, prices range
from a lobster risotto appetizer for $25 to striped bass served with caviar and
lemon sauce for $36. Black Angus steak, spit-roasted pigeon and Dover sole are
among the items available from the grill, with prices ranging from $28 to $39.
</P>
<P>
	   The restaurant has received a four-star rating from The New York Times and
has been recognized by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani as being one of the city's most
glamorous and hospitable restaurants.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a restaurant that must be seen and experienced to be believed,"
said Fodor's "City Guide New York," adding: "Order the creme brulee for dessert
and you'll leave happy."
</P>
<P>
	   Maccioni, born and raised in Italy, was forced to go to work after his
father was killed during World War II. He worked in hotels and restaurants in
France, Switzerland and Germany before moving to the United States in 1956.
</P>
<P>
	   "I didn't do this out of inspiration or desperation. I realized very early
that I couldn't afford to be young," he said. "I did completely give my life to
this business. Is it worth it? Maybe not. But I had no choice, and I've never
felt exploited."
</P>
<P>
	   He attended Hunter College during the day. At night, he worked at The
Colony, one of New York's trendiest restaurants, where Frank Sinatra, the Duke
and Duchess of Windsor, and Aristotle Onassis frequently dined. After a few
years, he moved to a club at the Pierre Hotel before opening Le Cirque.
</P>
<P>
	   His sons now run Osteria del Circo on 55th Street and Le Cirque and Circo in
the Bellagio Hotel in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
	   "My three sons were born in New York. I've worked hard to give them a good
life, but they're all selling soup for me," Maccioni said. "I wanted them to be
a lawyer, a doctor and an architect."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1338 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0126 </DOCNO>
