<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Chased and Caught Success  </HEADLINE>
    By BETH HARRIS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Edwin McCain always wanted to be a rock 'n'
roll guy. No one is more surprised than the singer-songwriter to find himself a
balladeer.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm going to replace Adam Sandler as the wedding singer," McCain joked.
"I've got a career after my 15 minutes (of fame) is over just going around
singing 'I'll Be' and 'Could Not Ask for More."'
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has already had two wedding gigs. He sang at the weddings of friends
Mark Bryan of Hootie and the Blowfish and Rob Thomas of Matchbox 20.
</P>
<P>
	   "What an honor to be invited to be a part of something like a wedding.
That's a once-in-a-lifetime, supposedly, thing that people do," he said. "It's a
moment of great fellowship with friends and family."
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, 30, took the matrimonial plunge himself last year with a former
high-school classmate.
</P>
<P>
	   He tours constantly to support "Messenger," his follow-up album to
"Misguided Roses," which produced the Top 10 ballad "I'll Be." The song wasn't a
hit right away. "I'll Be" finally broke through a year after "Misguided Roses"
was released in 1997. For McCain, that followed years of being a regional hit in
the Deep South with his self-released album "Solitude."
</P>
<P>
	   McCain and his band's stint as an opening act for Hootie and the Blowfish
brought them to the attention of Atlantic Records, which released "Honor Among
Thieves" in 1995. The album yielded a Top 40 hit. But it would be another three
years and more than 600 road dates before McCain scored with "I'll Be."
</P>
<P>
	   Before national success arrived, McCain changed his personality to suit
whatever situation he was in.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was so busy trying to present this homogeneous version of myself. I'm so
busy making sure that everybody's happy with me that I wasn't really sure who I
was anyway," he said. "So now, it's like here it is. Here's all of it, and if
you don't like it, kiss off."
</P>
<P>
	   McCain writes most of his own material, so he was surprised when hit-maker
Diane Warren called and offered him "I Could Not Ask for More."
</P>
<P>
	   Then he heard the demo.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was really smarmy, very schmaltzy," he said, wrinkling his lightly
tanned nose. "Apologies all around because I can't say enough good things about
Diane, but for my gig, we had to do something different with it."
</P>
<P>
	   Out went a verse McCain didn't think he could sing honestly, the kind of
words "you've heard a million times in every love song everywhere," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Then McCain and his band upped the tempo, making it into an acoustic track
that builds into the Los Angeles Symphony Orchestra. Warren wasn't thrilled
about the changes to her song, which McCain originally did for the "Message in a
Bottle" movie soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
	   "Then after it grew on her she was like, 'Yeah, that's good,"' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's "I Could Not Ask for More" (Lava) is currently in the top 10 of
Billboard's listing of contemporary adult singles.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite his success with ballads, McCain plays plenty of rock 'n' roll. One
of the liveliest songs on "Messenger" is "Do Your Thing," inspired by a young
boy who asked McCain how he got to do what he does.
</P>
<P>
	   "They think you're going to hand them that instructional booklet on how to
be successful in the musical industry," he said. "I just say 'find the thing you
love to do and do it all the time and never take no for an answer. Eventually
you'll be happy or not, but at least you did it.'
</P>
<P>
	   "The problem is everybody is too busy with finish lines. It's all about the
journey, being allowed to chase after whatever it is that you love to do. Even
if it's not successful, there's absolute validation in the trying. You already
win when you do that."
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's decade of chasing success started out on the bar circuit in his
hometown of Greenville, S.C. When he realized he could earn $150 for three hours
of performing, he dropped out of college and decided that he would take his
guitar and "go have adventures everywhere." His black guitar case is evidence of
those trips. It's plastered with stickers from radio stations and bars
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's travels prompt many of his songs. A morning drive to the airport
that took him past a strip bar and its packed parking lot led to "Beautiful
Life," a sassy commentary on rock stars and regular people.
</P>
<P>
	   "People want to go see naked girls and drink beer at nine o'clock in the
morning. I've wanted to," he said. "That's a part of our world. I love that
about us."
</P>
<P>
	   Such frankness is part of his determination to shake things up.
</P>
<P>
	   "People like to have their emotional pendulum kind of sit there, it swings
happy and it swings sad, but it's not too happy or too sad," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Then there's people like me who like to watch it whip around the pole a few
times because it's obnoxious and because it's fun."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1343 </TRAILER>
