<HEADLINE> Celebrity Spotlight &AMP; Birthdays  </HEADLINE>
    By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   In the spotlight:
</P>
<P>
	   Jack Lemmon was named best actor in a TV movie or miniseries for Showtime's
"Inherit the Wind" at this year's Golden Globe Awards. Lemmon was nominated in
the same category for his role in "Oprah Winfrey Presents: Tuesdays With
Morrie." A few years ago, Ving Rhames spontaneously gave his Golden Globe to
Lemmon, who had presented him with it. But Lemmon won't be giving his Golden
Globe to Rhames. "In his spirit, I gave it to me," said Lemmon, who was born on
Feb. 8, 1925. Lemmon has been nominated for a Screen Actors Guild award for his
performance in "Tuesdays With Morrie." The winners will be announced at an
awards show on March 12, broadcast on the TNT cable channel.
</P>
<P>
	   Chris Rock didn't fret over his role in the controversial biblical satire
"Dogma," directed by Kevin Smith. "Everything should be satirized and skewered.
Nothing is above jokes," the comedian says. "I don't want to go to heaven if it
ain't funny." Rock, who was born on Feb. 7, 1966, says he was kicked out of
Bible school as a child. "I was always joking and laughing. They finally just
said, 'Get out of here.' I went home crying, 'They kicked me out for laughing."'
</P>
<P>
	   Christina Ricci, who was born on Feb. 12, 1980, has grown up in films. Her
career began with "Mermaids," "Casper," "That Darn Cat" and two "Addams Family"
movies. "It was really stressful," she recalls. "They want to make films where
you're gangly and really skinny and that whole romantic notion of gangly
teen-age girls -- the Nabokov thing -- and I was never that." Her independent
films include "Ice Storm," "Buffalo '66" and "The Opposite of Sex." Now she's
ready to tackle more mainstream fare. She co-stars with Johnny Depp in "Sleepy
Hollow," Tim Burton's retelling of Washington Irving's classic tale. In the
upcoming "The Man Who Cried," she portrays a young woman who flees Germany and
falls for a Gypsy. This World War II drama also stars Depp and Cate Blanchett.
</P>
<P>
	   Celebrity birthdays Feb. 6-12:
</P>
<P>
	   Feb. 6: Actor Rip Torn is 69. Actor Mike Farrell ("Providence") is 61.
Singer Natalie Cole is 50. Actor-director Robert Townsend ("The Parent 'Hood")
is 43. Actress Kathy Najimy ("Veronica's Closet") is 43. Actress Megan Gallagher
is 40. Singer Axl Rose of Guns N' Roses is 38.
</P>
<P>
	   Feb. 7: Actor Miguel Ferrer ("Lateline") is 46. Actor James Spader is 40.
Country singer Garth Brooks is 38. Musician David Bryan of Bon Jovi is 38.
Actor-comedian Chris Rock is 34. Actor Jason Gedrick is 33. Actor Ashton Kutcher
is 22. Actress Tina Majorino is 15.
</P>
<P>
	   Feb 8: Actor Jack Lemmon is 75. Actor Nick Nolte is 59. Comedian Robert
Klein is 58. Actress Mary Steenburgen is 47. Singer Vince Neil of Motley Crue is
39. Actor Gary Coleman is 32. Actress Mary McCormack is 31. Actor Seth Green
("Buffy the Vampire Slayer") is 26.
</P>
<P>
	   Feb. 9: Singer-songwriter Carole King is 58. Actor Joe Pesci is 57. Actress
Mia Farrow is 55. Actress Judith Light is 51. Country singer Travis Tritt is 37.
Actress Julie Warner ("Family Law") is 35. Actor David Gallagher ("7th Heaven")
is 15.
</P>
<P>
	   Feb. 10: Actor Robert Wagner is 70. Singer Roberta Flack is 61. Actress
Laura Dern is 33.
</P>
<P>
	   Feb. 11: Actor Leslie Nielsen is 74. Actor Burt Reynolds is 64. Actress
Carey Lowell is 39. Singer Sheryl Crow is 38. Actress Jennifer Aniston
("Friends") is 31. Singer D'Angelo is 26. Singer-actress Brandy ("Moesha") is
21. Actor Matthew Lawrence is 20.
</P>
<P>
	   Feb 12: Musician Ray Manzarek of the Doors is 65. Actor Joe Don Baker is 64.
Actor Michael Ironside is 50. Actor Arsenio Hall ("Martial Law") is 45. Singer
Chynna Phillips is 32. Actress Christina Ricci is 20.
</P>
