<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Wynonna Judd  </HEADLINE>
    By JIM PATTERSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Wynonna Judd is reaching into the future with a new
solo album "New Day Dawning" at the same time she's reviving her past with a
reunion tour of The Judds.
</P>
<P>
	   Will reprising 1980s hits like "Why Not Me?" with her mother Naomi Judd take
away attention from her new music?
</P>
<P>
	   "I think two or three years ago, I would have worried about that," Judd
said. "Because I was working so diligently at being independent from my family.
We all feel the need to move out of the house and get our own apartment and
forge ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   "I've already done that."
</P>
<P>
	   The Judds rose to stardom in 1984 with their first chart-topping hit "Mama
He's Crazy." They went on to score 14 more No. 1 hits, sell more than 20 million
albums and win six Grammys.
</P>
<P>
	   Naomi Judd retired in 1991 after contracting hepatitis C. Wynonna Judd went
on to solo success with a slick R&AMP;B-leaning sound that is worlds away from The
Judds' homespun country style.
</P>
<P>
	   "Now, I can just be my own bad self because I've pushed two babies through
my body. I've married and divorced. So I'm touring with my mother again. Go
figure. I feel like I can do anything," Judd said.
</P>
<P>
	   The reunion tour features solo and duo hits. Major cities on the three-month
tour, which is scheduled to end in April, include Denver, Chicago, Las Vegas,
Atlanta, Detroit, Dallas and Houston.
</P>
<P>
	   The 35-year-old singer is confident enough to package "New Day Dawning" with
a separate CD that has four new recordings by The Judds. It's their first new
music since their 1990 "Love Can Build a Bridge" album.
</P>
<P>
	   1. Do you get along with your mom and sister (actress Ashley Judd) better
now than, say, 10 years ago?
</P>
<P>
	   Judd: Oh, God yes. God yes. There's been a lot of Christian counseling.
There are a lot of rules, like no interrupting and no hollering. We've worked 10
years at being a dysfunctional family. Mom says we put the fun in dysfunctional.
... We save our competitiveness for when we're playing a game. And then I will
do anything to smash both of them. We play Gestures and Taboo. Anything where we
can scream and holler is our game.
</P>
<P>
	   2. How do you feel about being on the road with your mom after a decade on
your own?
</P>
<P>
	   Judd: It feels so awesome. ... If this reunion were all about show biz and
fluff, it would really probably scare the crap out of me, quite frankly. But
spiritually, I feel really that it's right. It's a celebration.
</P>
<P>
	   3. Your mom has said she's clear of hepatitis. Are The Judds coming back for
good?
</P>
<P>
	   Judd: Unless the heavens part and I actually see my angel, my gut instinct
is 'Don't push it.' We have to be realistic. There's mom's health, and I have my
own plans, as my own person.
</P>
<P>
	   4. On "New Day Dawning," you do songs by Joni Mitchell, Macy Gray and The
Fabulous Thunderbirds. That's pretty diverse.
</P>
<P>
	   Judd: I continue to thrive on being a musical troublemaker. I want to stir
it up and try things that feel right to my gut. People don't really understand
that. They think that (country music) is all formula and it's all about coming
up with some regular deal every year. Not me. I go with my gut instinct. I
continue to go down that unbeaten path. It's a very lonely journey sometimes. I
feel like I'm alone in the world. But (she starts singing) 'I got to be me.' My
mother raised two strong, very high-spirited women with a lot of independent
thinking. It's her fault.
</P>
<P>
	   5. Sales for country music are down. Why?
</P>
<P>
	   Judd: I see an awful lot of gimmicks going on. I see an awful lot of showy,
bright and shiny tricks, and I think we're getting so far into the entertainment
part of things that we're forgetting about the heart. I want it to get back to
the poetry of the everyday man. That's why I got into music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
