<DOCNO> APW20000202.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Oneidas offered $500 million to settle land claim  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - A reported $500 million settlement offer to the
Oneida Indians leaves out their Canadian cousins, says a member of the Canadian
tribe upset at being abandoned in the land claim talks.
<P>
	   "Legally, it doesn't seem right and morally, it doesn't seem right," said
Bob Antone, a member of the Thames Band of Oneidas from Ontario, Canada.
</P>
<P>
	   Incited by the turn of events, Antone decided to break a federal judge's
confidentiality order and provided a seven-page summary to The Post-Standard of
Syracuse detailing the three-day marathon negotiating session held last week in
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   The session was billed as a the last chance for a settlement before the case
would be turned back over to U.S. District Judge Neal McCurn to be decided in
court.
</P>
<P>
	   Antone said court-appointed mediator Ronald Riccio opened the talks with a
$500 million proposal that provided $225 million for the 1,000-member Oneida
Indian Nation of New York, no less than $250 million for the 14,000 members of
the Oneida Nation of Wisconsin and $25 million for the Thames tribe, which has
5,000 members.
</P>
<P>
	   The Oneidas, with the support of the U.S. Justice Department, are seeking
compensation for the loss of 250,000 acres of ancestral land in Oneida and
Madison counties. The U.S. Supreme Court found in 1985 that the land was seized
in questionable transactions with the state and private individuals and ruled
the Oneidas are entitled to compensation.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of the settlement, Madison and Oneida counties asked the Oneidas to
put $25 million in a trust fund to offset the county property taxes sovereign
Indian nations do not pay, Antone said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Oneida Indian Nation of New York would stop its land purchases at 45,000
acres and would consider quitting at 35,000 acres if the state would allow slot
machines at the nation's Turning Stone casino. The New York Oneidas currently
own about 10,000 acres, he told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
	   The Wisconsin Oneidas would receive as much as 1,500 acres of state-owned
land somewhere in St. Lawrence County. But they agreed to not use the land for
business development.
</P>
<P>
	   Antone said the Thames Oneidas have asked for 10,000 acres in Madison
County. That request was ignored. Also, on the first day of the session the
Canadian Oneidas were shocked and outraged when the Wisconsin tribe said it was
prepared to settle without the them.
</P>
<P>
	   Justice Department negotiators agreed, saying the United States government
has no responsibility to the Oneidas who live in Canada.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've been cut out," Antone said. "We've been told by the federal
government not to say anything. We don't have a voice."
</P>
<P>
	   The federal and state governments would each contribute half of the $500
million, Antone told the newspaper. Federal negotiators would ask Congress to
extinguish aboriginal title of all three Oneida groups, which would make the
settlement final and preclude the Oneidas from suing again, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   New York state officials said there would not be a settlement unless the New
York Oneidas agreed to collect and remit sales taxes on all sales to
non-Indians, Antone said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Oneidas declined comment on the reported offer, citing McCurn's
confidentiality order. Others involved in the negotiations also held their
silence.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is no settlement package at this time," said Oneida County Executive
Ralph Eannace. "Once we have a settlement proposal we will take it to the
residents of Oneida and Madison counties before consideration and a vote by the
county legislative bodies."
</P>
<P>
	   Riccio is scheduled to hold a public meeting Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
