<HEADLINE> URGENT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   MILFORD, Conn. (AP) - Two people were killed and at least two others
injured when a crane collapsed at a power plant construction site this morning.
<P>
	   The crane was used in building a natural gas-fired power plant on Bic Drive.
It collapsed around 10:30 a.m., Milford fire Capt. Robin Tummins said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bridgeport Hospital spokesman John Cappiello said the hospital had received
one dead victim. Tummins said a second dead person was located amid the
wreckage.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's pretty bad," Tummins said.
</P>
<P>
	   The crane operator was trapped in the rubble of the collapsed crane and the
steel frame of the building. He was injured but was able to communicate with
rescue workers, Tummins said.
</P>
<P>
	   A fourth worker was taken the Hospital of Saint Raphael in New Haven where
he was in fair condition, spokeswoman Bonnie Lukacs said. The man's injuries did
not appear life-threatening, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Identities of the dead and injured were not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
	   It was not clear whether the crane or the building collapsed first, Tummins
said. The structure was about 45 feet high at the point of the collapse, he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Other cranes at the job site were being positioned to help remove the
wreckage. Some workers were ordered home for the day while others were kept at
the site to assist rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
	   State records show Houston-based El Paso Energy Co. and Power Development
Corp. of Boston started work on the plant last year. An El Paso official said
the company was unaware of the accident and had no immediate comment. No listing
could be located for Power Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   Overland Park, Kan.-based Black &AMP; Veatch, a consulting engineering firm, was
overseeing the construction. A message was left seeking comment from company
officials.
</P>
<P>
	   Milford is on the Connecticut shoreline, about 10 miles west of New Haven
and some 60 miles northeast of New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
