<HEADLINE> Harrison Loses Property Ruling  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    HONOLULU (AP) -- George Harrison's neighbors are now free to cut through his
Maui estate to get to the ocean.
</P>
<P>
	   The Hawaii Supreme Court upheld a 1993 lower-court ruling that said owners
of two neighboring properties could use the easement on Harrison's 60-acre
oceanfront parcel on the remote eastern end of the island.
</P>
<P>
	   Harrison said in 1993 he would sell the property if the ruling went against
him.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have to protect my privacy, and there is my need to have security," he
said at the time.
</P>
<P>
	   In December, a homeless woman was found inside the estate doing her laundry
and eating pizza. Her Dec. 23 arrest came a week before Harrison was stabbed in
the chest by an intruder in his mansion near London.
</P>
</TEXT>
