<HEADLINE> Stocks Move Higher; Dow Up 26.76  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved moderately higher today as investors expected
the Federal Reserve to increase interest rates only modestly at its meeting
today.
</P>
<P>
	   Shortly before the Fed's decision was expected to be announced at 2:15 p.m.
EST, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 26.76 at 11,067.81.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators also advanced. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
up 4.86 at 1,414.14, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 34.78 at 4,086.76.
</P>
<P>
	   Fears that interest rates are headed sharply higher have roiled the market
recently, sending most stocks tumbling last week. On Monday and Tuesday,
however, stocks rebounded as investors proved unwilling to get out of the market
that has rewarded them so richly the past several years.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, trading was fairly volatile, suggesting investors remained wary of
the Fed's decision. Most analysts expected the Fed to raise rates by a
quarter-percentage point, although some believed an increase of a
half-percentage point would be no surprise as the Fed works to slow the pace of
U.S. economic growth.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors would also be closely attuned to the statement the Fed releases
with its decision, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
	   "For today, the important part of the announcement probably won't be the
amount of the rate hike, because the markets will be looking for hints about
future rate increases and the temperament of the Fed," said Paul Cherney, market
analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's.
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed imposed three quarter-percentage point increases in 1999 in its bid
to keep inflation under control, and has suggested it will continue raising
rates until it sees tangible evidence of a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, IBM led the Dow's advance, rising 4 3/16 to 114 3/16.
</P>
<P>
	   General Motors fell 3 7/16 to 81 13/16 after the company named president and
chief operating officer G. Richard Wagoner as chief executive officer, preparing
GM for the retirement of chairman and CEO John F. Smith Jr.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume was running well ahead of Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 5.32 to 509.07.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
