<DOCNO> APW20000202.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRS Struggles With Spouse Claims  </HEADLINE>
   By CURT ANDERSON AP Tax Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Internal Revenue Service is struggling with a backlog
of some 46,000 claims under a new ``innocent spouse'' law intended to protect
divorced or separated partners from getting unfairly entangled in tax debts.
</P>
<P>
	   IRS Commissioner Charles Rossotti told the Senate Finance Committee on
Wednesday that the agency was surprised by the sheer number of claims following
congressional passage of the law in 1998 and also wasn't fully prepared for the
complexity of determining which ones are legitimate.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are really quite determined to get the claims right,'' Rossotti said.
``Sometimes, that has resulted in taking more time to get the result out to the
taxpayer.''
</P>
<P>
	   In general, the innocent spouse law enables one partner to obtain relief
from tax liabilities stemming from a jointly filed tax return -- if the
requesting spouse can prove no knowledge of the offending items on that return.
The new law relaxed and broadened many requirements, among other updated
taxpayer rights.
</P>
<P>
	   In the four months before the 1998 IRS reform law took effect, Rossotti said
the agency had received about 3,000 innocent spouse claims. Since then, the
number of claims has ballooned to 63,906, with about 2,800 pouring in each month
-- and the backlog as of Dec. 31 was 46,665.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is not satisfactory,'' said Finance Committee Chairman William Roth,
R-Del. ``We do have to find some answers.''
</P>
<P>
	   Rossotti said the IRS intends for ``progress to pick up'' during 2000 and
projected the backlog to drop to about 30,000 claims by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   Several senators were critical of reports that IRS enforcement actions --
liens, levies and property seizures -- have plummeted since the 1998 reform law
passed. Rossotti released new estimates predicting that the drop will end in
2000 as the agency improves how it administers the law and Congress provides
adequate money for staff and computer improvements.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I do think we have gotten past the first stage,'' Rossotti said. ``We want
to respect taxpayer rights. We also have to collect the taxes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1420 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Commerce Official Resigns  </HEADLINE>
   By MARTIN CRUTSINGER AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Commerce Under Secretary David Aaron, the top trade
official at the agency, announced Wednesday that he was leaving his post next
month to take a job with a Minnesota-based law firm.
</P>
<P>
	   Aaron, who had been the administration's chief troubleshooter on a number of
contentious trade issues with the European Union, said he would be joining the
Washington office of Dorsey &AMP; Whitney, a law firm that has its main offices in
Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
	   Before he leaves office, Aaron said he hoped to have resolved a dispute with
the EU involving data privacy. But he indicated that a second dispute with the
EU involving the proper approach to limiting airplane noise would have to be
dealt with by his successor.
</P>
<P>
	   Aaron said no decisions had been made yet on who would be nominated by
President Clinton to take over his job. The under secretary for international
affairs at Commerce oversees the 2,000-member International Trade
Administration, the government's primary agency for enforcing trade agreements
negotiated by the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative.
</P>
<P>
	   The ITA will also be in the lead in efforts to win congressional approval
for permanent normal trade status for China.
</P>
<P>
	   Aaron forecast an administration victory on the China vote and rejected
suggestions that because of strong opposition from labor unions, a key
Democratic constituency, that the administration may ultimately decide to put
off a vote if Republican leaders in Congress delay the matter until close to the
November elections.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Now we have the opportunity to do it,'' Aaron said. ``I don't see anything
next year that will make it easier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
