<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bills propose abolition of sheriffs system  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The eight county sheriffs would be stripped of
the bulk of their powers under four bills proposed Wednesday.
<P>
	   Each bill would take responsibility for courthouse security away from the
high sheriffs and give it to the state's Judicial Department.
</P>
<P>
	   Two bills would put the Department of Corrections in charge of prisoner
transportation, while the other two would give that job to the Judicial
Department. Currently, special deputy sheriffs transport prisoners.
</P>
<P>
	   The sets of bills differ when it comes to determining the fate of their
deputies, who serve legal papers such as summonses and divorce writs.
</P>
<P>
	   One set would leave it to lawmakers to decide whether paper servers should
be under the control of the Judicial Department. The other set proposes a
constitutional amendment which would let voters decide whether the Judicial
Department should oversee the deputies.
</P>
<P>
	   The constitutional amendment would also abolish the office of high sheriff,
the last remnant of county government in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
	   A public hearing on the bills likely will be held next month.
</P>
<P>
	   "Raising these different options gives everyone a bite at the apple," said
Sen. John Fonfara, co-chairman of the Program Review and Investigations
Committee, which proposed the bills. "There's legitimate arguments for each of
the positions, and they should all be debated."
</P>
<P>
	   Since Gov. John G. Rowland proposed abolishing the sheriffs last year, the
system has been socked with scandal. Two high sheriffs were indicted - one
charged with illegally possessing an assault weapon in his courthouse office,
the other accused of embezzlement and election fraud.
</P>
<P>
	   A female prisoner says she was raped by male inmates while being transported
in a New Haven County sheriff's van, and a special deputy was arrested for
firing his gun at a couple of black motorists as he chased them into Rhode
Island.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Michael Lawlor, co-chairman of the Judiciary Committee, said more bills
probably will be raised to abolish the sheriffs system.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is going to happen this year," said Lawlor, D-East Haven. "There's no
doubt in my mind."
</P>
<P>
	   Lawlor said he wants all duties now performed under the sheriffs system to
be transferred to the Judicial Department. Eventually, he said prisoner
transportation should be moved to the Department of Corrections.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's not something that can just happen overnight," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
