<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Turn Mixed; Dow Down 31.95  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned mixed today after the Federal Reserve raised
interest rates a modest quarter-percentage point and said that inflation poses a
threat to the booming U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
	   Shortly after the Fed's announcement, which was widely expected, the Dow
Jones industrial average was down 31.95 at 11,009.10. The Dow was up about 60
points in the moments before the Fed released its decision.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 2.83 at 1,406.45, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 42.27 at 4,094.25.
</P>
<P>
	   Blue-chip industrials turned lower after the Fed said it was increasing its
target for the federal funds rate -- the interest that banks charge each other
on overnight loan -- to 5.75 percent from 5.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   It also raised its mostly symbolic discount rate, the interest that the Fed
charges to make direct loans to banks by a quarter point to 5.25 percent from 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Higher rates can cut into corporate profits by raising the cost of borrowing
money. That makes it more difficult for businesses to finance growth.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors were also selling stock on the fear that today's rate increase
might be the first of several this year. In a statement explaining its decision,
the Fed said it continued to be worried that the rapidly growing economy "could
foster inflationary imbalances that would undermine the economy's record
economic expansion."
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed imposed three quarter-percentage point increases in 1999 in its bid
to keep inflation under control, and has suggested it will continue raising
rates until it sees tangible evidence of a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
	   While interest rate concerns dominated Wall Street, investors found little
corporate news to shape the market.
</P>
<P>
	   General Motors fell 3 7/16 to 81 13/16 after the company named president and
chief operating officer G. Richard Wagoner as chief executive officer, preparing
GM for the retirement of chairman and CEO John F. Smith Jr.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner rose 5 1/8 to 83 1/16 after reporting earnings that beat
analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume was running well ahead of Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.70 to 508.45.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
