<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton under fire for "murder" claim; launches own ad  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton was attacked Wednesday for
saying last month that unarmed African immigrant Amadou Diallo, fatally shot by
New York City police last year, had been murdered.
<P>
	   Clinton Senate campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said the first lady had
misspoken and "knows that only a jury can decide the outcome of this case."
</P>
<P>
	   The criticism came as Clinton launched the first advertising - a radio ad
seeking volunteers - that is being paid for from her own campaign funds. She is
expected to face New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
	   The complaints about the first lady's comment came as the murder trial of
four New York City police officers charged in the Diallo shooting began in
Albany. The trial was ordered moved to the state capital from the Bronx where
the shooting took place because of concerns over pre-trial publicity. The
officers have maintained that they thought Diallo was armed and felt their lives
were in danger. The officers fired 41 shots at Diallo, striking him 19 times.
</P>
<P>
	   During a visit to the Rev. Al Sharpton's New York City headquarters on
Martin Luther King Day, Mrs. Clinton had noted that "Senator (Charles) Schumer
... gave a speech after the tragic murder of Mr. Diallo in which he said that
what every community, but particularly the African-American community, wants is
to be respected and protected."
</P>
<P>
	   A group of police officers and others, calling themselves "The Coalition for
a Fair Trial," held a news conference Wednesday in Albany at a hotel near the
courthouse where the Diallo trial was underway.
</P>
<P>
	   In a letter to Clinton, the group said her statement had "prejudged the
officers" and "poisoned the jury pool."
</P>
<P>
	   Behind those at the news conference was a banner for the Law Enforcement
Alliance of America, a group that has been highly critical of the Clinton
administration and has in turn been criticized by it for taking money from the
National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
	   "It is not surprising that an NRA front group would attack Hillary in light
of her strong record on gun safety," Wolfson said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Victoria D'Angelo, a representative of the LEAA, said at the news conference
that her group's concern was not politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is not about Mayor Giuliani running for Senate. This is not about Mrs.
Clinton running for the Senate," she said. "This is about four police officers
on trial."
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the New York Post reported Wednesday that Clinton's newly hired
ad agency, DeVito/Verdi, produced a full-page newspaper ad for the American
Civil Liberties Union last year criticizing the Diallo shooting.
</P>
<P>
	   Featuring 41 jagged bullet holes, the ad said: "On February 4, 1999, the
NYPD gave Amadou Diallo the right to remain silent. And they did it without
saying a word." The ad was denounced at the time by the police and their union.
</P>
<P>
	   "We certainly don't endorse its content," Wolfson said when asked about the
Diallo shooting ad.
</P>
<P>
	   The new Clinton 60-second radio ad, also produced by DeVito/Verdi, features
the first lady talking about the "many goals I'd like to accomplish as your
senator." In explaining the goals, such as college tuition tax credits, her
voice alternately gives way to that of a woman, then a child and finally a man.
</P>
<P>
	   "Join the New Yorkers for Hillary team," the first lady says at the end of
the ad.
</P>
<P>
	   While the national Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee financed a
series of televisions ads across upstate New York last year boosting Clinton,
the radio ad represented the first time she had dipped into her own campaign
coffers for advertising. Wolfson said the ads would run in all of the state's
major radio markets for at least a week.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton plans to formally announce her Senate candidacy on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
