<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes Liability Limit Bill  </HEADLINE>
   By JANELLE CARTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Though President Clinton may veto the measure, the House
passed a bill Wednesday that creates an 18-year liability limit when
manufacturers are sued by employees who have been injured by aging equipment.
</P>
<P>
	   Critics called it ``unfair'' to American workers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have left workers out to dry,'' Rep. Stephanie Tubbs Jones, D-Ohio,
said before the measure passed 222-194. ``It (the bill) provides more protection
for machines than people.''
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., said. ``This malicious bill threatens worker
safety.''
</P>
<P>
	   But supporters said in an age of ``frivolous lawsuits,'' the measure was
needed. Often, machines are resold or modified without a manufacturer's
knowledge, they said.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Steve Chabot, R-Ohio, and the bill's sponsor, said endless lawsuits
cost businesses, employees and consumers. ``A very significant amount of the
money that's won or settled ends up in the lawyers' pockets.''
</P>
<P>
	   Besides, said Rep. Deborah Pryce, R-Ohio, ``If a product is used safely for
a substantially long period of time, it is not likely it was defective when
originally purchased. It's more likely the product was either misused or not
well maintained.''
</P>
<P>
	   House Republicans have led the push for liability reform, but the bill's
future in the Senate is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House has already indicated President Clinton will veto the
measure, said Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill covers workplace goods like machine tools, printing presses and
farm equipment. It bars suing manufacturers of those products for incidents that
occur 18 years after it was delivered to its first purchaser.
</P>
<P>
	   Exempted from the bill are workers who do not qualify for any form of
workers' compensation and products with warranties that guarantee the life or
safety of the product for more than 18 years. The bill would not affect products
such as automobiles and commercial airplanes.
</P>
<P>
	   Nineteen states currently have similar laws on the books, although all are
for a period less than 18 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress passed a similar 18-year liability measure in 1994 to protect the
small aircraft industry from lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This bill will not cause injured parties to go uncompensated,'' said Rep.
Mark Green, R-Wis. ``It separates out the least productive portion. . . the
litigation driven costs.''
</P>
<P>
	   Unions have campaigned against the bill. John Irvine, spokesman for the
American Federation of Government Employees, called the measure ``a dangerous
bill that will eliminate workers' rights.''
</P>
<P>
	   The bill would also allow employers and innocent bystanders to sue for
damages, while eliminating workers, Michael E. Mathis, government affairs
director for the International Brotherhood of Teamsters complained in a letter
to lawmakers. ``This makes no sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1451 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0156 </DOCNO>
