<HEADLINE> Bigger models strut new lingerie  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - For years supermodel Kate Dillon starved herself to be
thin. Then she got fed up. She started eating and stopped working as a "skinny
model."
<P>
	   Today the 5-foot-11-inch, 175-pound Dillon is showing off revealing
negligDee on the runway, as part of retailer Lane Bryant's effort to kick off
Cacique - its new line of plus-size lingerie and sleepwear.
</P>
<P>
	   Lane Bryant, which already carries plus-size clothing, hopes to make an
impression with its thongs, plunging lace bras, and sleepwear for women sized 14
to 28.
</P>
<P>
	   The national chain had advertised Wednesday night's Webcast of its "intimate
runway show" in the New York Post, The New York Times and Women's Wear Daily, a
fashion trade paper.
</P>
<P>
	   The ads feature generously proportioned women stripping down to their
underwear, with the words "big girls take back the night" and a Web address for
virtual viewing of the show.
</P>
<P>
	   The actual runway show, Tuesday night in New York, included the likes of
former Playboy Playmate of the Year Anna Nicole Smith, actress Kathy Najimy of
the NBC show "Veronica's Closet" and Mia Tyler, daughter of Aerosmith's Steven
Tyler.
</P>
<P>
	   Before and after the show, black and white movies of women posing
seductively blanketed the walls of the packed studio in the West Village.
</P>
<P>
	   Like most lingerie runway shows, this one had models - most close to 6 feet
tall - strutting to the beat of bassy music, sporting garter belts, bodyslips,
bustiers, strapless tops, camisoles and flowing, see-through nightgowns.
</P>
<P>
	   Applause - and cleavage - abounded.
</P>
<P>
	   But unlike those typically seen on television and in magazines, some of
these models had cellulite and stretch marks, not to mention flabby thighs and
stomachs.
</P>
<P>
	   "They are very sexy, even if they are bigger," said audience-member Corrado
Speziali. "A slim model gives you the wrong idea."
</P>
<P>
	   But slim models have been the norm until recently.
</P>
<P>
	   "You couldn't have done this five years ago," said Julie Lewit, founder of
Mode magazine, which is targeted at plus-size women. "There was no one
manufacturing the clothes and no retailers selling them. The circle had to be
completed."
</P>
<P>
	   Lewit says Mode's circulation has tripled since its launch three years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   And for Kate Dillon, weighing 175 pounds is not hurting her career at all.
"I'm in the new Gucci ads coming out this spring," Dillon said. "Being a
plus-size model is a celebration. It's great not to be an automaton."
</P>
<P>
	   ---
</P>
<P>
	   The fashion show Webcast was scheduled for 7 p.m. Eastern Standard Time
Wednesday at www.lanebryant.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-02-00 1455 </TRAILER>
