<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutors: Diallo shot without warning  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Four police officers who killed the unarmed Amadou
Diallo on his Bronx doorstep unleashed a 41-shot barrage without any warning,
prosecutors charged Wednesday at the officers' murder trial.
<P>
	   "They never called out commands like 'Stop, police,' or 'Don't move"' before
gunning down the West African immigrant in an apartment house vestibule,
prosecutor Eric Warner told jurors during opening statements in a packed
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
	   Defendants Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon, Kenneth Boss and Richard Murphy
"acted recklessly and with depraved indifference to Amadou Diallo's life. ...
For that, they are guilty of murder," Warner said.
</P>
<P>
	   On the first day of the racially charged trial of the four white officers,
defense attorneys painted a much different picture: that of a suspicious-seeming
man who failed to stop on their command, turned and pointed a dark object at
them. The officers thought it was a gun and fired in self-defense; it turned out
to be a wallet holding $169.
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll's attorney, Bennett Epstein, described Diallo, a black, 22-year-old
street vendor, as "a person who felt compelled to avoid police." The lawyer said
the victim caused a deadly chain reaction by ducking into the vestibule as the
plainclothes officers searched for violent suspects.
</P>
<P>
	   "The officers identified themselves with their shields (badges) out, as they
are trained to; Mr. Diallo doesn't listen to their orders to stop, which they
are trained to give," Epstein said.
</P>
<P>
	   By the time Diallo turned around, "he had taken them into the no-man's land
that is every police officer's nightmare," Epstein said. Carroll, after
realizing the mistake, tried to resuscitate Diallo, saying, "Don't die, please
don't die."
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a case about five good men," Epstein said. "One of them was Mr.
Diallo."
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll, 36, McMellon, 27, Boss, 28, and Murphy, 27, - who plan to testify
in their own defense - have pleaded innocent to second-degree murder and
reckless endangerment charges in the slaying of Diallo shortly after midnight on
Feb. 4, 1999. If convicted, they face a maximum sentence of 25 years to life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
	   The shooting triggered a wave of pretrial publicity and protests alleging
widespread brutality against minorities, and prompted an appeals court to rule
the officers could not get a fair trial in New York City. The case was moved 150
miles to Albany, where State Supreme Court Justice Joseph Teresi decided the
trial could be televised.
</P>
<P>
	   In his opening, Warner detailed how the 19 bullets tore through Diallo's
vital organs. He alleged many were fired while Diallo was falling down and on
the ground.
</P>
<P>
	   "Let us be absolutely clear: Each shot required a separate pull of the
trigger," Warner told the six-man, six woman jury, which includes four blacks.
</P>
<P>
	   The defense claimed that the officers were forced to make a split-second
decision using rapid-fire weapons. They also portrayed Diallo's Soundview
neighborhood one of the most dangerous sections of New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense attorney Stephen Worth, who represents McMellon, asserted that the
officers were only on trial "because there was a furor created by people who
have their own agendas" - an allusion to activists who say the case exemplifies
racism.
</P>
<P>
	   Outside the courtroom, the Rev. Al Sharpton accused Worth of trying to
manipulate white jurors. "When has anyone called (the defendants) racist?" said
the civil-rights activist.
</P>
<P>
	   Sharpton also complained that the defense was giving the impression that
Soundview - located in a police precinct where violent crime has dropped more
than 22 percent in the last two years - is "the wild, wild west."
</P>
<P>
	   "That's insulting," he said. "It shows why this should have been a Bronx
jury."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-02-00 1506 </TRAILER>
