<DOCNO> APW20000202.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education Dept Defends Math Program  </HEADLINE>
   By ANJETTA McQUEEN AP Education Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Education Department defended its endorsement of 10
school math programs while enduring criticism Wednesday from parents and
educators who complained to lawmakers about low test scores and student
performance.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If medical doctors experimented with our kids in the same fashion school
districts do, they would be in jail,'' Mark Schwartz, a parent of three from
Livonia, Mich., told the House Education and the Workforce Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year the Education Department designated 10 math programs as
``exemplary'' or ``promising'' for school districts seeking to improve lagging
math scores. More than 200 mathematicians took out a full-page newspaper ad
condemning the programs and asking Education Secretary Richard Riley to withdraw
the designations. The department declined.
</P>
<P>
	   James Milgram, a Stanford University mathematician who led the campaign
against the lessons, told lawmakers that in California, where many of the
lessons are used, more college freshmen in the California State University
system need remedial math courses. In 1989, 23 percent of entering freshmen need
the courses; this school year, 55 percent enrolled in such classes.
</P>
<P>
	   Rachel Tronstein, a University of Michigan freshman, blamed the math program
she took in high school for her B-minus in first-semester college calculus. She
said she earned A grades in her other courses.
</P>
<P>
	   Other critics said the new math programs, many of which rely on calculators
and building blocks, neglected important skills such as dividing fractions and
multiplying multidigit numbers. The basics, they said, are essential to students
hoping to master algebra, calculus, physics and other advanced concepts.
</P>
<P>
	   Kent McGuire, a Riley deputy who oversees research, said the department had
an obligation to offer schools guidance on the best lessons available. He
defended the expert panel that reviewed the programs
</P>
<P>
	   ``We should respect the members of the panel and applaud their good-faith
efforts,'' McGuire said.
</P>
<P>
	   Many school districts are accepting Core-Plus Math, Mathland and Connected
Math and other lessons because they promote reasoning rather than rote
memorization, said Judith Sunley, who directs education programs for the
National Science Foundation, which studied and supported many of the recommended
math lessons.
</P>
<P>
	   McGuire said the department simply was following a 1994 law requiring
federal researchers to make the recommendations. By law, the department cannot
directly tell the nation's nearly 16,000 school districts what to teach.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans who favor a reduced federal role in education hinted Wednesday
they would repeal the law, which was enacted by a Democrat-controlled Congress
and is up for renewal this year.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I imagine there will be pressure to do that,'' said Rep. Bill Goodling,
R-Pa., the House Education Committee chairman. ``Our job is to present research
and let the states and local districts make the decision about what they will
teach.''
</P>
<P>
	   Committee Democrats and administration officials emphasized that districts
and schools do not have to adopt the recommendations, which also cover programs
in science, gender equity, school safety and technology.
</P>
<P>
	   But school-level officials tend to follow the federal government's lead,
Milgram said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They are easily swayed by trendy and unproven programs, which typically
offer a superficial treatment of the subject leading to weak backgrounds in
their students,'' he said. ``The programs they develop and push simply set too
low a standard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1513 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comptroller says Thruway toll hike plan is 'misguided'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A plan to allow New York State Thruway tolls to go
up by as much as 3 percent each year without public comment or review is
"misguided" and should be abandoned, New York's comptroller said Wednesday.
<P>
	   H. Carl McCall asked the chairman of the Thruway Authority, Louis Tomson, to
justify any toll hike by detailing the transportation projects the increases are
designed to fund and whether the money is already available from other Authority
sources.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a big problem," McCall said. "There's no justification for it. If
you're going to do this, you start off by coming forward and explaining why you
need it. What's the additional money for?"
</P>
<P>
	   McCall told Tomson in a letter dated Tuesday and released Wednesday that the
toll increase "may or may not be justified - it's impossible to determine"
without a close look at the agency's books.
</P>
<P>
	   Thruway Authority spokeswoman Anya Frost Wednesday called McCall's letter
"completely political" and "headline grabbing." She said officials last week
sent McCall much of the information he requested about the Thruway's finances.
</P>
<P>
	   When approving the previously unannounced toll increase plan last week, the
Authority said it would be used to help fund about $1 billion in improvements on
the superhighway and the other transportation facilities the Authority is
responsible for over the next five years. The agency detailed only the $275
million in projects to be funded this year.
</P>
<P>
	   The first toll increase would take effect June 1 and total 1.8 percent,
according to Authority Executive Director John Platt. The agency plans to hold
four public hearings on the toll increase this spring before finalizing the
plan.
</P>
<P>
	   Toll hikes would be tied to increases in a national construction cost index.
</P>
<P>
	   McCall is a Democrat. The governing board of the Thruway Authority is
appointed by Republican Gov. George Pataki and the board is chaired by Tomson,
once a top figure in Pataki's executive chamber.
</P>
<P>
	   McCoy said he can do nothing to stop the Authority from raising tolls. But
he said he can audit the agency's books and report to the public whether he
believes the toll hike is justified by the Authority's fiscal needs.
</P>
<P>
	   McCoy said the toll increase would hit upstate New York particularly hard at
a time when it is becoming clearer that the region has not participated fully in
the national recovery from the recession of the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
	   "Most commerce upstate depends on highway transport, and New York State
already has some of the highest trucking fees and taxes in the nation," he wrote
to Toms. "A toll increase now will serve only as a further detriment to the
upstate economy, and that economy can ill afford even more damage."
</P>
<P>
	   Frost, the Thruway Authority spokeswoman, countered that the toll increase
plan is a "balanced" one that will enhance economic development, not detract
from it.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Thruway has always been an economic engine for growth and this plan
builds on it," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The leaders of both the state Assembly and Senate say they will seek to
block the toll increase legislative if the Thruway Authority does not pull it
back voluntarily or Partake, as he did with a proposed increase in 1996, doesn't
compel the agency to do so.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Tuesday, a lawsuit was filed against the Thruway Authority and seven
other toll-collecting agencies in New York, New Jersey, Delaware and Maryland
seeking elimination of highway toll booths on the ground that they damage the
environment.
</P>
<P>
	   By slowing and stopping traffic to collect tolls, the suit claims, the
agencies are increasing toxic tailpipe emissions and violating the federal Clean
Water and Clean Air acts.
</P>
<P>
	   The suit was filed in federal court in White Plains by Kevin of Washington,
executive director of No More Tolls, who is acting as his own attorney.
</P>
<P>
	   "The technology exists to collect road-use fees without causing long traffic
delays and destroying the environment," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-02-00 1517 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Worry Over U.S. in Balkans  </HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE GEDDA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senators expressed growing impatience Wednesday with the
continuing U.S. military role in the Balkans, arguing that the failure of
European nations to do more is prolonging the American presence there.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., said he doesn't mind helping the Europeans on their
territory when there is a bona fide threat.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I do mind being a patsy to European nations who don't carry their own
load,'' he said at a hearing of the Senate Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   Gen. Wesley Clark, commander in chief of allied forces in Europe, told the
senators that U.S. forces often have to do police work in Kosovo because
European nations have been unable to meet that need due to shortage of police
available for such duty.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We desperately, urgently need more nations to provide police,'' Clark
said. He said there are fewer than 2,000 international police officers in
Kosovo, of whom 20 percent are Americans. The goal is to have 4,718 officers
deployed.
</P>
<P>
	   Clark acknowledged that U.S. forces in Kosovo face a dangerous and difficult
environment. During the first six months of the post-war U.S. deployment in
Kosovo, he said there were 615 incidents of hostile fire in the vicinity of
those troops, 15 mortar or recoilless rifle attacks, 20 altercations with unruly
crowds, 129 grenade attacks and 58 mine strikes.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the continued presence of the NATO-led Kosovo Force (KFOR) ``is
necessary to provide a secure environment for civil implementation to take place
and is key to achieving a lasting peace in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. troops have served in Bosnia since late 1995 and now number about
5,600. Two deadlines set by President Clinton for the return of the troops have
come and gone, and there is no longer a target date for their departure. All
told there are about 24,000 peacekeepers in Bosnia, mostly from NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the 50,000 peace implementation forces in Kosovo, about 6,000 are
Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. James Imhofe, R-Okla., said the deployments are ``a terrible drain on
our state of readiness.''
</P>
<P>
	   Committee chairman John Warner, R-Va., said it may be unrealistic to think
that ethnic reconciliation is possible in either Bosnia or Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
	   He added that he believes the United States has reached a point ``where it
is the responsibility of the Congress to reexamine the goals, their
achievability and what appears to be our open-ended involvement in Bosnia and
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clark said some European nations in recent months transferred police in the
Balkans to East Timor because that was considered a higher priority.
</P>
<P>
	   Warner reacted sharply, saying in a raised voice, ``The highest priority is
the protection of our armed forces, who weren't trained to do this.''
</P>
<P>
	   Warner said the European Union promised $500 million to peacekeeping in the
Balkans, then reduced that to $200 million. ``Now the $200 million is in
doubt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said the administration should let the Europeans
know that ``we are really disappointed that they have not come through with the
police force they had promised.''
</P>
<P>
	   There is widespread agreement among Europeans that they should be able to
deal with most security threats on the continent. Plans are being made for a
60,000 European-only defense force by the year 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1524 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sens. Impatient With Balkans Force  </HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE GEDDA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senators expressed growing impatience Wednesday with the
continuing U.S. military role in the Balkans, arguing that the failure of
European nations to do more is prolonging the American presence there.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., said he doesn't mind helping the Europeans on their
territory when there is a bona fide threat.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I do mind being a patsy to European nations who don't carry their own
load,'' he said at a hearing of the Senate Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   Gen. Wesley Clark, commander in chief of allied forces in Europe, told the
senators that U.S. forces often have to do police work in Kosovo because
European nations have been unable to meet that need due to shortage of police
available for such duty.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We desperately, urgently need more nations to provide police,'' Clark
said. He said there are fewer than 2,000 international police officers in
Kosovo, of whom 20 percent are Americans. The goal is to have 4,718 officers
deployed.
</P>
<P>
	   Clark acknowledged that U.S. forces in Kosovo face a dangerous and difficult
environment. During the first six months of the post-war U.S. deployment in
Kosovo, he said there were 615 incidents of hostile fire in the vicinity of
those troops, 15 mortar or recoilless rifle attacks, 20 altercations with unruly
crowds, 129 grenade attacks and 58 mine strikes.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the continued presence of the NATO-led Kosovo Force (KFOR) ``is
necessary to provide a secure environment for civil implementation to take place
and is key to achieving a lasting peace in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. troops have served in Bosnia since late 1995 and now number about
5,600. Two deadlines set by President Clinton for the return of the troops have
come and gone, and there is no longer a target date for their departure. All
told there are about 24,000 peacekeepers in Bosnia, mostly from NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the 50,000 peace implementation forces in Kosovo, about 6,000 are
Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. James Imhofe, R-Okla., said the deployments are ``a terrible drain on
our state of readiness.''
</P>
<P>
	   Committee chairman John Warner, R-Va., said it may be unrealistic to think
that ethnic reconciliation is possible in either Bosnia or Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
	   He added that he believes the United States has reached a point ``where it
is the responsibility of the Congress to reexamine the goals, their
achievability and what appears to be our open-ended involvement in Bosnia and
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clark said some European nations in recent months transferred police in the
Balkans to East Timor because that was considered a higher priority.
</P>
<P>
	   Warner reacted sharply, saying in a raised voice, ``The highest priority is
the protection of our armed forces, who weren't trained to do this.''
</P>
<P>
	   Warner said the European Union promised $500 million to peacekeeping in the
Balkans, then reduced that to $200 million. ``Now the $200 million is in
doubt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said the administration should let the Europeans
know that ``we are really disappointed that they have not come through with the
police force they had promised.''
</P>
<P>
	   There is widespread agreement among Europeans that they should be able to
deal with most security threats on the continent. Plans are being made for a
60,000 European-only defense force by the year 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
