<HEADLINE> Stocks Mostly Higher; Dow Up 31.95  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher today after the Federal Reserve
raised interest rates a modest quarter-percentage point, even as central bankers
warned that inflation remains a threat to the booming U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
	   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 31.95 at 11,009.10. The Dow was up about 60 points in
the moments before the Fed released its decision, then dipped as low as 53
points following the widely-expected announcement.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators also rose. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up
9.01 at 1,418.29, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 50.78 at 4,102.76.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks rose after the Fed said it was increasing its target for the federal
funds rate -- the interest that banks charge each other on overnight loans -- to
5.75 percent from 5.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   It also raised its mostly symbolic discount rate, the interest that the Fed
charges to make direct loans to banks, to 5.25 percent from 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Higher rates can cut into corporate profits by raising the cost of borrowing
money. That makes it more difficult for businesses to finance growth.
</P>
<P>
	   As a result, investors turned to the stocks that are advancing quickly
enough to outrun rising interest rates, said A. Marshall Acuff Jr., equity
strategist at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
	   "Investors are crowding into shares of the companies that they believe will
continue to grow earnings, despite the Fed's tightening of interest rates,"
Acuff said.
</P>
<P>
	   For the most part, that meant technology stocks. Hewlett-Packard gained 5
1/4 to 111 1/16, and IBM rose 4 7/8 to 114 13/16, the strongest of the Dow
components.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Nasdaq, Yahoo! rose 14 5/8 to 332.
</P>
<P>
	   Trading remained highly volatile as investors worried that today's rate
increase might be the first of several this year. In a statement explaining its
decision, the Fed said it continued to be worried that the rapidly growing
economy "could foster inflationary imbalances that would undermine the economy's
record economic expansion."
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed imposed three quarter-percentage point increases in 1999 in its bid
to keep inflation under control, and has suggested it will continue raising
rates until it sees tangible evidence of a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
	   While interest rate concerns dominated Wall Street, investors found little
corporate news to shape the market.
</P>
<P>
	   General Motors fell 3 1/4 to 82 after the company named president and chief
operating officer G. Richard Wagoner as chief executive officer, preparing GM
for the retirement of chairman and CEO John F. Smith Jr.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner rose 6 1/4 to 85 after reporting earnings that beat analysts'
expectations.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 814.18 million shares, well ahead of
Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 5.71 to 509.46.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
