<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army May Prosecute No Gun Ri Vets  </HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT BURNS AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army has begun interviewing Korean War veterans and
has not ruled out criminal prosecutions as a result of its investigation of the
alleged mass killing of South Korean civilians at No Gun Ri, Army Secretary
Louis Caldera said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Likening the situation to war crimes trials following World War II, Caldera
told the Associated Press, ``We don't want to set a double standard.'' He added,
however, that it is too early to conclude that any actions by American troops at
No Gun Ri at the outset of the Korean War rose to the level of war crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   Caldera said Army investigators so far have questioned a few dozen U.S.
veterans from units that were in the area at the time of the alleged killings,
but have not yet talked to those who told the AP last year that a large number
of South Korean refugees were gunned down at the hamlet of No Gun Ri.
</P>
<P>
	   Before the AP report, which was based on ex-soldiers' statements as well as
declassified U.S. government documents, both U.S. and South Korean officials had
insisted there was no evidence to support the claims. After the report, however,
both the Defense Department and South Korea launched investigations.
</P>
<P>
	   Caldera said the Army needs to investigate further before deciding whether
criminal prosecutions are warranted.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have not ruled that out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Caldera, the Army's top civilian official, made these other points in a
wide-ranging interview with the AP:
</P>
<P>
	   --In searching for more effective recruiting methods, the Army has begun
trying to reach more young people who otherwise would move directly from high
school into college. Recruiters also will seek out college students who, for
financial or other reasons, are willing to leave school to join the Army. With
these and other new approaches, the Army's recent slump in recruiting ``will
turn around for us.''
</P>
<P>
	   --The Army's budget for 2001, to be submitted to Congress on Monday, will
include $1 billion for an ambitious effort to transform the service into a
lighter, more mobile force. Caldera would not discuss specifics, but said some
big weapons programs such as the Crusader mobile artillery will be scaled back.
</P>
<P>
	   --Debate over whether gays ought to be allowed to serve openly in the
military is unlikely to be settled during the final year of the Clinton
administration. Caldera said he supports the current ``don't ask, don't tell''
approach of letting gays serve so long as they keep their sexual orientation to
themselves. Those who say that allowing acknowledged gays to serve would
undermine discipline in the military have ``valid concerns.''
</P>
<P>
	   In describing the Army's No Gun Ri investigation, Caldera said officials
have reviewed more than 1 million documents but have not yet approached the
ex-soldiers who have publicly asserted that they knew of -- or participated in
-- deliberate killings of South Korean refugees in the war's opening weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead, the Army investigators are talking to veterans who had an indirect
connection, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It makes sense from an investigative perspective to begin your
investigation with those who may have knowledge of the actions of others, that
can shed light on the actions of others, before moving up to those who may
themselves have participated'' in the killings, Caldera said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If you go directly to the person involved, that person is going to be
represented by counsel, and the first thing they're going to do is ask for
immunity from any prosecution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   At some point the Army will have to decide whether to grant some witnesses
limited immunity that would bar prosecutors from using their testimony against
them, he said. He distinguished this from offering complete immunity, which
protects a person from being prosecuted for crimes they testify about.
</P>
<P>
	   In saying the Army did not rule out seeking criminal prosecutions in No Gun
Ri, Caldera noted that the U.S. government supports various international
conventions that try war criminals.
</P>
<P>
	   ``And we go after Nazis and others who perpetrated atrocities in World War
II, and we certainly don't want to set a double standard,'' Caldera said. ``But
we don't know at this point -- by any stretch -- whether this (No Gun Ri) is a
situation that is anywhere near related to those kinds of criminal activities.''
</P>
<P>
	   Caldera said the Army hopes to finish its No Gun Ri investigation before
June, when both Seoul and Washington will be holding special ceremonies to mark
the 50th anniversary of the start of the Korean War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
