<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wahid Attends Cabinet Meeting  </HEADLINE>
   By GEOFF SPENCER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- The standoff between Indonesia's president and
the military intensified Wednesday when the security minister attended a Cabinet
meeting despite the president's demand that he resign.
</P>
<P>
	   President Abdurrahman Wahid insisted during a European tour that his
authority remained intact and that he has ``no personal enemies'' at home. Life
went on as usual in the Indonesian capital, with commerce operating normally and
people in the streets. The military discounted coup rumors.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, the conflict between Wahid and Security and Political Affairs
Minister Gen. Wiranto highlights the power struggle between the new, reformist
president and army hard-liners linked to authoritarian ex-President Suharto.
</P>
<P>
	   That friction came to a head Monday when Wahid, who took office in October,
demanded that Wiranto resign. His call followed the release of a government
report that held the former army chief responsible for killing and destruction
in East Timor after its people voted for independence from Indonesia last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Wiranto denies any wrongdoing and says the report's authors are biased
against the military.
</P>
<P>
	   The general, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, smiled at
reporters Wednesday but did not comment as he strode into the Cabinet room. Some
ministers expressed sympathy for his stand, and one suggested Wiranto should be
given more time to step down.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It would be fair and good for Wiranto,'' said Human Rights Minister
Hasballah Saad.
</P>
<P>
	   In Paris, Wahid spoke briefly with reporters. He took only two questions --
neither of which touched on specifically what he would do if Wiranto refuses to
quit. He had said the day before in London that if Wiranto won't leave, he will
``remove him from office'' when he returns to Indonesia on Feb. 13.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I can handle the country as a whole,'' Wahid said in Paris. ``I do not
have any personal enemies there.''
</P>
<P>
	   Military spokesman Air Vice Marshal Graito Usodo dismissed the possibility
Wednesday that the army might stage a coup in support of Wiranto.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Wiranto is a minister,'' he said. ``The president has the right to choose
or dismiss ministers.''
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, United Nations officials in East Timor said Wednesday they dug 10
bodies from a grave believed to contain the remains of up to 60 people killed by
anti-independence militias backed by Indonesian troops.
</P>
<P>
	   U.N. spokesman Manoel de Almeida e Silva said the bodies were recovered near
the border town of Pasabe, in the isolated enclave of Oecussi.
</P>
<P>
	   Human rights groups and East Timor's independence leaders want the U.N.
Security Council to set up a tribunal to try those responsible for the violence.
But U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, the United States, and other countries
have backed Wahid's position that Indonesia should be allowed to conduct any
trials.
</P>
<P>
	   Wiranto is a former close aide of Suharto, who used the might of the
military to rule for 32 years until he was forced to quit as president after
riots and protests shook the world's fourth-most populous nation in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1610 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Seeks Major IRA Disarm Move  </HEADLINE>
   By SHAWN POGATCHNIK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The survival of Northern Ireland's
Protestant-Catholic administration will depend on ``substantial progress'' soon
toward disarming the Irish Republican Army, British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Blair scheduled a meeting Thursday with his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern,
as the two governments struggled to calm the crisis imperiling the Cabinet for
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
	   The four-party coalition Cabinet -- the intended cornerstone of the
province's 1998 peace accord -- finally took shape nine weeks ago as part of a
U.S.-brokered deal. But that deal is now falling apart.
</P>
<P>
	   After behind-the-scenes diplomacy stretching from Belfast to Dublin, London
and Washington, Blair's government was expected to announce Thursday whether the
Cabinet's powers should be transferred back to London to enable fresh
negotiations in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
	   Such a move was envisaged in November's deadlock-breaking deal produced by
American diplomat George Mitchell. It required the Ulster Unionists to drop
their demand for an IRA arms handover in advance of the Cabinet's formation --
but on condition that IRA disarmament would speedily commence in response.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal specified that Canadian Gen. John de Chastelain, chairman of
Northern Ireland's independent disarmament commission, should assess in January
whether his secret negotiations with IRA leaders had borne fruit.
</P>
<P>
	   Though the British and Irish governments have refused to release the
general's full report since its delivery two days ago, Blair emphasized that it
contained ``insufficient progress.''
</P>
<P>
	   Blair said his officials were working ``day and night'' on potential moves
the IRA might offer, and whether these could be sufficient to keep the Ulster
Unionists governing Northern Ireland alongside Sinn Fein. But he didn't sound
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Unless there is substantial progress, then we have a serious crisis on our
hands,'' Blair said.
</P>
<P>
	   In Washington, White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said President
Clinton strongly urged all parties not to allow the Cabinet to unravel and ``to
understand how harshly history will judge the parties at this point if they turn
back from the progress they made.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams said he believed Blair was ``going to be
spooked by the unionists into suspending the institutions.'' He said the IRA
would not disarm in those circumstances, and called the Ulster Unionists'
handling of the situation ``disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble emphasized they would be obliged to
resign from the Cabinet within the next week if the IRA refused to disarm and
the British government didn't intervene.
</P>
<P>
	   The Cabinet can't operate without the Ulster Unionists, the biggest party in
Northern Ireland. But rising Protestant hostility to sharing power with Sinn
Fein also means that Ulster Unionists can't count on sufficient support to win
re-election to Cabinet posts in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1611 </TRAILER>
