<HEADLINE> Israeli Planes Strike Lebanon  </HEADLINE>
   By SAM F. GHATTAS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Islamic militants set off a roadside bomb in
southern Lebanon on Wednesday, killing a man and injuring two Israeli-allied
militiamen, despite a string of Israeli air raids intended to halt guerrilla
attacks.
</P>
<P>
	   Hezbollah guerrillas claimed responsibility for the bombing, which targeted
a military vehicle belonging to the South Lebanon Army near the village of
Braachit, six miles north of the Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
	   A Lebanese contractor doing construction work for the SLA was killed,
Lebanese security officials said, and another contractor and two militiamen in
the vehicle were injured.
</P>
<P>
	   Shortly after the bombing, SLA militiamen opened fire with mortars and
machine guns, said the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel carried out air raids throughout the day, apparently to keep the
guerrillas at bay after days of heavy fighting. On Monday, a Hezbollah rocket
attack killed three Israeli soldiers in south Lebanon. The day before, Hezbollah
guerrillas detonated a bomb that killed the No. 2 man in the SLA militia.
</P>
<P>
	   The fighting could aggravate efforts to get peace talks back on track
between Israel and Syria, the dominant power in Lebanon. The talks, which began
in December, were postponed indefinitely last month. U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has appealed to Syria and Israel to show restraint.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first airstrike Wednesday, Israeli fighter jets fired two missiles
into a valley between the villages of Chaaitiyeh and Zibqine, apparently in
pursuit of guerrillas attempting to infiltrate the Israeli-occupied zone, the
Lebanese officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Israeli fighters later struck an olive grove outside the village of Jouaya,
six miles to the northeast.
</P>
<P>
	   In a third raid, Lebanese officials said Israeli helicopter gunships strafed
guerrilla infiltration trails near the village of Yater, four miles east of the
first strike.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday evening, Israeli jets fired two rockets at suspected guerrilla
positions about 10 miles northeast of Yater, in the central sector of the
occupied zone, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Both the security officials and Hezbollah's office in Beirut reported
exchanges of rockets and machine-gun fire in the area that took place around the
time of the Israeli air raids.
</P>
<P>
	   In Jerusalem, the Israeli army confirmed three of the raids, saying planes
struck ``terrorist targets'' and returned safely to base. It did not issue a
statement on the raid reported near Yater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
