<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Passes Bankruptcy Bill  </HEADLINE>
   By MARCY GORDON AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate today passed legislation to raise the
$5.15-an-hour minimum wage by a dollar while reducing people's ability to sweep
away credit card and other debts through bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
	   The 83-14 vote was on a broad bankruptcy overhaul bill that also would give
new tax breaks to small businesses and increase penalties for powder cocaine
crimes. The House has passed a similar but narrower bankruptcy bill; the Clinton
administration opposes both versions.
</P>
<P>
	   The vote culminated several hours of drama in which Democrats summoned Vice
President Al Gore to break a possible tie vote on an abortion rights measure.
Republicans dropped their opposition to the amendment upon Gore's arrival at the
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill would raise the minimum wage to $6.15 an hour over three years, a
span that Democrats and President Clinton say is too long. They also object to
$76 billion in tax breaks over 10 years that Republicans maintain would help
small businesses deal with the impact of raising the wage floor. The House has
taken no action on a minimum wage increase, but Republican leaders have promised
a vote before November's election.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier today, the Senate voted 80-17 to prohibit people found to have
violated laws protecting abortion clinics from using bankruptcy proceedings to
escape fines and civil judgments. The lopsided voted denied Gore an opportunity
to reaffirm his abortion rights credentials.
</P>
<P>
	   Former Sen. Bill Bradley, opposing Gore for the Democratic presidential
nomination, has questioned the vice president's commitment to protecting women's
right to choose abortion, citing Gore's votes on abortion measures as a House
member nearly 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   ``With this amendment, nobody will be able to politically demagogue this
issue,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee,
said shortly before the vote.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, called Gore's rush back to Washington
``theater'' -- adding, ``the vice president's going to need it'' to win election
in November.
</P>
<P>
	   Grassley's comments prompted Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., to say, ``This
issue is not about theater. It is about the very real issue of violence against
women. ... We cannot allow violent extremists to use the bankruptcy code to
carry out'' their agenda.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This issue is so important, I'm not going to take a chance of seeing it
fail,'' Gore said just prior to the vote.''
</P>
<P>
	   The amendment's sponsor, Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., cited the case of
Operation Rescue founder Randall Terry, who filed for bankruptcy court
protection in November 1998, blaming heavy debts owed to women's groups and
abortion clinics that have sued him.
</P>
<P>
	   Partisan fighting over abortion and guns has marked Senate debate on the
legislation, which would make it tougher for people to sweep away their debts
through bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., denounced Schumer's proposal Tuesday as an attempt
``to silence the free speech of abortion opponents.''
</P>
<P>
	   Defeated today was an amendment by Sens. Carl Levin, D-Mich., and Richard
Durbin, D-Ill., to prohibit gun makers and dealers from erasing debts in
bankruptcy that arose from successful lawsuits against them.
</P>
<P>
	   The proposal ``is designed to encourage lawsuits ... and put the firearms
industry in this country out of business,'' said Hatch.
</P>
<P>
	   Noting that some two dozen U.S. cities and towns have sued gun makers and
distributors, Levin said the firearms industry ``should not be able to evade
judgments by going bankrupt.''
</P>
<P>
	   Also Tuesday, the Senate rebuffed an attempt by some Democrats to make it
harder for high-interest, storefront lenders to collect debts from people who
have filed for bankruptcy relief.
</P>
<P>
	   Senators voted, 53-44, to reject an amendment proposed by Sen. Paul
Wellstone, D-Minn., that would have prohibited lending businesses charging more
than 100 percent annual interest in recovering debts from consumers in
bankruptcy proceedings.
</P>
<P>
	   A partisan dispute over a minimum wage increase and tax breaks for small
businesses, meanwhile, threatened to delay final Senate passage of the
legislation to overhaul the bankruptcy laws.
</P>
<P>
	   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said a $1 increase in the $5.15
hourly minimum over three years was insufficient. In addition, the White House
and Democratic lawmakers oppose $18.4 billion in small-business tax breaks
proposed by the GOP that are tied to the minimum wage increase.
</P>
<P>
	   If changes are not made, Daschle told reporters, ``I'm concerned that the
bankruptcy bill could be in some jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
	   Voting against the abortion rights amendment were Republican Sens. Wayne
Allard of Colorado, Sam Brownback and Pat Roberts of Kansas, Jim Bunning of
Kentucky, Mike DeWine of Ohio, Michael Enzi of Wyoming, Phil Gramm of Texas, Rod
Grams of Minnesota, Jesse Helms of North Carolina, Tim Hutchinson of Arkansas,
Jon Kyl of Arizona, Richard Lugar of Indiana, Don Nickles of Oklahoma, Jeff
Sessions of Alabama, Bob Smith of New Hampshire, Fred Thompson of Tennessee and
George Voinovich of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who is campaigning for the Republican
presidential nomination, and Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., did not vote. Sen.
Peter Fitzgerald, R-Ill., whose family owns a bank, recused himself by voting
'present.'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
