<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal Judges Scrap Bypass Rule  </HEADLINE>
   By PETE YOST Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal judges in the nation's capital have quietly
scrapped a rule that allowed their chief judge to bypass normal random
assignments and send cases involving prominent Democrats to appointees of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   After a lengthy review, the full-time and senior judges for the District of
Columbia rescinded the rule during their closed monthly meeting Tuesday,
according to several officials at the U.S. Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
	   The judges are developing a new system in which protracted or complex cases
will be randomly assigned from a separate pool of all the judges at the
courthouse, the officials said, speaking only on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
	   Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, the chief judge for the U.S District
Courthouse in Washington, has been under scrutiny since last summer when The
Associated Press reported she used the rule to bypass the normal computerized
random assignment system in two high-profile Democratic cases.
</P>
<P>
	   AP reported that Johnson had specially assigned the criminal cases of
presidential friends Webster Hubbell and Charlie Trie to judges appointed by
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   It was later learned that Johnson directed a total of five Democratic
fund-raising prosecutions to Clinton-appointed judges, plus the Hubbell tax
evasion case.
</P>
<P>
	   Critics questioned whether the special assignments created the appearance of
political favoritism. At the time Johnson assigned the cases, four of the 12
full-time judges at the courthouse were Republican appointees and all eight
senior judges were appointed by presidents other than Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   Johnson has declined repeated requests for interviews. But in a letter to a
newspaper after the controversy erupted, she said she made the special
assignments to ``move the docket as expeditiously as possible'' and that
politics was ``never a factor.''
</P>
<P>
	   Her decisions, nonetheless, caused unrest among her colleagues about the
rarely used rule she invoked to make the special assignments. Congressional
investigators and a federal appeals judge also reviewed Johnson's actions.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge Paul Friedman, who received some of the campaign
fund-raising cases from Johnson, spearheaded the internal courthouse review of
the long-standing rule -- a review that began last April, before the issue
became public. He recommended the rule be abolished.
</P>
<P>
	   The rule stated that criminal indictments can be specially assigned ``if the
chief judge determines ... that the case will be protracted and that the
expeditious and efficient disposition of the court's business requires
assignment of the case on a nonrandom basis.''
</P>
<P>
	   Pressure to scrap the rule increased last month when Rep. Howard Coble,
R-N.C., chairman of a House Judiciary Committee panel, disclosed that Johnson
assigned a Clinton judge a case that was not ``protracted'' -- the guilty plea
of prominent Miami businessman Howard Glicken, a former fund-raiser for Vice
President Al Gore. Glicken admitted to two misdemeanors in the fund-raising
investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   The chief judge has never said why she bypassed the random assignment system
in Glicken's case.
</P>
<P>
	   Court records show presidential friend Vernon Jordan intervened in the case,
asking the sentencing judge to be lenient. Glicken was given community service
work and probation.
</P>
<P>
	   The Friedman-led review began after the Judicial Conference, the
policy-making body for the federal judiciary, last March revoked the 28-year-old
policy that allowed for special assignments of certain cases, saying they raise
concern about ``judge shopping.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a good development,'' New York University law professor Stephen
Gillers said of the judges in Washington killing the rule. ``Even though there
may be some unusual situations in which it makes sense to have a specific
assignment, in the long run, confidence in the justice system will be stronger
if the choice is random.''
</P>
<P>
	   In the Watergate and the Iran-Contra scandals, several high-profile criminal
cases at the courthouse in Washington were specially assigned. In those cases,
juries convicted the defendants.
</P>
<P>
	   In the Hubbell prosecution and the fund-raising cases such as the one
against former Gore fund-raiser Maria Hsia, the judges Johnson assigned the
cases originally tossed out the indictment or key charges in them.
</P>
<P>
	   The decisions were overturned on appeal, but prosecutors lost valuable time.
Testimony in the 2-year-old Hsia case begins Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1628 </TRAILER>
