<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Mixed; Dow Down 37.85  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks struggled to a mixed finish today after the Federal
Reserve's widely expected interest-rate increase did little to calm the
turbulent U.S. financial markets.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 37.85 to close at 11,003.20. The Dow
rose as much as 60 points in the moments before the Fed released its decision,
then bobbed between positive and negative territory for much of the rest of the
session.
</P>
<P>
	   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 0.16 to 1,409.12, and the Nasdaq composite
index rose 21.95 to 4,073.93.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 1,681 up, 1,340 down and 519 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
	   NYSE volume totaled 1.03 billion shares as of 4 p.m., vs. 974.38 million in
the previous session.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 6.14 to 509.89.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks gave up early gains after the Fed said it was increasing its target
for the federal funds rate -- the interest that banks charge each other on
overnight loans -- to 5.75 percent from 5.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   It also raised its mostly symbolic discount rate, the interest that the Fed
charges to make direct loans to banks, to 5.25 percent from 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Higher rates can cut into corporate profits by raising the cost of borrowing
money. That makes it more difficult for businesses to finance growth.
</P>
<P>
	   As a result, investors turned to the companies that are advancing quickly
enough to outrun rising interest rates, said A. Marshall Acuff Jr., equity
strategist at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
	   "Investors are crowding into shares of the companies that they believe will
continue to grow earnings, despite the Fed's tightening of interest rates,"
Acuff said.
</P>
<P>
	   For the most part, that meant technology stocks. Hewlett-Packard and IBM
posted the strongest gains among Dow components.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Nasdaq, Yahoo! and Qualcomm rose sharply.
</P>
<P>
	   "Those are the companies that are driving innovation and improving
productivity for the U.S. work force," said Philip S. Dow, director of equity
strategy at Dain Rauscher Wessels in Minneapolis. "They're helping this economic
expansion continue."
</P>
<P>
	   Trading remained highly volatile as investors worried that today's rate
increase might be the first of several this year. In a statement explaining its
decision, the Fed said it continued to be worried that the rapidly growing
economy "could foster inflationary imbalances that would undermine the economy's
record economic expansion."
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed imposed three quarter-percentage point increases in 1999 in its bid
to keep inflation under control, and has suggested it will continue raising
rates until it sees tangible evidence of a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
	   That hampered financial services companies like American Express, which
accounted for much of the Dow's decline. Higher interest rates are especially
damaging to financial companies, which see lending volume slide.
</P>
<P>
	   While interest rate concerns dominated Wall Street, investors found little
corporate news to shape the market.
</P>
<P>
	   General Motors fell after the company named president and chief operating
officer G. Richard Wagoner as chief executive officer, preparing GM for the
retirement of chairman and CEO John F. Smith Jr.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner rose after reporting earnings that beat analysts' expectations.
The strong report also lifted shares of America Online, which has stumbled since
it made its bold bid to acquire Time Warner last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
