<HEADLINE> White House Urges China Trade Bill  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM RAUM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration waged a two-sided lobbying
campaign on Wednesday, urging Congress to approve a World Trade Organization
deal with China but reject legislation to increase military ties with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We ought not to upset that apple cart,'' Sandy Berger, the president's
national security adviser, said a day after the House overwhelmingly passed the
Taiwan military bill, a measure condemned by China and under a veto threat from
the administration.
</P>
<P>
	   Berger said the administration hoped to work with the Senate in an effort to
prevent the bill from becoming law, suggesting it was needlessly confrontational
with China. No date has been set for Senate consideration.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill, approved 341-70 on Tuesday in the House, would lift the
long-standing prohibition on formal U.S-Taiwan military cooperation, increase
Taiwanese attendance at U.S. military academies and require an annual Pentagon
report on the threats faced by Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill was watered down from an earlier version to the point where its
impact would be largely symbolic. Berger suggested that by formalizing a
military relationship between the United States and Taiwan, the legislation
would jeopardize the ``one China'' policy that has governed U.S. relations with
both sides of the Taiwan Strait for decades.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If it ain't broke, don't fix it,'' he said in remarks to the Woodrow
Wilson Center, a foreign policy group.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, Berger pledged a ``full court press'' by President Clinton
and his national security team on behalf of legislation to grant permanent trade
benefits to China.
</P>
<P>
	   That status now must be reviewed annually for China even though it is
routinely conferred on other U.S. trading partners. Permanent trade status for
China is part of a package to complete China's entry into the 135-member World
Trade Organization, the Geneva-based organization that sets rules for world
trade.
</P>
<P>
	   After the collapse of global trade talks in Seattle and a determined
campaign by organized labor and environmental groups against the measure,
Clinton faces a tough sell in persuading Congress to support the bill.
</P>
<P>
	   But Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., predicted earlier this week
that the legislation would be approved.
</P>
<P>
	   Berger said that giving China permanent trade relations would ``get us out
of the cycle we are now in, where the future of Chinese trade comes up every
single year for a divisive and not very effective vote.''
</P>
<P>
	   Although the renewal of trade benefits for China has come up in Congress
each year for the past 20 years, Congress never has voted to withdraw the
benefits.
</P>
<P>
	   Threatening to withhold trade benefits ``is like a nuclear bomb. It's not
very good for what's happening in China,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, a top Taiwanese presidential adviser said Wednesday that it would
be a ``terrible blunder'' for China to threaten Taiwan during next month's
election as it did in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Any act of intimidation or use of force against Taiwan would simply be
counterproductive,'' John H. Chang said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
	   There is no indication China is preparing to launch missiles and conduct war
games near the island like it did in the run-up to Taiwan's 1996 presidential
elections. That intimidation campaign backfired as the Taiwanese overwhelmingly
electing Beijing's nemesis, Lee Teng-hui.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, rhetoric has been heating up between mainland China and Taiwan as the
island prepares for its election March 18.
</P>
<P>
	   Separately, CIA Director George Tenet told the Senate Intelligence Committee
that because of the increased tensions, ``we see high potential for another
military flare-up across the Taiwan Strait this year.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said that China had been increasing the ``size and sophistication'' of
its forces arrayed along the Strait, including deploying short-range ballistic
missiles. China should receive the first of two modern Russian-built destroyers
later this month, and ``we expect the ship to join the East Sea Fleet, which
regularly conducts operations near Taiwan,'' Tenet said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1637 </TRAILER>
