<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Ask For 2-Year Budget  </HEADLINE>
   By JIM ABRAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bipartisan group of lawmakers pressed Wednesday for
adoption of a two-year budget cycle, saying it would give Congress more time to
oversee the programs it funds and ensure that federal money is spent wisely.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., said the ``long-overdue common-sense reform''
could be ``the most sweeping change in the budget process in the last quarter
century.''
</P>
<P>
	   Congress now spends much of its time on the annual process of drawing up a
budget and passing the 13 appropriations or spending bills. Lawmakers rarely
finish by the Oct. 1 beginning of the fiscal year; last year they completed
their work 50 days late.
</P>
<P>
	   The numerous biennial budgeting bills introduced in the House and Senate
would, as in some 20 state governments, have Congress devote the first year of a
two-year session to approving a budget. In the second year, lawmakers would
oversee programs to ensure they are being run well.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We need to spend less time putting together a budget that spends the
taxpayers' money and more time making sure that taxpayer dollars are spent
wisely,'' said Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., chairman of the Senate Governmental
Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Joe Lieberman of Connecticut, the ranking Democrat on the Governmental
Affairs Committee, said the biennial budget would alleviate ``the gridlock so
often caused by our annual confrontations over budget and appropriations.''
</P>
<P>
	   One longtime supporter of the change is the chairman of the Senate Budget
Committee, Republican Pete Domenici of New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
	   As an example of the inefficiencies of the current system, he noted that the
Army Corps of Engineers produced eight volumes, 2,000 pages, as part of its $3.7
billion budget proposal for 2000. He said in many cases 90 percent of the budget
requests are unchanged from previous years.
</P>
<P>
	   Dreier got 245 House members, more than half the House, to sign onto a
non-binding resolution that the issue should be taken up this year. The idea has
some powerful backers, including President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, in a speech to the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce on Tuesday, said he was ``very much for biennial budgeting. ... This
year I think we're actually going to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
	   Also endorsing the idea was House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, who
said Tuesday he did not think it could get passed in the second year of a
congressional session.
</P>
<P>
	   Resistance to the biennial budget generally comes from members of the
appropriations committees and others unwilling to surrender their annual shot at
influencing federal spending.
</P>
<P>
	   Critics also argue the biennial budget lacks the flexibility to cope with
sudden economic changes, wars or disasters. Supporters counter that supplemental
budgets can be passed to handle emergencies.
</P>
<P>
	   That support ranges from conservatives to moderates to liberals and ``puts
pressure to bear on the leadership,'' said Rep. Karen McCarthy, D-Mo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1638 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
