<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Passes Bankruptcy Bill  </HEADLINE>
   By MARCY GORDON AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate overwhelmingly passed legislation Wednesday
making it harder for people to sweep away credit card and other debts through
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
	   The 83-14 vote was on a bill that also would raise the hourly minimum wage
to $6.15 over three years, give billions in new tax breaks to small businesses
and increase penalties for powder cocaine crimes. The House last year passed a
similar bill, also with a veto-proof margin, which is limited to bankruptcy
provisions.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This bill will end the free ride for wealthy freeloaders and deadbeats who
walk away from their debts,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate
Judiciary Committee, said before the vote.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill applies a new standard for determining whether people filing for
bankruptcy should be forced to repay their debts under a court-approved
reorganization plan rather than having them abrogated. If a debtor is found to
have sufficient income to repay at least 25 percent of his or her debts over
five years, a reorganization plan generally would be required.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton administration, which supports rewriting the bankruptcy laws in
principle, has criticized both versions because it believes they are too hard on
debtors. The White House also opposes the business tax breaks and wants to see
the minimum wage increase over a shorter period of time.
</P>
<P>
	   House and Senate negotiators now must iron out differences between the two
bills.
</P>
<P>
	   The Senate vote culminated several hours of drama in which Democrats
summoned Vice President Al Gore to break a possible tie vote on an abortion
rights measure attached to the bankruptcy bill. Republicans dropped their
opposition to the amendment upon Gore's arrival at the Capitol; it sailed
through by an 80-17 vote.
</P>
<P>
	   The bankruptcy legislation has been pushed by banks, credit card companies
and retail-business groups. Proponents say the bankruptcy overhaul is needed to
stem abuse by people who can afford to repay their debts.
</P>
<P>
	   They point to the rise in personal bankruptcies of Americans in recent
years, which reached a record 1.4 million in 1998, despite the strong economy,
up more than 300 percent since 1980.
</P>
<P>
	   The rate declined last year, though, as an estimated 112,000 fewer people
received bankruptcy court protection than in 1998. Some consumer advocates have
attributed the decline largely to consumers speeding up repayment of their
credit card debts.
</P>
<P>
	   Consumer groups and other opponents maintain the legislation favors
corporate profits over the needs of families struggling with debt. They insist
that the credit card companies share the blame by flooding consumers with mailed
solicitations to entice them into easy credit.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Senate bankruptcy bill is a triumph for the credit card industry but a
disaster for consumers who responsibly use the bankruptcy system,'' said former
Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, chairman of the Consumer Federation of America.
``It will deny many families in financial crisis a fresh start while spurring
more reckless and irresponsible lending by credit card issuers.''
</P>
<P>
	   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who has taken no position on the
bankruptcy legislation, noted the aggressive marketing of credit cards in his
testimony at the Senate hearing on his renomination last week.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Children, dogs, cats and moose are getting credit cards,'' he told the
Senate Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   The legislation includes a requirement that credit card companies explain to
customers in their monthly statements how long it would take to pay off balances
if they make only the minimum required payments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1657 </TRAILER>
