<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group Aims To Help Disaster Victims  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new coalition of insurance companies, governments,
universities and non-governmental organizations has signed on to a World Bank
effort to try to reduce the cost of natural disasters to developing nations.
</P>
<P>
	   The ``ProVention Consortium,'' officially launched at World Bank
headquarters on Wednesday, aims to help poor countries -- many of which cannot
afford to insure their public buildings -- rebuild their infrastructure after
earthquakes, floods and other kinds of catastrophes, and lessen the impact of
future disasters.
</P>
<P>
	   An estimated 1 billion people worldwide live in shanty towns, which have
substantially higher death tolls from natural catastrophes than the housing
found in industrialized nations, said Alcira Kreimer, a World Bank official who
leads the consortium.
</P>
<P>
	   As a result, said Kreimer, ``Ninety-six percent of deaths from natural
disasters occur in the developing world.''
</P>
<P>
	   Members of the partnership say promoting tougher building codes, mandatory
insurance and more effective land management are some of their main objectives.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of the program, some of the world's largest insurance companies say
they will provide lower-cost insurance for participating nations. Industrialized
nations, such as the United States, Japan and members of the European Union,
have pledged to contribute expertise and funding.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, non-governmental organizations like the Red Cross/Red Crescent
and universities, like the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School, will
work with governments of developing nations to create emergency management plans
in advance of disasters, and to increase public awareness of disaster-related
risks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
