<HEADLINE> U.S. Airmen Patrol Iraq Safely  </HEADLINE>
   By LOUIS MEIXLER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NORTH OF THE TURKISH-IRAQI BORDER (AP) -- Air Force 1st Lt. Chris McCarthy
flashes a thumbs up and pulls his F-15 Eagle away from an aerial refueler and
toward northern Iraq, where he patrols a no-fly zone with heat-seeking missiles
tucked under the wings of his fighter.
</P>
<P>
	   Nearby, other F-15s gulp down a few more gallons of fuel from the tanker and
prepare to prowl the skies of northern Iraq carrying 2,000-pound guided bombs.
Those aircraft will pound any Iraqi anti-aircraft unit that dares threaten
McCarthy or the other men in his Wild Boars squadron.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. airmen have been guarding the no-fly zone over northern Iraq for nearly
a decade. They have flown an average of 500 sorties a month for the past two
years, setting out whenever the weather permits.
</P>
<P>
	   It's a mission that has been largely successful; Iraq rarely flies its
aircraft over the zone and no U.S. aircraft have gone down. U.S. aircraft have
also carried out some 90 strikes against Iraqi anti-aircraft targets during the
past year.
</P>
<P>
	   But it is a strategy fraught with danger.
</P>
<P>
	   Iraqi gunners threaten U.S. aircraft an average of once or twice a week by
opening fire or turning on targeting radar. The latest incident was Monday, when
Iraqi gunners fired artillery at U.S. jets, which responded by striking a site
near Bashiqah, some 250 miles north of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
	   Iraq claims more than 100 civilians have been killed in attacks on Iraqi
anti-aircraft positions, a number the U.S. military says is greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
	   Politically, the patrols seem to have humiliated President Saddam Hussein by
denying him the use of his own airspace, but the Iraqi leader appears to be
firmly in power.
</P>
<P>
	   The patrols have maintained ``a symbolic knife in the back of the dictator
... rather than effecting any great change on the ground,'' said William
Hopkinson of the Royal Institute of International Affairs in London.
</P>
<P>
	   The no-fly zone was set up in 1991 to protect rebellious Iraqi Kurds from
Saddam's forces. A similar zone was set up over southern Iraq a year later and
is also patrolled by U.S. and British aircraft.
</P>
<P>
	   The job of patrolling the zones became far more dangerous in December 1998,
when Iraqi gunners began routinely firing on the American and British jets.
</P>
<P>
	   But pilots say there recently has been a slight decrease in Iraqi attempts
to shoot down planes, a development they say is mostly due to the poor weather.
Iraqi gunners usually don't turn on their radar, which can be instantly detected
by U.S. planes, but fire heavy machine guns or artillery that they aim by sight.
</P>
<P>
	   Although a few British planes fly refueling and reconnaissance missions, the
vast majority of the sorties over the northern zone are flown by Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We just kind of tune out the `It's been going on for 10 years,''' said Lt.
Col. Mark Larson, an F-15 pilot with the Bold Tigers squadron. ``We're focused
on our mission.''
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. pilots try to steer clear of anti-aircraft weapons in civilian areas
and say they only drop precision weapons that are guided to their targets by
lasers or television cameras.
</P>
<P>
	   At one point, pilots aiming at sites in populated areas tried to avoid
civilian casualties by dropping bombs filled with concrete -- meaning they
didn't explode but crushed their targets. Concrete bombs have not been used
since Brig. Gen. Bob DuLaney took command of the northern air patrols in
October, he said. He refused to say why.
</P>
<P>
	   Most pilots are rotated out after 90 days, a move that officers says keeps
morale high. Many are also volunteers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We want to be where the action is,'' said Larson of Mercer Island, Wash.
``We drop bombs back home on the training range, but this is where it happens.''
</P>
<P>
	   He quickly added, however, that ``it would be a different perspective ... if
we were losing jets every day.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCarthy, of Midwest City, Okla., returned home to Incirlik air base in
southern Turkey on Sunday after an uneventful mission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1710 </TRAILER>
