<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that have been moving substantially or trading
heavily today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
	   The automaker named president and chief operating officer G. Richard Wagoner
as chief executive officer. Wagoner's appointment lays the ground for the
upcoming retirement of chairman and CEO John F. Smith Jr.
</P>
<P>
	   The media company earned 20 cents per share in the fourth quarter, easily
beating analysts' estimates of 16 cents per share. Time Warner said stronger
results from cable and publishing offset downturns in music and movies.
</P>
<P>
	   The drug maker posted fourth-quarter earnings of 34 cents per share, up from
28 cents per share in the fourth quarter of 1998. Schering-Plough said worldwide
sales of the company's Claritin allergy medication grew 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said fourth-quarter revenues will miss expectations due to
problems with its sales force. Inso, a maker of multilingual data-access and
electronic publishing software, has retained an adviser to explore options
including a possible sale of the company.
</P>
<P>
	   Coulter Pharmaceutical won a patent for a drug expected to challenge Idec's
antibody Zevalin. The drugs are used to treat non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. Coulter is
jointly developing the drug with SmithKline Beecham.
</P>
<P>
	   The company widened its losses in 1999, losing $3.08 per share compared with
$2.72 per share in 1998. For the fourth quarter, SonoSite lost 38 cents per
share compared with 99 cents per share a year earlier. SonoSite makes ultrasound
systems.
</P>
<P>
	   The company received a U.S. patent for its drug delivery system for a class
of drugs that boosts blood cell counts in patients with cancer and kidney
disease. Patients would inhale the drugs, which are currently used in an
injectable form to treat anemia and depressed white blood cell counts.
</P>
</TEXT>
