<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earnings Rise for Time Warner  </HEADLINE>
    By SETH SUTEL AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Time Warner Inc., the leading media conglomerate that has
agreed to be acquired by America Online Inc., reported higher fourth-quarter
earnings Wednesday as stronger results from cable and publishing offset
downturns in music and movies.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner, whose properties include CNN, Time magazine and the Warner
Brothers film and music studios, earned 20 cents per share, easily beating
analysts estimates of 16 cents per share, according to First Call/Thomson
Financial.
</P>
<P>
	   Earnings before taxes and amortization, a measure of cash flow used by
analysts, jumped 79 percent to $2.45 billion from $1.37 billion. After adjusting
for several one-time gains including a $1 billion profit from the sale of cable
systems, cash flow rose 12 percent, still a healthy advance.
</P>
<P>
	   Net profits were $848 million for the fourth quarter compared to $90 million
a year ago. Per-share figures were 62 cents versus a loss of 17 cents, when
dividend payments of $304 million brought down per-share earnings.
</P>
<P>
	   Fourth-quarter revenues rose 10 percent to $7.99 billion from $7.27 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Most segments of Time Warner's sprawling media empire reported higher
earnings, including Time Inc., which publishes Sports Illustrated, Money,
Fortune and other magazines. Cable networks, which include TNT and TBS, also had
a strong run and HBO made a splash with the hit series "The Sopranos."
</P>
<P>
	   Music continued to be a sore spot for Time Warner. Poor sales at home and
abroad, combined with a downturn at the Columbia House direct marketer, which is
half-owned by Sony, led to a 16 percent drop-off in earnings for the struggling
division.
</P>
<P>
	   Hoping to address its music problem, Time Warner last month announced a deal
to combine its music operations with Britain's EMI, the last remaining
independent music company, to form the industry's largest player. The
combination should lead to cost savings, increased clout with distributors, and
a stronger position in the race to bring music to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner expects its music business to be the first to take full
advantage of the new opportunities in distribution and promotion offered by the
Internet. Unsuccessful in previous efforts to bring its media properties online,
Time Warner is betting that its combination with AOL will help it leapfrog ahead
of competitors like Disney and CBSViacom on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors have been struggling to make sense of the AOL-Time Warner merger,
which brings together a high-flying Internet company with a media conglomerate
firmly rooted in traditional businesses like publishing and broadcasting. AOL
stock, which is being used to acquire Time Warner, has slumped badly since the
deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
	   Both stocks rebounded, however, after the strong earnings report from Time
Warner Wednesday. Time Warner shares rose $7.06 1/4 to $85 in trading at 5:15
p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange, while AOL's rose $5.50 to $60.75, also on
the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner chairman Gerald Levin, speaking to reporters after the earnings
announcement, reaffirmed his commitment to the merger, saying he did not have
"emotional highs and lows" because of the daily stock fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
	   Levin also said there was no chance of a renegotiation of the deal, which
calls for Time Warner shareholders to receive a fixed amount of AOL stock,
making the deal's value subject to AOL share prices. "I'm absolutely convinced
that the deal is structured appropriately," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   At the time the merger was announced Jan. 10, AOL's lofty stock price placed
a value of $166 billion on Time Warner, a huge premium of 71 percent. But the
subsequent decline in AOL's shares make the deal worth $135 billion at current
rates.
</P>
<P>
	   In other parts of Time Warner's media holdings, the only division besides
music to show a decline was the film studio, where earnings edged down 3.5
percent. The company's WB television network, which aims for younger audiences
with shows like "Buffy the Vampire Slayer," edged into the black for the first
time since it was launched in 1995.
</P>
<P>
	   For the full year, cash flow rose 64 percent to $7.33 billion from $4.46
billion a year ago. After adjusting for the cable profit and other one-time
effects, cash flow rose 15 percent for the year. Revenues for 1999 rose 4
percent to $27.33 billion from $26.24 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   On a per-share basis, excluding one-time items, Time Warner earned 39 cents
per share, beating analyst estimates of 36 cents per share. That compared to a
loss of 6 cents per share in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The media conglomerate had net earnings of $1.95 billion compared to $168
million in 1998. The equivalent per-share amounts were $1.42 versus a loss of 31
cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
