<HEADLINE> Schering-Plough Profits Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Schering-Plough said its fourth-quarter profits surged 21
percent, driven by strong sales of the allergy pill Claritin.
</P>
<P>
	   Schering-Plough said Wednesday it earned $506 million, or 34 cents per
share, up from $419 million, or 28 cents per share, in the same period a year
ago. Results beat Wall Street forecasts by a penny, according to First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
	   Sales rose 12 percent to $2.3 billion from $2.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The allergy drug Claritin had a sales increase of 14 percent to $573 million
from $505 million. Claritin, the most heavily advertised prescription drug to
consumers, has been the leading allergy drug for several years.
</P>
<P>
	   Combined sales of Intron A and Rebetron Combination Therapy for hepatitis
rose 37 percent to $297 million from $217 million.
</P>
<P>
	   For all of 1999, the Madison, N.J.-based company said it earned $2.1 billion
or $1.42 per share, up from $1.8 billion or $1.18 per share in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Sales rose 14 percent in 1999 to $9.2 billion from $8.1 billion a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Claritin's 1999 sales rose 18 percent to $2.7 billion from $2.3 billion in
1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of Schering-Plough rose 93 3/4 cents to $60.75 in trading at 5:15
p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
