<HEADLINE> Wahid in Netherlands Amid Protests  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid arrived
in the Netherlands Wednesday on the first official Dutch visit by an Indonesian
head of state in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
	   His two-day trip began as several dozen Indonesian exiles demonstrated
peacefully at Amsterdam's Schiphol Airport, demanding that the president take
action to stop continuing ethnic violence back home.
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid, an Islamic moderate in his fifth month of office, is on a European
tour to bolster foreign political support for his reform policies and attract
investors to his impoverished country. Arriving at Queen Beatrix's royal palace
in The Hague Wednesday evening for a ceremonial welcome, Wahid declined to
comment on his decision Monday to fire Security and Political Affairs Minister
Gen. Wiranto.
</P>
<P>
	   Wiranto has refused to step down despite a harsh government report that
linked him to atrocities in East Timor. A state-appointed commission
investigating the conflict found Wiranto and 32 other military leaders
responsible for the slaughter of thousands after the region voted for
independence from Indonesia in August.
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid ordered Wiranto's resignation while in Switzerland Monday, but the
former army chief was seen at regular government meetings the next day.
Wiranto's resistance has created a standoff between Wahid's new reformist
government and the old-style military regime of former president Suharto, under
which Wiranto had significant power.
</P>
<P>
	   While in the Netherlands, Wahid will meet with Prime Minister Wim Kok. He
also hopes to convince former Premier Ruud Lubbers to mediate in the conflict in
Indonesia's eastern Maluku Islands.
</P>
<P>
	   The Netherlands has a large population of people from the islands. They have
held repeated demonstrations against the violence between Christians and Muslims
there, which has cost about 2,000 lives since last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
