<HEADLINE> Kenya Air Black Box Said Located  </HEADLINE>
   By TIM SULLIVAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) -- Ivorian authorities on Wednesday defended their
response to the Atlantic Ocean crash of a Kenya Airways jet carrying 179 people,
while acknowledging that the seaside airport had no rescue boats on hand.
</P>
<P>
	   Some of the 10 survivors clung to bits of wreckage for hours before being
rescued, and at least one swam to shore. Many were saved by volunteers trawling
the waters in their own boats.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, state television reported that the ``black box'' had been
located, but search officials could not immediately be reached for confirmation.
It wasn't clear whether the report referred to the flight data recorder or voice
recorder, both of which could provide insight into the cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
	   The director of the Ivorian civil aviation authority said the country had
responded properly.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I can assure you that all navy and military forces were mobilized within
one-half hour'' of the crash, said Jean Kouassi Abonouan.
</P>
<P>
	   The crash occurred Sunday night about 2 miles off the coast of Abidjan, just
after the Airbus 310 took off, destined for Lagos, Nigeria. One survivor said
more people would have lived if the rescue had come quicker.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The accident happened at night, making the search very difficult, but I
was informed and (rescuers) went to the site as soon as possible,'' Abonouan
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
	   He also conceded that while the plane went down within sight of the airport,
``unfortunately, we had no boats at the airport that could be ready to go to sea
in case of such an accident.''
</P>
<P>
	   He also added at one point: ``You also have to take into account that this
happened on a Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
	   Abonouan said that the country did not have the equipment needed to located
the airplane's flight data recorder and cockpit voice recorder, but that a team
of French specialists were looking for them and the remains of the plane.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier Wednesday, three fire department divers jumped into 80 feet of clear
water about 2 miles off the coast, also trying to locate the plane's wreckage. A
military vessel also took part in the search.
</P>
<P>
	   Kenya also sent 21 divers to assist in the search for bodies, while a barge,
diving gear and hoisting equipment are on the way from Senegal.
</P>
<P>
	   A Kenya Airways flight Wednesday brought scores of relatives from Lagos and
Nairobi to identify the victims. But only 86 bodies had been recovered,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   The airline released a list of 26 victims from the United States, Canada,
United Arab Emirates, Zambia, Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Burkina Faso, Mali,
Nigeria, Congo, Rwanda, India and Ghana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
