<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford, UPS Join Forces  </HEADLINE>
    By JOSEPH ALTMAN Jr. Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. said Wednesday it will work with a
subsidiary of United Parcel Service to nearly cut in half the time it takes
vehicles to move from the assembly line to the dealership.
</P>
<P>
	   Eventually, the partnership with UPS Logistics Group will let car buyers use
a Web site to track a new vehicle through the delivery process the way they now
can track packages.
</P>
<P>
	   When it is implemented in March, the system should reduce the time the
average new vehicle is in transit from 14 or 15 days to about eight or nine,
said Frank Taylor, Ford's vice president of material, planning and logistics.
</P>
<P>
	   "Speed is a competitive advantage," Taylor said. "If you look at what
happens in the total network today, it's lacking speed, and it's lacking
precision, and the customer needs both. Speed and precision will drive cost
down."
</P>
<P>
	   UPS Logistics will revamp Ford's network of road and rail carriers and add a
high-tech information system that makes it easy to track individual vehicles,
said Dan DiMaggio, chief executive officer of UPS Logistics Group.
</P>
<P>
	   "When the optimized network is complete, Ford customers can expect the same
on-time delivery reliability they get from UPS," DiMaggio said.
</P>
<P>
	   Pete Greiner, chairman of the National Auto Dealer Association's Ford
committee, said the ability to tell customers exactly when their vehicle will be
available will become a selling point.
</P>
<P>
	   "It provides an unprecedented connection between Ford, its dealers and its
customers," said Greiner, who owns a Casper, Wyo., dealership. "The ability to
have our customers instantly informed is definitely a competitive advantage, and
any reduction in delivery time is a plus."
</P>
<P>
	   Automakers have reported problems with rail delivery in recent months, due
to congestion on some routes.
</P>
<P>
	   The new system may not completely solve all transportation problems, but,
"even with logistical problems of delivering, whether that's by rail or truck,
to provide consumers information about where their car is in transit is an
absolute home run," Greiner said.
</P>
<P>
	   Industry analyst Alan Baum said the initiative by Ford, the world's No. 2
automaker, is a combination of streamlining internal operations and providing
better customer service.
</P>
<P>
	   "UPS has made a business of this kind of work," said Baum, of IRN Inc. "It's
significant because they (Ford) are looking -- like lots of companies are
looking -- at the service aspect to try to improve revenues."
</P>
<P>
	   The partnership continues the trend of making more of the car-buying process
accessible through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford in January partnered with Yahoo! to create a Web site where vehicle
owners can get access to owner guides, recall notifications, Ford Credit account
information and personalized maintenance logs.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford said it will begin the program with Ford, Lincoln and Mercury cars in
the western and southwestern United States. The system will cover all of North
America when it is fully functional in late 2001, according to Taylor. Ford then
plans to expand the system to its Volvo, Mazda and Jaguar lines.
</P>
<P>
	   Between 100-150 UPS employees and 30-50 Ford employees will manage the
system together, and UPS will be compensated based on how it helps Ford meet its
speed and efficiency goals, Taylor said. Detailed terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
	   On the New York Stock Exchange, Ford fell $1.18 3/4 to $48.62 1/2 a share in
trading at 5:15 p.m. Wednesday, while UPS fell $2.75 to $58.62 1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1756 </TRAILER>
