<HEADLINE> Stocks End Mixed; Dow Down 37.85  </HEADLINE>
    By EILEEN GLANTON AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks struggled to a mixed finish Wednesday after the
Federal Reserve's widely expected interest rate increase did little to calm
turbulent U.S. financial markets.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 37.85 to close at 11,003.20. The
blue-chip index rose as much as 60 points in the moments before the Fed released
its decision, then bobbed between positive and negative territory for much of
the rest of the session.
</P>
<P>
	   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 slipped 0.16 to 1,409.12, and the Nasdaq composite
index rose 21.98 to 4,073.96.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks gave up early gains after the Fed said it was raising its target for
the federal funds rate -- the interest banks charge one another on overnight
loans -- to 5.75 percent from 5.50 percent. Several commercial banks quickly
announced that they, too, would boost borrowing costs.
</P>
<P>
	   Higher rates can cut into corporate profits by making it more difficult for
companies to borrow money to finance growth.
</P>
<P>
	   As a result, investors Wednesday turned to the companies that are advancing
quickly enough to outrun rising rates, said A. Marshall Acuff Jr., equity
strategist at Salomon Smith Barney. For the most part, that meant technology
stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   "Investors are crowding into shares of the companies that they believe will
continue to grow earnings, despite the Fed's tightening of interest rates,"
Acuff said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hewlett-Packard rose 4 3/4 to 110 9/16 and IBM rose 3 1/2, the strongest of
the Dow components.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Nasdaq, Yahoo! rose 10 5/8 to 328 and Qualcomm rose 6 to 142 1/16.
Turnstone Systems, which makes equipment that allows for high-speed Internet
connections over telephone wires, soared 50 1/4 to 147 1/4 in its second day of
trading following its initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
	   "Those are the companies that are driving innovation and improving
productivity for the U.S. work force," said Philip S. Dow, director of equity
strategy at Dain Rauscher Wessels in Minneapolis. "They're helping this economic
expansion continue."
</P>
<P>
	   Trading remained highly volatile as investors worried that Wednesday's rate
increase might be the first of several this year. In a statement explaining its
decision, the Fed said it remains worried that the rapidly growing economy
"could foster inflationary imbalances that would undermine the economy's record
economic expansion."
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed imposed three quarter-percentage point increases in 1999 in its bid
to keep inflation under control, and has suggested it will continue raising
rates until it sees tangible evidence of a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
	   "The market knows that the Fed is in a gradual tightening mode," said Acuff.
"As long as that's in place, it will be hard to advance significantly."
</P>
<P>
	   Financial services companies like American Express, which fell 4 13/16 to
164 13/16, are especially vulnerable, analysts said. Lending volume typically
slides when interest rates are rising.
</P>
<P>
	   While interest rate concerns dominated Wall Street, corporate news also
drove trading Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   General Motors fell 3 7/8 to 81 3/8 after the company named president and
chief operating officer G. Richard Wagoner as chief executive officer, preparing
GM for the retirement of chairman and CEO John F. Smith Jr.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner soared 7 1/16 to 85 after reporting earnings that beat analysts'
expectations. The strong report also lifted shares of America Online, which has
stumbled since it announced plans to acquire Time Warner last month. AOL rose 5
1/4 to 60 1/2.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange. NYSE composite volume totaled 1.24 billion shares, compared with
1.17 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 6.14 to 509.89.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.8 percent. Germany's Xetra DAX
index was up 1.7 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.2 percent, and France's
CAC-40 was up 3.0 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
