<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Times Mirror Profits Drop  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Times Mirror Co., publisher of the Los Angeles Times and
The Baltimore Sun, reported lower fourth-quarter operating profits Wednesday,
despite an increase in revenues, due to higher debt service costs.
</P>
<P>
	   Times Mirror earned $67.5 million from continuing operations, or $1.03 per
share, matching the forecasts of analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson
Financial.
</P>
<P>
	   That compared to $75.5 million, or 87 cents per share, in the same period a
year ago. The per-share amounts rose because of a decline in the amount of
shares outstanding and lower preferred dividend payments.
</P>
<P>
	   The results did not include a gain in the year-ago quarter of $232.6 million
on the sale of the company's medical publishing operations or other one-time
items. Including the items, net profits were $67.9 million in the fourth quarter
compared to $246.3 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Revenues rose 12 percent to $836.6 million in the quarter compared to $750.1
million in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Newspaper publishing, which makes up the bulk of the company's business, had
a 15 percent gain in operating profit during the quarter thanks to strong gains
in advertising and lower costs for newsprint.
</P>
<P>
	   Interest expenses rose during the quarter because of a higher debt load
incurred because of a recapitalization transaction with the company's largest
shareholders, the Chandler Trusts.
</P>
<P>
	   For the full year, income from continuing operations rose to $248.4 million,
or $3.23 per share, matching analyst expectations. In 1998 the company earned
$246.5 million or $2.59 per share. Including gains from the sale of legal and
medical publishing operations in 1998 and other one-time effects, net income was
$259.1 million in 1999 and $1.42 billion the year before.
</P>
<P>
	   Full-year revenues rose 9 percent to $3.03 billion from $2.78 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Times Mirror's newspapers include Newsday, The Hartford Courant and The
Advocate of Stamford, Conn. It also publishes several magazines including Field
&AMP; Stream and Popular Science. Times Mirror has agreed to sell The Sporting
News.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
