<HEADLINE> IHS Files for Chapter 11  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SPARKS, Md. (AP) -- Integrated Health Services, Inc. has filed for federal
Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection and arranged for financing to keep its 400
nursing homes and other facilities operating.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said the filing was made to allow normal operations of its
long-term care facilities and other operations to continue.
</P>
<P>
	   IHS operates about 1,600 post-acute care facililties, including about 400
nursing homes nationwide. The company's services also include home respiratory
services, subacute care, long-term care and contract rehabilitation services.
</P>
<P>
	   To ensure that the company has enough capital to continue business
operations, IHS has arranged for up to $300 million in financing from Citibank.
</P>
<P>
	   "The dramatic impact of the implementation of the 1997 Balanced Budget Act
on our revenues and cash flow severely impacted the company's ability to service
our current capital structure," said Robert N. Elkins, chairman and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
	   "We believe we are taking the appropriate steps to assure that we emerge
from the reorganization process with a sound capital structure. During this
process, we will not lose sight of our core mission of providing quality patient
care."
</P>
<P>
	   The filling was made in the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Wilmington, Del.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
