<HEADLINE> Bertelsmann Wants To Top Music Cos.  </HEADLINE>
    By HANS GREIMEL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The drive to make Bertelsmann AG the world's No.
1 player in the music industry is still alive, the company said Wednesday amid
increased speculation that it is weighing a partnership with Sony Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   Bertelsmann chief executive Thomas Middelhoff said last month he wanted to
make the German media conglomerate the world leader in music by the end of the
year. But that was before the music industry was surprised last month by the
acquisition by Time Warner of British music company EMI Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
	   That merger would produce the world's No. 1 music group, just ahead of
Seagram's Universal Music, and create a music megahouse representing 2,500
performers, including names like the Rolling Stones, Spice Girls, Eric Clapton
and Madonna.
</P>
<P>
	   With Bertelsmann now in fourth place, Middelhoff has stepped up the campaign
to build his company -- even opening the door for a possible linkup with the
Japanese electronics and entertainment company Sony.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the company could be interested in a partnership with Sony and was
also considering various ventures for Internet music distribution, according to
reports in The Wall Street Journal and The Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
	   Company spokesman Oliver Herrgesell denied Wednesday that Bertelsmann was in
negotiations with any other record label but reiterated that "it is still our
goal to be the world leader by year's end."
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement late Wednesday, Sony also denied that its entertainment
businesses were in play.
</P>
<P>
	   "There has been much unfounded speculation in the press in recent weeks
about Sony's plans for its entertainment assets," said Sony president and chief
executive Nobuyuki Idei. "We want to be very clear in stating that our
entertainment businesses, Sony Music Entertainment and Sony Pictures
Entertainment, are not for sale."
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts say a full merger with Sony would be unlikely because it would give
the combined company nearly 30 percent of the world's music market. Universal
and Timer Warner-EMI have each just around 25 percent, and regulators usually
balk at approving mergers that push market shares above that level.
</P>
<P>
	   Together, the world's top four music houses -- including Time Warner-EMI as
one entity -- control about 80 percent of the global market.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, there are plenty of ways for companies to cooperate and cut costs,
such as sharing CD manufacturing and splitting distribution.
</P>
<P>
	   "The only place the music industry competes is in signing and promoting
acts," said Paul Richards, a music industry analyst with WestLB Panmure in
London. "Everything else is open."
</P>
<P>
	   And open is a good way to describe the music entertainment industry right
now, he added.
</P>
<P>
	   "After the Time Warner-EMI merger, the obvious question facing Bertelsmann
and everybody else is how to respond to the competitive threat," he said, adding
closer cooperation between Bertelsmann and Sony would be one means of defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1814 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
