<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Try To Overturn FEC Ruling  </HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN D. SALANT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Democratic National Committee has sued the Federal
Election Commission over the agency's decision to drop an investigation of
foreign donations to the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
	   At issue is a $2.1 million donation in 1994 to the Republican National
Committee's National Policy Forum from a Hong Kong businessman, Ambrous Young.
The contribution was solicited by then-party chairman Haley Barbour.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal law prohibits contributions from foreign nationals.
</P>
<P>
	   The forum used $1.6 million of the funds to pay off a loan from the RNC,
which, in turn, spent the funds to help the GOP in the 1994 elections. The
National Policy Forum eventually defaulted on the loan.
</P>
<P>
	   Acting on a complaint by the Democratic Party, the FEC's general counsel,
Lawrence Noble, concluded in September: ``Both Mr. Barbour and the RNC knew the
foreign source of the security for the loan, and that the known purpose of
seeking repayment in 1994 was to make funds available to the RNC for the
upcoming elections.''
</P>
<P>
	   Noble's office recommended the commission proceed with the investigation.
But the six-member commission deadlocked along party lines, 3-3, and dropped the
case, according to records in the case made public Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic officials, in their suit filed Friday in U.S. District Court in
Washington, want a judge to force the FEC to act.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Before the Republican Party and the leading Republican presidential
candidates start throwing stones about campaign finance reform and foreign
contributions, they had better make sure their own house is in order,'' DNC
National Chairman Joe Andrew said.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal Election Commission spokeswoman Kelly Huff said the agency could not
comment because the matter is in litigation.
</P>
<P>
	   Republican National Committee spokesman Mike Collins said the lawsuit was an
attempt to divert attention from Democratic fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Democrats have no shortage lawyers willing to file frivolous
lawsuits,'' Collins said. ``This is basically a subterfuge to cover up what Sen.
Bob Kerrey of Nebraska said was an embarrassing effort to violate the law in
1996 by the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Democratic National Committee was forced to return millions of dollars
in campaign contributions after the 1996 elections amid allegations that they
came from foreign sources, which is illegal.
</P>
<P>
	   But Democrats on the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee, which
investigated campaign fund raising during the 1996 elections, said Barbour
``intentionally solicited'' foreign money. Barbour told the committee that he
did not know the money came from overseas, but Democrats called his testimony
``not credible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1815 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain N.H. Win Revives TV Concerns  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID BAUDER AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- John McCain's easy New Hampshire primary victory has
revived a concern for television networks about whether to report how an
election is going while people still have the chance to vote.
</P>
<P>
	   Hours before voting was done Tuesday, exit polls had revealed McCain was
headed for a surprisingly big victory over GOP frontrunner George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   The three cable news networks declared McCain the winner at 7 p.m. EST, when
most -- although not all -- of New Hampshire's polls closed.
</P>
<P>
	   Fox News Channel's Brit Hume had reported at 6 p.m. that "all signs point to
a very good night for John McCain." Much of the next hour included discussion on
the implications of a big McCain victory.
</P>
<P>
	   "To do otherwise would have taken us completely off what we knew to be the
news," Hume said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Early victory projections were a big issue in the 1980s, when West Coast
politicians worried that network calls on a presidential race would keep voters
at home.
</P>
<P>
	   Research on whether this was true has been inconclusive, said Tom
Rosensteil, director of the Project for Excellence in Journalism. But networks
have generally waited in recent elections to avoid alienating voters, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   With two new cable news networks this presidential election and more refined
exit polling, there's a greater temptation to break ranks, said Kathleen
Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg School for Public Communication at the
University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead of a competition among news networks on who could call the race
first, "we got into a race of who could insinuate first," Jamieson said.
</P>
<P>
	   On the "CBS Evening News" at 6:30 p.m., Dan Rather said there were "early
indications of possible surprises" in both parties. Correspondent Bob Schieffer
said exit polls concluded New Hampshire Republicans gave McCain an "astonishing"
70 percent favorability rating.
</P>
<P>
	   David Bloom said on NBC's "Nightly News" that "the McCain camp is brimming
with confidence tonight, and Bush aides appear resigned to defeat."
</P>
<P>
	   ABC waited until 8 p.m., when all New Hampshire polls had closed, to declare
McCain the victor. But Peter Jennings reported 90 minutes earlier that it
appeared to be a good day for McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   Rosensteil said that television commentators "pushed the semantic envelope
more last night than I have seen in a long time."
</P>
<P>
	   "We would argue that it's not semantic," ABC spokeswoman Eileen Murphy said.
"You're not projecting a winner."
</P>
<P>
	   CNN's 7 p.m. declaration made for one awkward moment: a half-hour later,
Judy Woodruff noted on the air that polls hadn't closed everywhere in New
Hampshire and that voters should exercise their rights.
</P>
<P>
	   Before 7 p.m., CNN political director Tom Hannon said he emphasized to
correspondents not to let what they knew from exit polls seep into their
reporting.
</P>
<P>
	   "The risk of influencing, potentially, the outcome of an election is a
weighty responsibility, so we kind of play it straight," Hannon said. "I
recognize that it's a difficult issue. I'm not trying to imply any criticism of
the other networks."
</P>
<P>
	   Hume said Fox tries to strike a balance.
</P>
<P>
	   "You don't want it to be a situation where the media and all the players
know what the score is and the spectators don't," he said. "There's nothing more
journalistically suspect to me than a bunch of journalists working with a head
full of knowledge and not telling the audience."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
