<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Soar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Long-term Treasury prices soared Wednesday after the
government said it would sell fewer bonds as part of the Clinton
administration's long-term plan to pay off the national debt.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of the 30-year Treasury shot up 1 27/32 points, or $18.43 3/4 per
$1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, fell to
6.28 percent from late Tuesday's 6.42 percent. As recently as Jan. 18, the yield
on the long-term bond was at a 2 1/2-year high of 6.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Wednesday's rally, one of the biggest in the past year, was sparked by news
that the U.S. Treasury would sell $10 billion in new 30-year bonds, $12 billion
of five-year notes and $10 billion of 10-year notes at next week's refunding
auction. That's $5 billion less than the market had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
	   Further, the Treasury also said it would auction off fewer 30-year bonds at
its next auction in August.
</P>
<P>
	   Reducing bond sales is part of the federal government's strategy to make use
of the huge budget surplus to pay down the national debt. Treasury officials
said they plan to buy back up to $30 billion of the national debt this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Bond prices were little affected by the Federal Reserve's widely anticipated
decision Wednesday to raise interest rates by a quarter-point, its fourth hike
since June.
</P>
<P>
	   Prices of short-term Treasury securities were down 1/32 to up 1/32 point,
while intermediate maturities rose 3/32 to 5/16 point, according to Bridge
Telerate news service.
</P>
<P>
	   In other trading Wednesday, yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.63
percent, with a discount rate falling 0.06 percentage point from late Tuesday to
5.47 percent. Six-month yields were 5.89 percent with a discount falling 0.05
percentage point to 5.64 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   One-year yields finished at 6.19 percent, with the discount dropping 0.10
percentage point from Tuesday's auction to 5.81 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the discount is the
interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, fell
to 5.50 percent from 5.87 1/2 percent late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bond Buyer index of municipal bonds rose  1/8 point to 91 7/16. The
yield was 6.30 percent, down from Tuesday's 6.31 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1825 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
