<HEADLINE> Dominica Leader To Form Coalition  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSEAU, Dominica (AP) -- Dominica's new leader said Wednesday he will form a
ruling coalition with conservatives after winning elections on the Caribbean
island.
</P>
<P>
	   The announcement by Rosie Douglas comes after a final recount Tuesday night
confirmed that his Labor Party had won 10 of the 21 parliamentary seats in
Monday's polls. The United Workers' Party of outgoing Prime Minister Edison
James garnered just nine seats.
</P>
<P>
	   With the conservative Dominica Freedom Party's two seats, Douglas' coalition
will have a majority in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The two parties will work together in offering the country a new
direction,'' Douglas said at a joint news conference with Freedom Party leader
Charles Savarin.
</P>
<P>
	   He has said one of his first acts will be to suspend an ``economic
citizenship'' program selling passports to foreigners, some of whom the Labor
Party has said are criminals.
</P>
<P>
	   Douglas said he would give the Freedom Party two Cabinet posts and two seats
in the 10-member senate. The outgoing government had 11 ministers holding 27
posts.
</P>
<P>
	   Savarin said he and the Labor Party had fought the election to remove the
Union Workers' Party from office and that the next objective was to
``restructure the economy, restructure the society and create a better life for
the people.''
</P>
<P>
	   Douglas also has promised to set up an inquiry into alleged corruption in
the UWP government.
</P>
<P>
	   Douglas will be sworn in as prime minister on Thursday, and is expected to
announce his Cabinet afterward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
