<HEADLINE> Storks Threaten Spanish Church  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALARAZ, Spain (AP) -- A 16th-century church here has become popular with the
local stork population -- so popular, in fact, that the birds' 440-pound nests
may bring the roof down.
</P>
<P>
	   Marceliano Iglesias, the mayor of Alaraz, told the news agency Efe that he
has counted 23 nests atop the Gothic edifice.
</P>
<P>
	   The church suffered previous stork damage that cost $150,000 in repairs in
1997. Now the birds are back and mating with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
	   ``At this rate we will have to build them a new church in two years,'' said
Iglesias.
</P>
<P>
	   Alaraz is a town of some 700 people in Spain's central Salamanca province.
</P>
</TEXT>
