<HEADLINE> 7 Charged in Milosevic Murder Plot  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A military court in Belgrade indicted seven
people Wednesday for allegedly planning to assassinate President Slobodan
Milosevic and two others.
</P>
<P>
	   The seven -- one army lieutenant and six civilians -- are charged with
plotting to kill Milosevic, Yugoslav Army Gen. Nebojsa Pavkovic and opposition
leader Vuk Draskovic, the independent Beta news agency reported. The defendants
also allegedly conspired to form a terrorist organization called the Serbian
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
	   A lawyer for the seven denied all the charges.
</P>
<P>
	   The lieutenant was identified as Boban Gajic, 26, of Belgrade. The other
defendants are from the central town of Krusevac. All seven were arrested two
months ago and remain in custody pending trial in military court in the southern
city of Nis.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities say the group collected arms, equipment and propaganda material
for an all-out Serb uprising against Milosevic. Also, a statement attributed to
the group claimed responsibility for a November traffic accident in which
Draskovic was injured and four associates were killed.
</P>
<P>
	   Draskovic, though, has blamed the government for that incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
