<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AmeriServe Clients Report Shortages  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID KOENIG AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DALLAS (AP) -- A federal bankruptcy court Wednesday approved a $150 million
line of credit from Burger King Corp. and Tricon Global Restaurants Inc. to keep
a financially troubled Texas food distributor in business.
</P>
<P>
	   The distributor, AmeriServe Food Distribution Inc., had missed payments to
suppliers, resulting in spot shortages of food and paper products at some
restaurants and causing some Burger King franchisees to ask about switching to
other distributors.
</P>
<P>
	   Addison, Texas-based AmeriServe, one of the nation's largest food
distributors, filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection from creditors on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The $150 million line of credit is good for six months, giving AmeriServe
time to negotiate with debtor-in-possession lenders for more conventional
financing, said Matthew Kleiman, an attorney representing the company.
</P>
<P>
	   "The court's decision puts the company in great position because we'll be
able to continue normal operations and make a seamless transition to
reorganization," Kleiman said after the bankruptcy court proceeding before
Bankruptcy Court Judge Peter Walsh in Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
	   Privately held AmeriServe has not disclosed its current assets and
liabilities but reported in November assets of less than $2 billion and
liabilities and long-term debt of slightly more than $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts say AmeriServe grew too quickly, particularly with two large
acquisitions in 1997 and 1998, and could not service its debt.
</P>
<P>
	   The line of credit was offered Tuesday by two of the distributor's biggest
customers. Burger King and Tricon Global Restaurants Inc., the parent of Pizza
Hut, KFC and Taco Bell, comprise about two-thirds of AmeriServe's accounts.
</P>
<P>
	   AmeriServe's problems paying its bills have led to breaks in the chain that
supplies goods to restaurants. Food and paper-goods suppliers send their
products to distribution centers, which fulfill orders from restaurants.
</P>
<P>
	   "Some suppliers have been reluctant to ship anything to us because they are
owed money by AmeriServe," said Robert Doughty, a spokesman for Miami-based
Burger King Corp. Wednesday's temporary financing should give suppliers
confidence that they will be paid for current shipments, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Doughty said AmeriServe supplies 75 percent of the 8,100 U.S. Burger Kings,
and there have been "some minor, spot outages around the country."
</P>
<P>
	   Some franchisees have asked about switching distributors, Doughty said. He
said the company advises the franchises, who typically sign long-term contracts
with distributors, to consult a lawyer before attempting to get out of a
contract involving a company that is going through bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials at AmeriServe did not respond to several calls seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 1855 </TRAILER>
