<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wednesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Note: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Students Rally for Tuition Freezes
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Rachelle Sauve draped a thick, metal chain around her neck as
she joined a national day of student protests against tuition increases and
crippling debt.
</P>
<P>
	   It symbolized how getting an education will tie her down, the second-year
Carleton University student said.
</P>
<P>
	   Less than two years into a bachelor's degree in human rights and women's
studies, 21-year-old Sauve says she's $27,000 in debt.
</P>
<P>
	   That figure will mushroom to at least $50,000 by graduation, she expects.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The loan system is not working,'' she said on Parliament Hill as about
1,500 students and other supporters waved placards and called for lower tuition,
more grants and a $3.7-billion federal reinvestment in higher education.
</P>
<P>
	   The full day of protest was to push for renewed education and social
spending in the federal budget expected this month.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
Health Care Tops Premiers' Agenda at Quebec City Meeting
</P>
<P>
	   QUEBEC (AP) -- The healthcare system is expected to get top treatment as
premiers gather to set their priorities for the coming federal budget.
</P>
<P>
	   The premiers, who meet in Quebec City today, are expected to ask Prime
Minister Jean Chretien's government to put several billion dollars back into the
healthcare system.
</P>
<P>
	   The four Atlantic premiers -- Prince Edward Island's Pat Binns, Nova
Scotia's John Hamm, New Brunswick's Bernard Lord and Newfoundland's Brian Tobin
-- say Ottawa has no other choice if it wants to preserve the system.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The federal government has already made clear its intention to introduce
tax cuts in the upcoming budget,'' they said in a statement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The time has come for it to complete the balance through a recommitment of
funding for health care.''
</P>
<P>
	   Tobin said the system needs an immediate injection of $3.5 billion to $4.5
billion -- part of it in cash and part to be used in consultation with the
provinces and healthcare professionals.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
Commons Finance Committee Report Holds Clues to Federal Budget
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Personal income tax cuts, a major infrastructure program and
changes to RRSPs are all recommendations from the Commons finance committee that
will likely be part of this month's federal budget.
</P>
<P>
	   While budget details are leaking out, more clues can be found in recent
recommendations of the powerful, all-party committee.
</P>
<P>
	   The committee's record for seeing its advice translated into budget measures
is good, observers say.
</P>
<P>
	   Critics complain that's because Finance Minister Paul Martin has too much
influence over the Liberal-dominated committee.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think the finance committee in its recent incarnation is more frequently
than not a branch plant of Paul Martin's office,'' said Scott Brison,
Conservative finance critic and a committee member.
</P>
<P>
	   Brison would like even deeper tax cuts than the $46 billion over five years
recommended by the committee.
</P>
<P>
	    Parliament To Pass Bill Outlawing Police Chases
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Criminals who spark high-speed police chases could soon face
severe jail sentences if Parliament manages to achieve consensus Monday in its
first debate of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   The proposed law, which has been delayed since December, could be on its way
to the Senate for final approval if all five parties agree to pass it when
Parliament reopens Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   But Dan McTeague, an Ontario Liberal MP who introduced the bill in October,
says he can't be sure everyone is on side.
</P>
<P>
	   Since the government's introduction of a bill spelling out terms for Quebec
separation in December, the Bloc Quebecois promised to do what it could in the
Commons to delay the clarity bill's passage.
</P>
<P>
	   McTeague tried to get consensus on the high-speed chase bill before
Parliament broke for the holidays but failed because of the Bloc's tactics.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Their tactic was to simply delay, stall, obfuscate at any cost,'' he said
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
	   A spokeswoman for the Bloc said while the party does plan to slow things
down in the House, it will be picking its battles.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bloc has no official position on the police chase bill, she said, and
will allow its members a free vote Monday.
</P>
<P>
	    Study: Many Canadians Have Trouble Coping With Stress
</P>
<P>
	   TORONTO (AP) -- Workplaces are a major source of stress, but most Canadians
feel supported on the job, the Heart and Stroke Foundation said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Doctors with the foundation released a report card evaluating how 1,751
Canadians over age 30 felt about stress and their coping abilities.
</P>
<P>
	   Of those surveyed, 43 per cent said they felt overwhelmed by work, family or
financial responsibilities, while only one-quarter felt they coped well with
stress.
</P>
<P>
	   Eighty per cent, however, realized prolonged stress can harm the heart.
</P>
<P>
	   Stress can be healthy, spurring us to do more than we think we can. But too
much -- as a result of major transitions such as a job change, illness or new
baby, or a combination of many factors -- can leave one feeling overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
	   But are Canadians more stressed out than, say, 30 years ago, before
technology, shifting family structures and workplace uncertainty were issues?
</P>
<P>
	   Dr. Paul Dorian, a cardiologist at St. Michael's Hospital in Toronto, says
it's hard to tell because there's little previous research for comparison
purposes.
</P>
<P>
	    Ontario Seeks To Fix Violent Offender Rule Glitch
</P>
<P>
	   TORONTO (AP) -- Ottawa must move quickly to fix a ``defect'' in the Criminal
Code that allows violent offenders to serve their jail terms in the community,
says Ontario's attorney general.
</P>
<P>
	   Jim Flaherty wrote a letter Wednesday urging federal Justice Minister Anne
McLellan to curb the use of so-called conditional sentences as soon as
Parliament resumes next week.
</P>
<P>
	   The letter follows a Supreme Court ruling Monday that upheld the use of
conditional sentences, despite the efforts of Ottawa and the provinces to have
certain violent crimes declared ineligible.
</P>
<P>
	   Conditional sentences allow offenders facing jail terms of less than two
years to serve their time in the community rather than behind bars, under
certain limitations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We consider that's a discretion that ought not to be extended to the
courts, quite frankly,'' Flaherty said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Society demands, and the people of Ontario demand, that serious and
violent crime not be dealt with by way of conditional sentences. That's the
position I've taken.''
</P>
<P>
	   The high court noted in its ruling that the Criminal Code itself could
easily stipulate that violent crimes like sexual assault and manslaughter be
excluded from conditional sentence eligibility, but does not.
</P>
<P>
	   Ottawa introduced conditional sentences in 1996 to give judges an
alternative to jail for offenders not considered a threat to society. Judges can
also impose any conditions they see fit.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Expert: Black Babies Not Getting Proper AIDS Treatment
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Many babies of African and Caribbean descent in Canada are
not getting the treatment which could prevent them from developing AIDS, says an
expert who works with immigrants and refugees.
</P>
<P>
	   AIDS rates among the black immigrant population are far above the national
average, said Esther Tharao of Women's Health in Women's Hands, a Toronto health
agency.
</P>
<P>
	   She said black people in Ontario account for 12 per cent of the province's
HIV cases, a highly disproportionate share, and the situation is similar in
Montreal and Vancouver. ``For African and Caribbean women it is a big problem.''
</P>
<P>
	   A 1996 study found that 70 per cent of HIV-infected children at the Toronto
Hospital for Sick Children were born to mothers of African descent, Tharao told
a briefing Wednesday on children affected by AIDS.
</P>
<P>
	   A child born to an HIV-infected mother has an approximately 30 per cent
chance of being infected. This can be reduced to eight per cent with AZT
treatment shortly after birth.
</P>
</TEXT>
