<HEADLINE> Primary Calendar at a Glance  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Key dates in the 2000 presidential campaign, including the total number of
delegates at stake, and an analysis of campaign strategies. The Republican
figures include total delegates to be allocated. The Democratic totals include
unpledged and official delegates who are not bound by election results.
</P>
<P>
	    Feb. 8
</P>
<P>
	   Delaware GOP primary
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 12
</P>
<P>
	   Analysis: Texas Gov. George W. Bush and conservative Steve Forbes both need
a win here to recover from their drubbing in New Hampshire's primary. Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, who won Tuesday's contest, has not campaigned in Delaware,
but can still receive votes.
</P>
<P>
	    Feb. 19
</P>
<P>
	   South Carolina GOP primary
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 37
</P>
<P>
	   Analysis: McCain's long-odds strategy to defeat Bush for the nomination
includes a victory in South Carolina. The staunchly conservative state has
tended to favor establishment candidates such as Bush and has supported his
father in the past.
</P>
<P>
	    Feb. 22
</P>
<P>
	   Arizona GOP primary
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 30
</P>
<P>
	   Analysis: McCain's home state, but Bush was holding his own in polls before
New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   Michigan GOP primary
</P>
<P>
	   Michigan Republican delegates: 58
</P>
<P>
	   Analysis: Another political ``firewall'' for Bush, with fellow governor John
Engler in the Texan's camp.
</P>
<P>
	    Feb. 26
</P>
<P>
	   American Samoa GOP caucus
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 4
</P>
<P>
	   Guam GOP caucus
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 4
</P>
<P>
	   Virgin Islands GOP caucus
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 4
</P>
<P>
	    Feb. 27
</P>
<P>
	   Puerto Rico GOP primary
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 14
</P>
<P>
	    Feb. 29
</P>
<P>
	   North Dakota GOP caucus
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 19
</P>
<P>
	   Virginia GOP primary
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 56
</P>
<P>
	   Analysis: Gov. Jim Gilmore promises to bail out Bush if McCain or Forbes are
still threats.
</P>
<P>
	   Washington GOP primary
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 12 (of 37)
</P>
<P>
	   Analysis: McCain strategists say the state, like New Hampshire, favors
self-styled independents like their boss.
</P>
