	    March 7
</P>
<P>
	   California primaries
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic delegates: 434
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 162
</P>
<P>
	   Analysis: Bush and Gore lead by wide margins in polls. This also is a
critical general election state. Gov. Gray Davis backs Gore over Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   Connecticut primaries
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic delegates: 67
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 25
</P>
<P>
	   Analysis: Democrat Bradley, a former senator from New Jersey, led Gore in
pre-New Hampshire polls in this state, part of his strategy to sweep Northeast
contests. Bush leads in most March 7 GOP polls, but the surveys mean little
until the field shakes out during earlier contests.
</P>
<P>
	   Georgia primaries
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic delegates: 92
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 54
</P>
<P>
	   Analysis: Gore expects to do particularly well in this state. Blacks, who
tend to back Gore, cast nearly a third of all votes in the Democratic primary
</P>
<P>
	   Hawaii Democratic caucus
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic delegates: 33
</P>
<P>
	   Idaho Democratic caucus
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic delegates: 23
</P>
<P>
	   Maine primaries
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic delegates: 32
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 14
</P>
<P>
	   Analysis: An independent-minded state that should favor insurgent Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   Maryland primaries
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic delegates: 92
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 31
</P>
<P>
	   Analysis: Gore held slight lead in polls and is backed by the state's
Democratic governor, but Bradley could fare well. No recent polls offer
guidance.
</P>
<P>
	   Massachusetts primaries
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic delegates: 118
</P>
<P>
	   Republican delegates: 37
</P>
<P>
	   Analysis: Gore has the backing of Sen. Ted Kennedy and a slight lead in
pre-New Hampshire polls, but the state's liberal Democrats could fall for
Bradley.
