<HEADLINE> Sharif Said To Want Plane Diverted  </HEADLINE>
   By ZAHID HUSSAIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) -- Hours before he was ousted in a coup, Nawaz Sharif
ordered the state-run airline to refuse landing rights to a plane carrying the
army chief, a witness at the former premier's trial testified Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors charge that Sharif ordered the airliner turned away as part of a
plot to kill Gen. Pervez Musharraf, who led the military coup when the plane
eventually landed.
</P>
<P>
	   Sharif was arrested and charged with hijacking, attempted murder, kidnapping
and terrorism. Three of the charges carry either the death penalty or life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
	   Sharif has denied the allegations and has demanded the restoration of his
civilian government, which was elected in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Shahnawaz Dara, director of flight operations for Pakistan International
Airlines, testified Wednesday that Sharif gave the order Oct. 12 as the jet was
approached Karachi's airport en route from Sri Lanka. The plane was carrying 188
passengers.
</P>
<P>
	   Dara said he received a call from the airline's chairman, telling him that
the flight should be diverted to Muscat, Oman. But the plane didn't have enough
fuel to make the trip, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Shortly afterward, military officers seized the airport's control tower and
allowed the plane to land. Military officials said the plane had been circling
the airport and had only minutes of fuel remaining when it touched down.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial began a week ago. The prosecution plans to call dozens of
witnesses in the case, and the trial is expected to last several weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
