<DOCNO> APW20000202.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Die As Bus Carrying Serbs Attacked  </HEADLINE>
   By ELENA BECATOROS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KOSOVKSA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A U.N. bus carrying 49 Serb civilians
was hit by a rocket Wednesday in Kosovo, U.N. officials said. Two people died
and three were injured.
</P>
<P>
	   The white bus bore markings of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. It
was struck on a hilly road near the village of Cubreljas, about 10 miles from
the city of Kosovska Mitrovica, said Olivier Saint Leger, a press officer for
Kosovo's multinational peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
	   Afterwards, snow near the bus was stained with blood. Shattered glass lay on
the side of the road, while the vehicle, with twisted metal protruding from its
right side, was parked a few yards further on.
</P>
<P>
	   The dead were an elderly man and an elderly woman, Saint Leger said. The
injured were taken to a military hospital in Kosovska Mitrovica, where one was
reported in very serious condition.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I cannot overemphasize how shocked and deeply disturbed I am by the
terrorist incident that happened today,'' said peacekeeper commander Gen. Klaus
Reinhardt. ``The deplorable attack ... was a deliberate attempt to kill and maim
defenseless Serbian men, women and children.''
</P>
<P>
	   Reinhardt said the peacekeeping force ``will conduct a full and thorough
investigation with the aim of bringing the terrorists to justice.''
</P>
<P>
	   The bus was taking Serbs from Kosovska Mitrovica to the nearby village of
Banja. Two French armored vehicles from the Kosovo multinational force were
acting as escorts, but the bus was driving through dense fog at the time.
</P>
<P>
	   The rocket or rockets were apparently fired from a gully by the side of the
road.
</P>
<P>
	   The attack comes as ethnic tensions remain high in Kosovo. Authorities say
many ethnic Albanians were killed by Serb forces during Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's 18-month crackdown against separatists here. After NATO
bombing forced the Serb troops to withdraw last spring, ethnic Albanians began
attacking Serbs as revenge.
</P>
<P>
	   No information was released about possible suspects. But a senior State
Department official traveling with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on her
flight home from Croatia said the attack appeared to be ``an ethnically
motivated crime.''
</P>
<P>
	   Albright issued a statement saying: ``This reprehensible act only serves to
prolong the cycle of violence that has plagued Kosovo. We call on the leadership
of the Kosovar Albanian community to join us in condemning this attack.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2036 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earlier Alaska Air Problems Reported  </HEADLINE>
   By LINDA DEUTSCH AP Special Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PORT HUENEME, Calif. (AP) -- Investigators said Wednesday they are looking
into a report that the Alaska Airlines jetliner that plunged into the Pacific
Ocean had problems with the aircraft's tail controls in a flight hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   The airline reiterated its statement that it knew of no previous problems
with the plane.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities also began analyzing recordings of the pilots' conversations
with a Seattle maintenance crew made while the pilots tried to control the plane
in the terrifying moments before it nose dived into the sea Monday, killing all
88 aboard.
</P>
<P>
	   The plane crashed after a pilot reported problems with the horizontal
stabilizer, a wing-like structure on the tail that keeps the plane flying level.
</P>
<P>
	   The first of three remote-operated underwater vehicles was set to dive
Wednesday night to 700 feet beneath the Pacific in search of Flight 261's
``black box'' voice and flight data recorders.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier dozens of ships were ordered to abandon the search for survivors and
shift their focus to recovering flight recorders and wreckage that could explain
why the plane went down about 10 miles off the Southern California coast.
</P>
<P>
	   The search was officially called off over the protest of some family members
who held out hope that some of the plane's passengers and crew might still be
alive in the chilly waters of the Santa Barbara Channel.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have far exceeded our estimate of survivability,'' Coast Guard Vice
Adm. Thomas Collins said.
</P>
<P>
	   On shore, investigators interviewed airline employees about the report that
a different crew of pilots complained of problems with the aircraft's horizontal
stabilizer as they headed toward Puerto Vallarta, Mexico, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The jetliner crashed hours later on the return trip to San Francisco and
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
	   The Seattle Times reported Wednesday that the crew had reported problems
with the stabilizer on the southbound leg of the flight.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We don't know if it's true, we are investigating that,'' John
Hammerschmidt, a member of the NTSB, said of the report.
</P>
<P>
	   When asked about the report, airline spokesman Jack Evans in Seattle again
said there had been no previous problem with the plane.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We stand by what we said earlier this week which is that we're not aware
of any maintenance anomalies with this aircraft,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
	   The pilots who reported the problem will be interviewed, an anonymous source
familiar with the investigation told the Times.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile a jammed horizontal stabilizer forced an American Airlines MD-80
to land in Phoenix 20 minutes after takeoff Wednesday, said Phil Frame, a
spokesman for the NTSB in Washington. The plane, which had been headed toward
Dallas, is part of the same series of aircraft as the Alaska MD-83 that crashed.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal investigators were having the flight data recorder from the American
Airlines plane sent to them.
</P>
<P>
	   Frame knew of no link between the American Airlines incident and the crash
investigation, but ``it may have piqued their interest.''
</P>
<P>
	   Investigators interviewed pilots who were flying in the area of the crash
and may have seen Flight 261 go down.
</P>
<P>
	   The audio tapes of the pilots and the Seattle maintenance crew apparently
capture an exchange that took place as the pilots tried to troubleshoot what was
going wrong, Jim Hall, chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board,
said on morning talk shows.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Obviously these pilots were struggling to maintain control of this
aircraft for a significant period of time. It's going to be very important to
this investigation,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
	   The tape was handed over Tuesday to federal investigators by Alaska Airlines
in Washington, D.C., Hall said.
</P>
<P>
	   The search for survivors had gone on for 41 hours and included dozens of
Coast Guard, Navy and civilian ships, boats and aircraft that combed a
1,100-square-mile area.
</P>
<P>
	   About 80 family members had arrived at an assistance center in the
Renaissance Hotel in Los Angeles by Tuesday night and another 50 were expected
to show up Wednesday, said Chris Thomas, an American Red Cross volunteer.
</P>
<P>
	   Many of those who had arrived at the hotel remained in a state of shock, he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I just want to know that our family members didn't suffer and that it was
just fast,'' said Janis Ost Ford, whose brother Bob Ost was on board the plane.
</P>
<P>
	   Alaska Airlines and Red Cross officials planned to take family members to
the coast near the crash site Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They will be able to deal with the emotional responses; they'll be able to
see the search-and-rescue recovery process,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
	   As the operation entered a third day, several ships used for salvage arrived
at Port Hueneme, including Navy vessels equipped with advanced side-scan sonar
that can be used to map debris on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
	   The gear will be used to locate the wreckage of the airplane and the flight
recorders. Searchers on Tuesday said they had detected pinging from one or both
of the devices.
</P>
<P>
	   The wreckage is about 700 feet down. Divers cannot operate below about 300
feet, so the search will be carried out by three unmanned vehicles. One, the
Scorpio, was at the crash site aboard the ship Kellie Chouest, and was scheduled
to dive Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
	   If one of the plane's two recorders -- the flight data recorder -- was
programmed to monitor the stabilizer, it might reveal the condition of the
stabilizer when the jet went down. If not, officials would have to deduce what
happened by studying how other systems performed before the crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2045 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Tied to Terrorist Case Released  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- A Moroccan man who was being held as a material witness --
reportedly in an alleged terrorist conspiracy case -- was released Wednesday,
the U.S. Attorney's Office said.
</P>
<P>
	   Youssef Karroum, 35, of Surrey, British Columbia, was detained last week
after attempting to cross from Canada into the United States at Blaine, a border
crossing about 100 miles north of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Magistrate Judge David E. Wilson had ordered Karroum held without bail
as a material witness. All records connected to his arrest, detention and
release are under seal, and no further details will be released, said Harold
Malkin, spokesman for U.S. Attorney Kate Pflaumer.
</P>
<P>
	   The Seattle Times, citing an unidentified Justice Department source,
reported that Karroum's arrest was related to the case of Ahmed Ressam, the
Algerian arrested Dec. 14 in Port Angeles and charged with trying to smuggle a
trunkful of explosives into Washington state.
</P>
<P>
	   Karroum's attorney, Gene Grantham, said his client was not a suspect in the
explosives case.
</P>
<P>
	   On Jan. 20, a federal grand jury returned a nine-count indictment charging
Ressam with conspiring ``to destroy or damage structures, conveyances or other
real or personal property within the United States.'' Ressam has pleaded
innocent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2048 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primaries Lure Record Numbers  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID TIRRELL-WYSOCKI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Good weather and hard-fought races produced a record
number of votes for New Hampshire's presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
	   The numbers shocked Secretary of State William Gardner, even though he had
predicted a record turnout.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Holy mackerel,'' he said as the total printed out on his adding machine.
He punched in the numbers again to make sure, and they were the same.
</P>
<P>
	   In the Republican primary, 238,606 votes were cast for president; Gardner
had predicted 191,000. In the Democratic primary, 154,639 votes were cast;
Gardner had anticipated 60,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I said it would be a record, but this is a record record,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gardner predicted 351,000 of the state's 738,000 registered voters would
cast ballots. His tally Wednesday was 393,245, surpassing by 10 percent the
previous record of 348,303 set in 1992.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Republican side, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., defeated Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, 49 percent to 30 percent. They were followed by Steve Forbes at
13 percent, Alan Keyes with 6 percent and Gary Bauer at 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Elizabeth Dole, who dropped out of the race before any ballots were cast,
attracted 231 write-in votes on the GOP ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   In the Democratic race, Vice President Al Gore defeated Bill Bradley, 50
percent to 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Interestingly, 3,320 Democrats wrote in McCain and 998 wrote in Forbes.
Another 827 picked Bush on the Democratic ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   Among Republicans, 1,025 wrote in Bradley and 1,155 wrote in Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   Gardner could not estimate a percentage of turnout because some people vote
only for vice president and others take a ballot and don't vote at all, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   New Hampshire lets undeclared voters cast ballots in either party primary.
Gardner expected 81,000 independents to vote Tuesday, but there was no
indication of how many voted, or in which primary.
</P>
<P>
	   Shortly before the primary, the state had 198,000 registered Democrats,
266,000 Republicans and 275,000 independents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2051 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hundreds Vote for Fringe Candidates  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID TIRRELL-WYSOCKI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Hundreds of New Hampshire voters turned away from
McCain, Bush, Bradley and Gore to vote for Buckley, Peters, Harder and Capalbo
in Tuesday's presidential primaries -- some of the 22 lesser-known candidates on
the ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   The winner among the fringe candidates was Democrat Charles Buckley of
Whitefield, N.H., who finished third, behind Al Gore and Bill Bradley, with 322
votes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``At the risk of sounding obnoxious and self-righteous, I am more qualified
than Gore and Bradley,'' Buckley, 58, said before the vote. ``I'm a former clerk
of court, former probation officer, former teacher, former bank examiner, a
trial lawyer for 30 years, a Navy veteran.''
</P>
<P>
	   Among Buckley's ideas was easing the shortage of affordable housing in the
East by irrigating vast tracts of land in the West and building more houses
there.
</P>
<P>
	   Heather Anne Harder, a lecturer, university professor and businesswoman from
Crown Point, Ind., was second among the lesser-known Democrats with 192 votes.
</P>
<P>
	   She is continuing her campaign to give power back to states and individuals
by simplifying laws and holding national referendums to let Americans speak
directly on key issues.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a life commitment for me -- not a whim, a quick fix or 15 minutes
of fame,'' she said Wednesday, as she prepared to move her operation from snowy
New Hampshire to sunny Arizona.
</P>
<P>
	   Harder attracted 369 votes in 1996 and suggested fewer people voted for the
lesser-known candidates this time ``because of the tight race between the big
boys.''
</P>
<P>
	   In the last primary, with an uncontested Democratic race, the lesser-known
candidates attracted nearly 4,000 votes. The total this year was just less than
1,100.
</P>
<P>
	   Jeffrey Peters, of Jackson, N.H., won 156 Democratic votes as part of his
plan to attract enough attention to become a coalition candidate for We the
People, representing nonvoters, independents and disillusioned Democrats and
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   On the GOP ballot, Dorian Yeager of Rye, N.H., picked up 98 Republican votes
to make her first among the lesser-known GOP candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   The ballot also included:
</P>
<P>
	   -- Democrat Mark Greenstein of Culver City, Calif., who got 75 votes.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Democrat Jim Taylor of St. Paul, Minn., who got 87 votes.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Republican Kenneth Capalbo, of Wakefield, R.I., with 51 votes.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Republican Thomas Oyler of Wichita, Kan., with 14 votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2052 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0275 </DOCNO>
