<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Details Airline Delays  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID HO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- America West airlines had the worst on-time arrival
record and highest rate of customer complaints of any major U.S. carrier last
year, according to a Transportation Department survey.
</P>
<P>
	   The most punctual airline of 1999 was TWA, with close to 81 percent of its
flights delivering passengers on time, according to the Air Travel Consumer
Report issued Wednesday. The Transportation Department report does not specify
the reasons for flight delays, which might be caused by severe weather, air
traffic control decisions, passenger problems or equipment failures.
</P>
<P>
	   The report showed that more than 30 percent of Phoenix-based America West's
flights arrived late in 1999. The airline also had the most arrival delays in
1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Doing only slightly better than America West in terms of flight delays was
Alaska Airlines, with 29 percent of its flights coming late. U.S. Airways
rounded out the bottom three with close to 29 percent of its flights being
tardy.
</P>
<P>
	   America West also had the highest rate of passenger complaints, most of them
relating to cancellations, delays and poor customer service. The airline drew
nearly four consumer complaints for every 100,000 passenger boardings. That
compared with an average of roughly 2 1/2 complaints per 100,000 passengers for
all 10 major airlines.
</P>
<P>
	   America West spokeswoman Patty Nowack said she couldn't comment until
reviewing the report.
</P>
<P>
	   Overall, the number of passenger complaints to the 10 major airlines more
than doubled last year, ballooning to 13,709 complaints in 1999 from only 5,808
in 1998. This increase occurred at a time when passenger boardings increased by
about 16 million between 1998 and 1999, a growth of about 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   David Stempler, president of the Air Travelers Association, a passenger
advocacy group, said a record numbers of passengers has led to full planes and
strained airline resources.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The irritation level is just a lot higher,'' he said. ``We keep demanding
of the airlines that they provide low fares and one of the ways they do that is
by tightening up the seat rows, by reducing the amount of food, by reducing the
number of flight attendants. Then we complain about it.''
</P>
<P>
	   In January, the Transportation Department's inspector general began
accepting complaints from consumers concerned about airline overbooking and
ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
	   Concerning reports of mishandled bags, United Airlines had the worst record,
with 543,491 complaints.
</P>
<P>
	   Southwest Airlines had the lowest rate of complaints overall last year, with
only 0.4 for every 100,000 passenger boardings. The airline also had the lowest
percentage of reports concerning bags that were damaged, lost or delayed. In
1998, Southwest had been the on-time winner but slipped to No. 2 with an 80
percent on-time record last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Northwest came in third with almost 80 percent on-time arrivals, a big
improvement for the airline, which had ranked No. 9 in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2057 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
