<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Warns of New Arms Race  </HEADLINE>
   By EDITH M. LEDERER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Calling efforts toward global disarmament deplorable,
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan warned Wednesday that ``a dangerous new arms
race looms on the horizon.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``If we are even to dream of a world free of nuclear weapons by the end of
the 21st century, we should start taking new and effective measures of nuclear
disarmament and nonproliferation right now,'' he said in a speech to the U.N.
Advisory Board on Disarmament Matters.
</P>
<P>
	   Annan urged the world's main disarmament forum -- the Geneva-based
Conference on Disarmament -- to show ``far greater urgency and flexibility in
its search for a compromise on its program of work.''
</P>
<P>
	   The 66-nation conference held an eight-month session which ended in
December. But it was so divided over calls for nuclear disarmament that it was
unable even to agree on an agenda for negotiations during the session.
</P>
<P>
	   In the past, the conference has negotiated bans on chemical weapons and
nuclear test explosions. But it has now been deadlocked for more than two years
between countries that demand a sweeping approach to nuclear disarmament and
nuclear powers that insist on sticking to a step-by-step process.
</P>
<P>
	   ``More countries have nuclear-weapon capability than ever before,'' the
secretary-general said.
</P>
<P>
	   He cited ``a discouraging list'' of nuclear disarmament measures that are
stalled and initiatives that haven't gotten off the ground. Among them:
</P>
<P>
	   --The START II accord, signed in 1993 and ratified by the U.S. Senate in
1996, was intended to halve U.S. and Russian nuclear arsenals to 3,000-3,500
warheads each. But Russia's parliament has balked at ratifying the accord.
</P>
<P>
	   --Passage of START II would clear the way for a proposed START III treaty,
which could reduce the sides' nuclear arsenals to as few as 2,000 warheads each.
But Moscow won't consider further cuts unless the United States backs down on
its plans to amend the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty to build defenses against
possible limited missile attacks. Russia views the plan as a threat to its own
security.
</P>
<P>
	   --The nuclear test ban treaty, championed by the United States, was rejected
by the U.S. Senate in October, and negotiations in the Conference on Disarmament
on a treaty banning the production of plutonium and highly enriched uranium used
to make nuclear weapons have not even begun, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
	   Annan's comments come less than three months before a scheduled conference
to review the 186-nation Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty. The treaty, signed in
1970, commits nuclear countries to work for disarmament and non-nuclear
countries to refrain from developing their own arsenals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2102 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
