<DOCNO> APW20000202.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Okla. Evolution Disclaimer Rejected  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Oklahoma's attorney general ruled Wednesday that a
state committee had no authority to require that biology textbooks carry a
disclaimer saying evolution is a ``controversial theory.''
</P>
<P>
	   The disclaimer provoked criticism from education groups, scientists and even
some religious groups.
</P>
<P>
	   In a nine-page opinion, Attorney General Drew Edmondson said the State
Textbook Committee has a constitutional duty to prepare multiple textbook lists
but lacks authority to add statements or pronouncements.
</P>
<P>
	   The disclaimer approved by the committee for all new biology books stated
that evolution is a ``controversial theory'' that can refer ``to the unproven
belief that random, undirected forces produced a world of living things.'' It
was unanimously adopted Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
	   Committee member John Dickmann, who introduced the disclaimer, has said it
was added because biology texts do not devote enough space to alternate
explanations of how life began. He did not return a telephone call to his home
by The Associated Press Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The disclaimer was identical to one that was added last year to textbooks in
Alabama. Kansas' board of education also removed evolution from state-mandated
tests, resulting in an avalanche of state and national criticism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
