<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain: More Than POW in Ads  </HEADLINE>
   By EUN-KYUNG KIM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- He has a millionaire wife and a penchant for telling
jokes, some of them off-color. He has admitted to adultery and relishes tales
about his rebellious days as a Navy cadet. And he was labeled a carpetbagger
long before being tagged as a maverick politician who tells it like it is.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. John Sydney McCain, the landslide victor of New Hampshire's GOP
presidential primary, is more than the POW hero portrayed in his television
campaign commercials, videotapes and a recent book he wrote about himself and
his namesakes.
</P>
<P>
	   Thanks to his rapport with reporters, particularly those traveling with him
on his ``Straight Talk Express'' campaign bus, elements of the Arizona senator's
blunt, loose-talking personality and his bawdy sense of humor are claiming more
attention as well. And with it, closer scrutiny on his open-book life.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has long been a darling of the national media because of his
willingness to buck the party line on such issues as overhauling federal
campaign finance laws and pressing for passage of anti-tobacco legislation. His
penchant for rankling the party leadership led to the maverick reputation that
McCain wears as a badge of honor.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I get in trouble all the time. I will continue to get in trouble,'' McCain
said early in the campaign. ``I say what's on my mind to the frustration of my
campaign people.''
</P>
<P>
	   Other components of McCain's bad-boy image come from his days at the U.S.
Naval Academy, where he piled up demerits and led a group of troublemaker
midshipmen who dubbed themselves, ``the Bad Bunch.'' McCain, the son and
grandson of Navy admirals, ended up graduating fifth from the bottom, a fact he
discloses, smugly, during interviews.
</P>
<P>
	   But he redeemed his dismal military beginnings through 5 1/2 years spent in
a Vietnam prisoner-of-war camp, where he endured long periods of solitary
confinement and regular beatings for displaying what his captors said was ``a
bad attitude.''
</P>
<P>
	   He has been married for nearly two decades to Cindy Hensley, the millionaire
daughter of an Arizona beer distributor. Together, they have four children, the
oldest one a 15-year-old daughter whom McCain escorted to last year's MTV Video
Music Awards.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has three grown children from his first wife, Carol, whom he divorced
shortly before remarrying.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Let me say that I am responsible for the breakup of my first marriage,''
said McCain, who has made no secret of his post-Vietnam womanizing.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's first election was in 1982, when he won a seat in the House of
Representatives. The former military brat had dismissed opponents who labeled
him a carpetbagger by telling them, ``the place I lived longest in my life was
Hanoi.''
</P>
<P>
	   But being a media darling hasn't prevented McCain from receiving his share
of bad publicity. His most notable notoriety came during the ``the Keating
Five'' scandal, when he and four other senators were accused of improperly
intervening with federal banking regulators to help Charles Keating, a wealthy
developer who owned a failing savings and loan -- and occasionally loaned his
Caribbean vacation home to the senator.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain eventually was cleared of any impropriety -- other than for ``showing
poor judgment'' -- but has said the episode ``will probably be on my
tombstone.''
</P>
<P>
	   He has a simple damage control strategy: reveal everything.
</P>
<P>
	   After coming under fire recently for letters pressing federal regulators to
act in cases involving campaign donors, McCain's campaign staff made public
hundreds of letters to various agencies over the last several years. He is
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, and argued that it was the everyday
business of Congress to prod the government to act. ``I was doing my job ...,''
McCain said at the time.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain also has been criticized for an explosive temper that supposedly has
led him to tell off Senate colleagues and storm out of hearing rooms. And then
there are the off-color jokes that often land him in water as hot as his temper.
</P>
<P>
	   He has told reporters about referring to the ``Leisure World'' senior
citizens home as ``Seizure World,'' and quipped that ``the nice thing about
Alzheimer's (disease) is you get to hide your own Easter eggs.'' And a joke, at
a GOP fund-raiser, about Chelsea Clinton had him apologizing to President
Clinton days afterward. McCain later said he deeply regretted the ``insensitive
and stupid and cruel'' attempt at humor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2105 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
