<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capt. Claims Innocence in Oil Spill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- The captain of an oil tanker that split in two off France's
western coast last month told reporters Wednesday that he is not to blame for
the spill that is still soiling beaches.
</P>
<P>
	   Karun Mathur, an Indian citizen, is under formal investigation for maritime
pollution and placing others in danger in the Dec. 12 spill. He is forbidden
from leaving France.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm not guilty of the sinking and I congratulate myself for saving my
crew,'' Mathur said Wednesday in his first meeting with reporters since the
spill.
</P>
<P>
	   ``As far as I knew the boat was safe,'' he said. ``But it's not my duty to
check.''
</P>
<P>
	   The aging Maltese-registered tanker Mathur was piloting, the ``Erika,''
spilled 3 million gallons of thick, gummy fuel into the Atlantic Ocean. The
spill has soiled hundreds of miles of rocky coastline and polluted oyster beds.
</P>
<P>
	   The 24-year-old vessel was transporting oil for Franco-Belgian oil giant
TotalFina from the Netherlands to Italy. The two halves of the vessel, still
underwater, contain about 6 million gallons of heavy oil, and more of it has
been seeping out.
</P>
<P>
	   A preliminary government report said the tanker's structure was probably at
fault. The report also criticized the tanker's owner and an Italian company
responsible for the ship's safety checkups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
