<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tuvalu Recommended for U.N. Seat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- A Security Council committee has recommended U.N.
membership for Tuvalu, but the tiny Pacific island's diplomatic ties to Taiwan
could prove a stumbling block in its effort to become the world body's 189th
member.
</P>
<P>
	   The council's committee on admissions backed Tuvalu in a report circulated
Monday. However, the report noted that China declined to join the recommendation
for reasons it did not reveal.
</P>
<P>
	   China claims Taiwan as a breakaway province with no right to international
recognition.
</P>
<P>
	   As a permanent member of the Security Council, China has the option to veto
Tuvalu's application when it comes before the 15-member council for a vote on
Feb. 17. Last year, Beijing delayed consideration of U.N. membership for the
Pacific island nation of Nauru because of Nauru's diplomatic relations with
Taiwan. The Security Council eventually voted 14-0 to let Nauru join, with China
abstaining.
</P>
<P>
	   Tuvalu is a country of 9,000 people inhabiting nine small coral atolls 620
miles north of Fiji. It has a total land area of 10 square miles. If the
Security Council approves Tuvalu's application, the U.N. General Assembly will
vote in September on whether to accept the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2106 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
