<HEADLINE> Notes, Quotes From Campaign Trail  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Secret Service agents called it unprecedented: a vice
president (or president, for that matter) sitting on a commercial flight,
snoozing like any other New York-to-Washington commuter.
</P>
<P>
	   So it was Wednesday morning on the 9 a.m. shuttle -- US Airways flight 6355
out of LaGuardia -- when Al Gore decided to make a mad dash for Washington and
Air Force Two wasn't ready to go. Gore hurried to Capitol Hill for a
tie-breaking Senate vote that ultimately wasn't needed.
</P>
<P>
	   Flight attendants looked surprised -- routine-weary commuters mostly didn't
notice -- as Gore boarded with his armed Secret Service agents and a military
aide carrying nuclear codes. ``Has anyone ever carried the Football on a
commercial flight?'' one aide wondered, speaking of the locked code box.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore tipped his head against the window to sleep, ignoring the bagel snack
that a flight attendant dropped on his tray. He also seemed blissfully unaware
of the interview with Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush being
broadcast on the cabin's small overhead TVs.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore did wake up in time to bring his seat back and tray table into the
full, upright and locked position.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   BY THE NUMBERS:
</P>
<P>
	   19 -- percentage points separating winner John McCain (49 percent) from Bush
(30 percent) in Tuesday's New Hampshire Republican primary
</P>
<P>
	   4 -- percentage points separating winner Gore (50 percent) from Bill Bradley
(46 percent) in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   VOTER'S VOICE:
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think it's good and bad when you have two strong personalities. It sort
of tears the party apart, but they're both good candidates. I believe our
presidential candidate ought to be a Washington insider because he would know
the ins and outs.'' -- Steve Auerbach, Democrat, at the Stage Deli in New York
City. He was torn between Gore and Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   THIS DATE FOUR YEARS AGO:
</P>
<P>
	   Attacks against publisher Steve Forbes piled up from his GOP presidential
rivals. Lamar Alexander said Forbes couldn't win a mayoral race without his
family's money. ``If his name was Forbes Malcolm, he wouldn't be a serious
candidate for mayor of a city in New Jersey,'' Alexander said in Manchester,
N.H. Phil Gramm cited an editorial Forbes wrote in 1973 in which he supported a
health care plan that called for nationalized insurance run by a federal health
security board.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton campaign consultant Dick Morris leaked internal poll results to an
adviser to Republican Bob Dole, arguing it would be in Dole's interest to cut a
budget deal with the president. Clinton concluded Morris' intentions were
honorable, aides said.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   WEDNESDAY'S ROUNDUP:
</P>
<P>
	   Gore greeted commuters at Grand Central Station in New York but interrupted
his campaign to go to Washington to cast a tie-breaking abortion vote that
became unnecessary. McCain said his win ``interfered with the coronation'' of
Bush. McCain, Bush and Alan Keyes campaigned in South Carolina. Gary Bauer, back
in Virginia, reassessed his candidacy after trailing the GOP field in New
Hampshire. Forbes, third in New Hampshire, spent the day at home in New Jersey
discussing strategy and preparing for a week of campaigning in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley held rallies in Connecticut and New York before flying to San
Francisco. He told supporters in Hartford, Conn., ``the warmups are over, the
national campaign has begun.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   THURSDAY'S TRAIL:
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley campaigns in San Francisco. Gore also is in California before flying
to Washington state for an event in Olympia. McCain and Bush are in South
Carolina, with the governor breaking off for a Detroit event. Forbes is in
Delaware.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
