<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyers: Diallo Shot Without Warning  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM HAYS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Four white New York City policemen accused of killing
an unarmed black man unleashed a 41-shot barrage with no warning and kept firing
as the victim was down on the ground, prosecutors said Wednesday as the
officers' murder trial opened.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They never called out commands like `Stop, police!' or `Don't move!'''
before gunning down Amadou Diallo in an apartment house vestibule in the Bronx,
prosecutor Eric Warner told a jury of four blacks and eight whites.
</P>
<P>
	   The officers -- Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon, Kenneth Boss and Richard
Murphy -- ``acted recklessly and with depraved indifference to Amadou Diallo's
life,'' Warner said. ``For that, they are guilty of murder.''
</P>
<P>
	   The defense in the racially charged case disputed the prosecution's claim
that the shots came without warning.
</P>
<P>
	   The defense attorneys said the officers were forced to make a split-second
decision using rapid-fire weapons. And they portrayed Diallo's Soundview
neighborhood in the Bronx as one of the city's most dangerous sections.
</P>
<P>
	   Diallo, a 22-year-old street vendor from West Africa, was shot 19 times a
year ago by members of an elite street-crime unit looking for violent criminals.
The officers said they thought he was holding a gun; it turned out to be a
wallet.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The officers identified themselves with their shields out, as they are
trained to. Mr. Diallo doesn't listen to their orders to stop, which they are
trained to give,'' defense attorney Bennett Epstein said.
</P>
<P>
	   By the time Diallo turned around, ``he had taken them into the no-man's land
that is every police officer's nightmare,'' Epstein said. Carroll, after
realizing the mistake, tried to resuscitate Diallo, saying, ``Don't die, please
don't die,'' the attorney said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a case about five good men,'' Epstein said. ``One of them was Mr.
Diallo.''
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll, 36, McMellon, 27, Boss, 28, and Murphy, 27, face 25 years to life
in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
	   The shooting touched off protests alleging widespread brutality against
minorities. The trial was moved 150 miles north to Albany after the judge ruled
that the officers couldn't get a fair trial in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
	   In his opening statement, Warner detailed how the 19 bullets tore through
Diallo's vital organs. He alleged many were fired while Diallo was falling down
and on the ground.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense attorney Stephen Worth asserted that the officers were only on trial
``because there was a furor created by people who have their own agendas'' -- an
allusion to activists who say the case exemplifies racism.
</P>
<P>
	   Detective Joseph Flannio, the only witness to testify Wednesday, described
finding the sidewalk, stoop and vestibule where Diallo was shot littered with 41
bullet shells and 27 bullets.
</P>
<P>
	   One bullet had pierced the wall and was found inside Diallo's apartment,
Flannio said. He said four more bullets fell from Diallo's body it was removed.
</P>
<P>
	   Photos of the scene, including ones showing Diallo's body, were passed among
the jurors. None had visible reactions.
</P>
<P>
	   Outside the courtroom, the Rev. Al Sharpton accused Worth of trying to
manipulate white jurors.
</P>
<P>
	   The civil rights leader also complained that the defense gave the impression
that Soundview -- located in a precinct where violent crime has dropped more
than 22 percent in the past two years -- is ``the wild, wild West.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``That's insulting,'' he said. ``It shows why this should have been a Bronx
jury.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
