<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Rise in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese share prices rose sharply in early trading Thursday,
with the planned launch of several large-scale investment trusts buoying market
sentiment. The dollar fell against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 273.38 points, or 1.40
percent, to hit 19,852.29 in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Wednesday, the
average closed up 155.53 points, or 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar was trading at 108.12 yen on the Tokyo foreign exchange market,
down 0.38 yen from Wednesday and below its late New York level of 108.26 yen.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, traders were upbeat about the Nikkei's outlook. The
launch of several large-scale investment trusts over the next few weeks was
expected to draw individual investors into the market, traders said.
</P>
<P>
	   Nomura Asset Management, a subsidiary of Japan's biggest brokerage house,
raised about $7.4 billion on Wednesday, the launch day for its "Big Project-N"
fund.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York on Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 37.85
points, or 0.3 percent, to close at 11,003.20.
</P>
<P>
	   The technology-rich Nasdaq Composite Index rose 21.98 points, or 0.54
percent, to finish at 4073.96.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index was up 14.63 points, or 0.85 percent, at
1,726.49 points. On Wednesday, the index rose 14.71 points, or 0.87 percent, to
1,711.86.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency markets, traders sold the greenback to take profits after buying
up dollars on anticipation of interest rate hikes by the U.S. Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed announced Wednesday it had decided to raise key rates, prompting
investors to cash in on their dollar holdings.
</P>
<P>
	   But traders said the outlook for the U.S. currency remained strong. The
increase in interest rates makes the dollar more attractive to Japanese
investors because it leads to a higher yield on dollar-denominated assets, they
said.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro traded at 105.39 yen early Thursday, above its
level of 104.77 yen late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.8400
from its close at 1.8350 Wednesday. Its price fell 0.05 point to 98.80.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
