<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.H. Margins of Victory Surprising  </HEADLINE>
   By WILL LESTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- If New Hampshire polling was like sports betting, most of
the players would have gotten the winner right but still lost on points.
</P>
<P>
	   Most pollsters picked Vice President Al Gore to win the Democratic primary
and Sen. John McCain to win the Republican contest. But almost nobody
anticipated that McCain would win by 19 percentage points, winning both the
independent and the registered Republican vote. For the Democrats, Gore had
about a four-point margin, close to the margin of several tracking polls just
before Tuesday's primary.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1996, some polls of the Republican race had Bob Dole ahead, and some had
Pat Buchanan ahead. Buchanan eventually won.
</P>
<P>
	   One pollster who came close to the right margins for both of Tuesday's races
was Robin Marra of Franklin Pierce College in Rindge, N.H., a relative newcomer
to the state's intensive polling scene.
</P>
<P>
	   When Marra got his last numbers that showed McCain leading by 11 points, he
shared them with his students and warned them they were out on a limb together.
``We'll all go down together,'' he told them.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Or rise together,'' a cheerful Marra said Wednesday, while scanning his
results. He had seen McCain's momentum building through the final week.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was like a tsunami,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was leading Bush by 30 points among independents in several polls,
but few picked up that he also would win among Republicans. And some felt that
independent turnout would be in the low 20s, hurting McCain's chances.
</P>
<P>
	   Exit polls indicated that turnout for registered independents and those who
weren't registered to vote was well over 30 percent of the total. State election
officials don't expect to have final numbers for about a week.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There was no poll that said McCain would win by 20 points,'' said
Secretary of State Bill Gardner. ``There's a big number of people who wait until
the end to make up their minds. They watched it play out before they made a
decision. That's pretty customary here.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's strong performance among Republicans surprised many pollsters, who
generally agreed he was 30 points ahead among independents.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This Republican electorate is a moderate-to-liberal Republican electorate
and a guy like McCain fits in with that,'' said Andy Smith, director of the
University of New Hampshire's survey research center. ``This was John McCain
territory -- an outsider willing to stand up to the party -- that really helped
him.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's stand on campaign finance reform helped, even though the issue was
not foremost on people's minds, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It made him look like a standup guy who's willing to take the heat and
stand up to his party,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
	   Keating Holland, whose CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll, was one of the first to
show Bush losing ground rapidly, said he noticed McCain steadily improving his
performance among women voters in his tracking poll. McCain, who finished with
about half the total primary vote, got about equal support from men and women in
the primary. Bush had been doing better among women, both nationally and in New
Hampshire, prior to the vote.
</P>
<P>
	   New Hampshire's 275,000 independents are the state's largest voting group
and they can decide on election day which party's primary they want to vote in.
</P>
<P>
	   Pollsters in New Hampshire will have to study their turnout models and
reconsider earlier estimates that independents don't turn out at the rate that
registered party members do, said Smith. ``Historical patterns just got thrown
out the window,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2134 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
