<HEADLINE> Pedophile Ex-priest Goes Free  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAFAYETTE, La. (AP) -- A Roman Catholic priest convicted of widespread child
molestation left jail Wednesday after a judge ruled his detention on a later
charge violated the terms of an earlier plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
	   Gilbert Gauthe, 59, first pleaded guilty in 1985 to 33 charges involving 11
boys, but he admitted that he had molested dozens of others. In exchange for his
guilty plea, prosecutors had given Gauthe immunity from any other charges
involving children molested before 1985.
</P>
<P>
	   He was released in 1995 after serving 10 years of a 20-year sentence. But
Gauthe was arrested two years later, charged with raping a 12-year-old girl in
1982.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, a judge ruled that Gauthe's 1997 arrest and detention pending
trial had violated his earlier plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   The former priest didn't speak to reporters as he stepped into a relative's
car outside jail. He was headed toward Texas, escorted by sheriff's deputies as
security, said his attorney G. Paul Marx.
</P>
<P>
	   When asked if his client planned to sue for false imprisonment, Marx
replied: ``My reading on him is he's real sorry for all the trouble he's caused
in this part of the state for so many years and would just as soon not come back
here.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gauthe is still on seven years probation for fondling a 3-year-old boy in
1996 -- the year after he was released from prison. Gauthe pleaded no contest to
the child injury charge.
</P>
<P>
	   Lafayette Parish District Attorney Mike Harson, who charged Gauthe in 1997,
said prosecutors who negotiated the 1985 agreement never meant for Gauthe to be
let out of prison early.
</P>
<P>
	   State law at the time gave most convicts one day off of their sentences for
every day of good behavior in prison. The law has since been changed to require
sexual or violent offenders to serve 85 percent of their sentences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
