<HEADLINE> Premium Juice Cos. To Merge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    HALF MOON BAY, Calif. (AP) -- Odwalla Inc., the upscale juice company that
survived a lethal E. coli outbreak in 1996, said Wednesday it would merge with
Maine juice company Fresh Samantha Inc., in a stock deal valued at $27 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Odwalla said merging with the East Coast's leading premium juice maker will
strengthen Odwalla's position in that section of the market.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are excited about bringing Fresh Samantha together with Odwalla," said
Stephen Williamson, Odwalla's chairman and CEO. "This combination creates a true
national leader in the fast growing, super premium, refrigerated juice
category."
</P>
<P>
	   Privately owned Fresh Samantha is headquartered in Saco, Maine.
</P>
<P>
	   Doug Levin, the CEO and a founder of Fresh Samantha, will be president of
Odwalla when the merger is complete.
</P>
<P>
	   Three years ago, Odwalla's image was tarnished by a deadly E. coli outbreak
linked to its juice. A Colorado girl died and 66 others were sickened by
bacteria in Odwalla's unpasteurized apple juice.
</P>
<P>
	   The company immediately recalled the juice, but sales plummeted.
</P>
<P>
	   Odwalla now flash pasteurizes its apple juices, a process it said keeps
juices fresher and more nutritious than traditional pasteurization.
</P>
<P>
	   The company that helped establish the premium natural juice and fruit
smoothie category continues to work to regain sales lost to competitors who
grabbed market share while Odwalla was mired in lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
	   Late last year, Odwalla has unveiled a new, slimmer bottle with a screw cap
and a bolder, more colorful label that keeps its juices fresher longer.
</P>
<P>
	   The company also expanded its product line to include energy bars and
dairy-free shakes, a wellness drink loaded with vitamin C and echinacea to fight
colds, and several fruit and vegetable blends.
</P>
<P>
	   While annual sales finally have surpassed peak 1996 levels, Odwalla's stock
remains at less than half of what it traded for before the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of Odwalla, which has its production facilities in Dinuba, Calif.,
were up 25 cents, or nearly 4 percent, Wednesday at $7.12 1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
