<HEADLINE> Cuban: Nun Is Instrument of Exiles  </HEADLINE>
   By ANITA SNOW Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HAVANA (AP) -- A senior Cuban official on Wednesday accused the Roman
Catholic nun involved in last week's meeting between Elian Gonzalez and his
grandmothers of being an ``instrument'' of Miami's anti-communist exile
community.
</P>
<P>
	   That communist officials remained focused on the meeting a full week after
it took place shows the depth of their anger about the way it was handled, as
well as their growing frustration as the international child custody dispute
over the 6-year-old Cuban shipwreck survivor drags into its third month. The
political rhetoric from communist officials has grown especially harsh in recent
days.
</P>
<P>
	   Jeanne O'Laughlin, a nun of the Dominican order, served as ``an instrument''
for anti-Castro exiles during the Jan. 26 meeting at her Miami Beach home, said
Ricardo Alarcon, Fidel Castro's key man on Cuba-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Laughlin said following the meeting that she favors keeping Elian in the
United States with his second cousin partly because the boy ``has transferred
his maternal love to her'' following the loss of his mother. She said the
grandmothers seemed fearful -- apparently of their own government.
</P>
<P>
	   Elian has been at the center of an international custody battle since
shortly after being rescued off the Florida coast on Nov. 25. The boy's mother
and 10 other people died when the boat carrying them from Cuba to the United
States sank.
</P>
<P>
	   Elian's father and grandparents want the child returned to them in Cuba, but
the boy's paternal great-uncle and second cousin are fighting to keep him in the
United States, saying they can give him a better life off the communist island.
</P>
<P>
	   Elian's paternal grandmother, Mariela Quintana, and maternal grandmother,
Raquel Rodriguez, traveled to the United States late last month. Their first
attempt at a meeting with their grandchild failed on Jan. 24, when the
grandmothers refused to meet with the boy at the home of Elian's Miami
relatives, which was surrounded by television cameras and anti-Castro
protesters.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. government ordered the Miami family to hold the meeting at a
neutral site and O'Laughlin, the president of Barry University, offered her
home.
</P>
<P>
	   But speaking Wednesday night during a second consecutive television program
with Elian's grandmothers, Alarcon complained that the reunion was interrupted
numerous times by another nun who brought notes asking that the grandmothers
meet with the Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
	   During the meeting, Elian's second cousin was allowed to stay next door
where she could listen in and later share details about the meeting with Miami's
news media, Alarcon said. Later, O'Laughlin met for dinner with the Miami
relatives and then announced that she thought Elian should stay in the United
States, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Laughlin's behavior ``has nothing to do with Christianity,'' said Alarcon,
president of Cuba's National Assembly and a former ambassador to the United
Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
