<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Tanker Searched for Iraq Oil  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A U.S. Navy ship patrolling the Persian Gulf detained a
Russian tanker Wednesday and was taking oil samples to determine whether it was
carrying Iraqi oil in violation of the U.N. trade embargo, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
	   The USS Monterey stopped the Russian merchant vessel off the coast of the
United Arab Emirates and the captain was cooperating, Defense Department
spokesman P.J. Crowley said. The tanker was traveling away from Iraq, through
the Straits of Hormuz, through which 20 percent of the world's oil passes.
</P>
<P>
	   Crowley did not say if the Pentagon knew where the Russian ship had picked
up the oil.
</P>
<P>
	   A second Pentagon spokesman, Jim Kout, said stopping a Russian ship was
``not new but it is unusual.''
</P>
<P>
	   If the oil is found to have come from Iraq, the boarding party likely would
request permission from an Emirates port to haul the ship to a nearby port and
dispose of the contraband, Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
	   White House National Security Council spokesman David Leavy said U.S.
officials have been communicating with the Russians through normal diplomatic
channels, but they haven't received any kind of protest.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The president made very clear we're going to vigorously enforce the
sanctions,'' Leavy said. ``It is a top priority to us to continue to deny
smuggling opportunities to the Iraqi regime.''
</P>
<P>
	   Iraq has been unable to sell its oil on the open market since sanctions were
imposed after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait. In 1996, the U.N. Security Council
launched the oil-for-food program to allow Iraq to export limited amounts of oil
to buy humanitarian goods for its people.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. military said in October that American sailors had diverted at
least five ships carrying cargo to Iraq after boarding parties had problems
searching for contraband over the past month. The United States and Britain are
the main enforcing parties.
</P>
<P>
	   A military spokesman said at the time that inspectors query ``every ship
that goes into the Gulf'' and board a vessel ``if there is any question about
the cargo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
