<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Jolt Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices ended the Thursday morning session sharply
higher amid hopes that the planned launch of several new investment trust funds
will draw more investors to the market. The dollar fell against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average ended the morning session up
217.45 points, or 1.11 percent, at 19,796.36 points. On Wednesday, the average
closed up 155.53 points, or 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar was trading at 107.98 yen on the Tokyo foreign exchange market,
down 0.52 yen from 108.50 yen of late Wednesday and also below its late New York
level of 108.26 yen.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, optimism about the Nikkei's outlook prevailed ahead of
the launch of several large-scale investment trusts over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders expected the funds to draw more individual investors into the
market.
</P>
<P>
	   But some cautioned that the Nikkei's morning rise was based largely on
market sentiment, rather than any fresh factors.
</P>
<P>
	   "For now, the market is supported merely by investor hopes for good demand
for investment trust funds," said Hidenori Karaki, general manager at Tokyo
Mitsubishi Personal Securities.
</P>
<P>
	   Nomura Asset Management, a subsidiary of Japan's biggest brokerage house,
raised about $7.4 billion on Wednesday, the launch day for its "Big Project-N"
fund.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 37.85 points, or 0.3
percent, to close at 11,003.20. The technology-rich Nasdaq Composite Index rose
21.98 points, or 0.54 percent, to finish at 4073.96.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index was up 13.57 points, or 0.79 percent, at
1,725.43 points. On Wednesday, the index rose 14.71 points, or 0.87 percent, to
1,711.86.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency markets, traders sold the greenback to take profits after buying
up dollars on anticipation of interest rate hikes by the U.S. Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, the Fed announced it had decided to raise key rates, prompting
investors to cash in on their dollar holdings.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders said, however, the outlook for the U.S. currency remained strong.
The increase in interest rates makes the dollar more attractive to Japanese
investors because it leads to a higher yield on dollar-denominated assets, they
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Japanese government officials repeated their concerns about an excessively
strong yen.
</P>
<P>
	   Vice Finance Minister for International Affairs Haruhiko Kuroda told
reporters Thursday morning that the ministry's foreign exchange stance remained
opposed to a higher-valued yen.
</P>
<P>
	   An excessively strong yen hurts export-based Japanese companies, as it
decreases their profitability when dollar earnings are repatriated back into
Japan.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro traded at 105.22 yen early Thursday, above its
level of 104.77 yen late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.8550
from its close at 1.8350 Wednesday. Its price fell 0.17 point to 98.68.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
