<HEADLINE> Orange County Bankruptcy Report OKd  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- A federal judge approved Orange County's final
bankruptcy report on Wednesday, clearing the way for the distribution of $871
million in settlements recovered from Wall Street investment firms.
</P>
<P>
	   The ruling, 3 1/2 years after Orange County emerged from bankruptcy, brings
to an end the $1.64 billion ordeal for most of the schools, cities and special
districts involved in the largest municipal insolvency in U.S. history
</P>
<P>
	   "It's the end of an incredibly successful case that started as a disaster
and has been resolved as successfully as any major bankruptcy case in history
has," said Patrick Shea, an attorney who represented many members of the
investment pool.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge John Ryan approved the report submitted by former
state Treasurer Thomas Hayes, who oversaw the county's litigation against
investment firms held responsible for the for losses, including Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm very happy with the results," Hayes said. "This has got to be one of
the highest collections in the history of the country."
</P>
<P>
	   Although it was unclear when the money would be released, an additional $21
million in interest that was earned while it was held in escrow will also be
distributed.
</P>
<P>
	   A small group of investors turned down an agreement to share in litigation
proceedings with the county, and a trial in their case is set for later this
year in Contra Costa County.
</P>
<P>
	   Orange County emerged from bankruptcy in June 1996 under a recovery plan
that included the sale of $880 million in bonds.
</P>
<P>
	   The bankruptcy came after then-Treasurer Robert L. Citron took a $7 billion
investment pool, borrowed another $14 billion from brokerages and invested
heavily in interest rate-sensitive securities. When the Federal Reserve forced
interest rates sharply higher to curb inflation in 1994, what had been a
spectacularly successful strategy turned sour.
</P>
<P>
	   Citron blamed Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., his chief investment house, accusing it
of failing to disclose risks associated with such investments. Merrill Lynch
officials said they had warned him.
</P>
<P>
	   Citron was forced to resign after revealing the losses. Soon after,
brokerages began liquidating securities they held as collateral, a process that
continued even after the county filed for bankruptcy in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
	   The county sued Merrill Lynch, which agreed to pay more than $450 million to
settle the suit and end a criminal investigation. The county recovered more than
$860 million from a series of lawsuits against brokerage firms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2253 </TRAILER>
