<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.C. State Sen. Indicted for Fraud  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- A Republican state senator faces federal charges of
bank fraud, mail fraud and making a false statement in connection with an
allegedly falsified loan application for his home, the U.S attorney's office
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Charles Tyrone ``Ty'' Courtney said he did nothing wrong and questioned
the timing, just before the March 30 filing deadline for November's election.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It wouldn't matter if he were Joe Blow from Alaska, the timing would have
been the same,'' said U.S. Attorney Rene Josey.
</P>
<P>
	   Courtney said he would suspend himself from the Senate floor temporarily,
but would continue to run his office and planned to run for re-election.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I can tell you from my heart I have never tried to defraud anyone,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   If convicted, Courtney, a 48-year-old lawyer who has served in the Senate
since 1991, could face as much as 30 years in prison and a $1 million fine on
each of the three counts, the U.S. attorney's office said.
</P>
<P>
	   Courtney is accused of telling Carolina First Bank that he was the sole
owner of property to help him secure a $150,000 loan in October 1996, when he
actually was half-owner.
</P>
<P>
	   He also failed to list an outstanding lien of $60,000 on another property,
the indictment said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2255 </TRAILER>
