<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Wednesday, Feb. 2, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Alaska Air Flight Recorder Recovered
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PORT HUENEME, Calif. (AP) -- One of the flight data recorders that could
hold the answer to the cause of Monday's Alaska Airlines crash off the Los
Angeles coast was recovered tonight by an unmanned vehicle. The search for
survivors ended earlier today. Investigators said today they were looking into a
report that the plane had problems with a part of the tail called the horizontal
stabilizer on the flight to Mexico. Records of radio conversations between the
pilots and air traffic controllers showed the crew was struggling with
stabilizer problems before the plane nose-dived into the sea, killing all 88
aboard.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Austria Govt. Decision Delayed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Facing European sanctions and worldwide scorn,
Austria's president on Wednesday delayed approving a new government that
includes Joerg Haider's rightists until leaders of the coalition pledge to
respect democratic values. The outrage over the coalition between Haider's
Freedom Party and the center-right Austrian People's Party was debated in world
capitals. Haider won international notoriety about 10 years ago by praising
Adolf Hitler's "orderly" employment policies. He has since sought repeatedly to
distance himself from those statements.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Moroccan Man Released From Custody
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- A Moroccan man who was being held as a material witness --
reportedly in an alleged terrorist conspiracy case -- was released today, the
U.S. Attorney's Office said. Youssef Karroum, 35, of Surrey, British Columbia,
was detained last week after attempting to cross from Canada into the United
States at Blaine, a border crossing about 100 miles north of Seattle. U.S.
Magistrate Judge David E. Wilson had ordered Karroum held without bail as a
material witness. The Seattle Times, citing an unidentified Justice Department
source, reported that Karroum's arrest was related to the case of Ahmed Ressam,
the Algerian arrested Dec. 14 and charged with trying to smuggle explosives into
Washington state.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senate OKs Minimum Wage Boost
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Teeing up for an election-year fight, the Senate approved
a Republican bill today that would boost the minimum wage by $1 an hour over
three years, a period of time President Clinton and Democrats say is too long to
wait. With many Republicans eager to avoid repeated campaign-season attacks on
the widely popular issue, some increase in the current $5.15 hourly minimum
seems likely to become law before Election Day. But with the White House and
Democrats also objecting to the measure's $18 billion in tax cuts over five
years -- mostly for small business owners -- it is unclear what the final
version will look like.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pfizer, Warner-Lambert Work on Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Pfizer Inc. and Warner-Lambert Co. are working out the
details of a deal that would form the second-largest pharmaceutical maker in the
world, as Pfizer tentatively agreed today to raise its takeover bid to $85
billion, according to two people familiar with the negotiations. The companies
must now placate American Home Products, the losing suitor in a 3-month fight
for control of Warner-Lambert. American Home had signed a $59 million deal in
November to acquire Warner-Lambert before Pfizer trumped the bid.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fed Nudges Interest Rates Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve, still seeking to slow the
supercharged U.S. economy, raised borrowing costs for millions of Americans for
a fourth time since June by pushing a key interest rate up a quarter point to
5.75 percent today. The Fed action to boost its federal funds rate, the interest
that banks charge each other, was quickly followed by announcements from major
banks around the country that they were raising their prime lending rate a
similar quarter point to 8.75 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Jolt Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices ended the Thursday morning session sharply
higher amid hopes that the planned launch of several new investment trust funds
will draw more investors to the market. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock
Average ended the morning session up 217.45 points at 19,796.36 points. On
Wednesday, the average closed up 155.53 points. The Dow Jones industrial average
fell 37.85 to close at 11,003.20 on Wednesday. The Nasdaq was up 21.98 to
4,073.96.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
No. 12 Florida Beats S. Carolina 86-82
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Teddy Dupay had a season-high 20 points tonight,
including a go-ahead four-point play, as No. 12 Florida held off South Carolina
86-82, the Gamecocks' seventh straight loss. Dupay had five of the 10 3-pointers
by the Gators (16-4, 5-2 Southeastern Conference), almost all of them at
critical moments. The biggest for the 5-foot-10 sophomore may have come after
Jamel Bradley's 3-pointer got the Gamecocks (9-12, 1-7) all the way back from an
eight-point deficit to lead 57-56.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS
</P>
