<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Search Continues for Alaska Musher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Three days after rookie dog sled racer Rod Boyce
disappeared in a blizzard, search crews Wednesday still had found no trace of
the 38-year-old or his dogs.
</P>
<P>
	   Boyce, a recreational musher from Two Rivers, was competing for the first
time in the Tustumena 200 Sled Dog Race.
</P>
<P>
	   He was last seen a few minutes after midnight Saturday when he passed a
checkpoint about a quarter of the way along the 200-mile trial. He never made it
to the next checkpoint 18 miles away.
</P>
<P>
	   The path wasn't treacherous, just a straight stretch that rises into the
hills, Alaska State Trooper John Brown said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Ten dogs and a person disappear at once. It seems like we should have seen
something,'' said Sgt. Jim Hibpshman, commander of the trooper post in Homer.
</P>
<P>
	   More than a dozen people on snowmachines searched the surrounding
recreational trails for Boyce on Wednesday, and a state trooper helicopter with
heat-detecting equipment was being sent from Anchorage to scan the area.
</P>
<P>
	   Boyce, the city editor for the Fairbanks Daily News-Miner, had 10 dogs when
he was last seen by race officials. He was carrying all the survival equipment
required in the race, including a heavy sleeping bag and an ax, and he had
enough food for him and the dogs for two days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2303 </TRAILER>
