<DOCNO> APW20000202.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 23:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Veteran AP Writer, Editor Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LIVINGSTON MANOR, N.Y. (AP) -- Lewis A. Head, a longtime Associated Press
reporter and editor in New Jersey and New York, died at age 87 of congestive
heart failure.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was one of those dedicated editors who trained a large army of young
journalists," said Robert A. Dubill, executive editor of USA Today and a former
AP bureau chief in Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
	   Head's wife, Lois Guthrie Head, said he died at his home Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
	   Head was born in Winnipeg, Canada, in 1912 and grew up in Glen Rock, N.J. He
graduated from Lafayette College in 1934. Head worked as a photo editor at The
New York Times from 1936 to 1941 and joined the AP in 1941.
</P>
<P>
	   "Lew turned out to be a delightful writer and a great feature reporter,"
said Bob Haring, a retired executive editor of the Tulsa World who was the AP's
bureau chief in Newark when Head worked there in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
	   Head retired in 1976 after a 35-year career.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to his wife, Head is survived by a daughter, Tamar Losec of Long
Island City, N.Y., and a sister, Jessie Broadfoot of Middletown, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2305 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No. 7 Connecticut 74, Villanova 60  </HEADLINE>
    By KEN BERGER AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Albert Mouring tied his career high with 22 points,
hitting 8-of-9 shots and all four of his 3-pointers as No. 7 Connecticut beat
Villanova 74-60 Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
	   UConn (16-4, 5-3 Big East) won its third straight conference game after an
0-2 start and had a big shot to answer every Villanova run.
</P>
<P>
	   The Wildcats (11-8, 2-5) got 19 points on 8-of-14 shooting from Malik Allen
but got no closer than seven points down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
	   Khalid El-Amin, the Huskies' crafty point guard, played sporadically and
grabbed his stomach while taking himself out of the game several times. He was
healthy enough to score 12 points and hit a 3-pointer to give UConn a 70-60 lead
in the closing minutes when Villanova tried to mount a comeback.
</P>
<P>
	   El-Amin scored 12 points, but had six turnovers and only three assists.
</P>
<P>
	   Souleymane Wane made two free throws to give UConn a 60-47 lead with 12:06
left. Villanova scored the next three baskets -- a one-handed putback slam by
Ricky Wright, a jump-hook by Allen and a dunk by Brooks Sales.
</P>
<P>
	   Mouring stopped the run with a 3-pointer from the corner, ending his perfect
night from beyond the arc and giving UConn a 63-53 lead with 8:17 left.
</P>
<P>
	   Kevin Freeman scored inside, but Sales made a layup and Brian Lynch hit a
3-pointer from the corner to cut it to seven points again, 65-58 with 4:56 left.
</P>
<P>
	   Edmund Saunders hit a tough turnaround jumper, and El-Amin hit a 3-pointer
to make it 70-60 with 4:24 left and shut the door on Villanova.
</P>
<P>
	   El-Amin played hurt in the Huskies' 66-56 victory over Seton Hall on Sunday
after suffering a deep thigh bruise last Thursday against Providence. He was
obviously hobbled, and looked to pass instead of forcing the action and then
made the shot he had to with 3:44 left.
</P>
<P>
	   Gary Buchanan, Villanova's best shooter who averaged 22 points the last two
games, played only nine minutes in the first half and heard a mouthful from
coach Steve Lappas when he went to the bench. He finished 3-for-10 for seven
points.
</P>
<P>
	   UConn made nine straight field goals in the final 8:02 of the first half to
take a 46-34 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2306 </TRAILER>
