<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Charles L. Byars
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Charles L. Byars, who held top editing jobs at three
South Carolina daily newspapers, died Tuesday of cancer. He was 71.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1959, Byars started his own newspaper. He and Jack Brewster published the
weekly Ninety Six News. The paper was merged into The (Greenwood) Index-Journal
in 1961. At the larger paper he was a wire editor, sports editor, news editor
and managing editor.
</P>
<P>
	   He left Greenwood for the now-defunct evening daily The Columbia Record and
worked as assistant city editor, news editor, assistant managing editor and
managing editor before moving over to The Record's sister paper and larger
daily, The State.
</P>
<P>
	   He was a member of Associated Press Managing Editors, a national group of
editors promoting continuing studies of news publishing, a member of the South
Carolina Press Association and a former president of the South Carolina
Associated Press News Council.
</P>
<P>
	   Byars retired in May 1988 after eight years as managing editor of The
(Columbia) State, which featured his column of homespun musings titled
``Personally.''
Mary Cantwell
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mary Cantwell, who wrote essays, books and editorials for
The New York Times, died Tuesday of cancer. She was 69.
</P>
<P>
	   Cantwell, a member of the Times editorial board for 16 years, often wrote
about issues affecting women.
</P>
<P>
	   She wrote three books -- ``American Girl'' (1992), ``Manhattan, When I Was
Young'' (1995) ``Speaking with Strangers'' in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Cantwell started as a copy editor at Mademoiselle magazine, where she worked
for 23 years, nine of them at managing editor and features editor.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1980, she was invited to be a guest writer for the Times' ``Hers''
column. Later that year she joined the newspaper's editorial board.
Gary E. Cooper
</P>
<P>
	   ROANOKE, Va. (AP) -- Gary E. Cooper, a longtime Roanoke radio personality,
died Tuesday of an apparent heart attack. He was 62.
</P>
<P>
	   Cooper spent 38 years as host of ``Swap Shop'' on WRIS-AM until his
retirement in May. On ``Swap Shop,'' people call to buy, sell or trade their
personal belongings. Callers give a brief description of what they have to offer
and leave a telephone number.
</P>
<P>
	   From 1965 to 1981, Cooper made announcements at the Lee-Hi Drive-In.
</P>
<P>
	   He spent three years in the Army before returning to Roanoke to work at WROV
and later WRIS.
Lewis A. Head
</P>
<P>
	   LIVINGSTON MANOR, N.Y. (AP) -- Lewis A. Head, a longtime Associated Press
reporter and editor in New York and New Jersey, died Jan. 10. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
	   As an editor in the AP's Newark, N.J., bureau, Head was a mentor to a
generation of young AP journalists that included Victor Simpson, the news
cooperative's Vatican reporter; James Gerstenzang of the Los Angeles Times, and
Chris Connell, former assistant chief of the AP Washington bureau.
</P>
<P>
	   Robert A. Dubill, executive editor of USA Today, said Wednesday, ``He was
one of those dedicated editors who trained a large army of young journalists.''
</P>
<P>
	   Dubill, while AP's New Jersey bureau chief in the early 1970s, gave Head the
assignment to travel the state writing offbeat features and columns.
</P>
<P>
	   He worked as a photo editor at The New York Times from 1936 to 1941 and
joined the AP in 1941.
</P>
<P>
	   He retired from AP after a 35-year career in 1976.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to his wife, Head is survived by a daughter, Tamar Losec and his
sister Jessie Broadfoot.
Art Hoppe
</P>
<P>
	   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Art Hoppe, whose political and social satire
entertained readers of his syndicated column in the San Francisco Chronicle for
more than 40 years, died Tuesday from complications linked to lung cancer. He
was 74.
</P>
<P>
	   Hoppe's column featured a cast of whimsical characters -- lovable redneck
Joe Sixpak, Private Oliver Drab, all-knowing expert Homer T. Pettibone, the
celestial Heavenly Landlord and a presidential candidate named Nobody.
</P>
<P>
	   He joined the Chronicle as a copy boy in 1949 and was soon promoted to
reporter. He spent a week as a bum, trekked to a snowbound train in the Sierra
Nevada and was sent to Europe to explain to readers the foreign policy of
Liechtenstein and Monaco.
</P>
<P>
	   At the peak of the space race, he went to the African nation of Zambia,
where he described how astronauts were being trained by being rolled downhill in
barrels.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1960, he covered the presidential race between John Kennedy and Richard
Nixon.
</P>
<P>
	   He is survived by his wife, Gloria, and four children.
Joseph Eugene Jackson
</P>
<P>
	   NEWNAN, Ga. (AP) -- Joseph Eugene Jackson, the father of country music star
Alan Jackson, died Monday of a ruptured aorta. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
	   Jackson was a mechanic at the Ford Motor Co. assembly plant in Hapeville
from 1964 to 1989.
</P>
<P>
	   Diane Dawson, the singer's sister, said Alan Jackson used his parents' life
together as the basis of his song ``Livin' on Love.''
Gil Kane
</P>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- Gil Kane, the comic book artist who spent more than half a
century sketching such memorable characters as the Atom, Green Lantern, the
Hulk, Captain Marvel and Spider-Man, died Monday of cancer. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
	   Fans and collectors revered the work Kane did from 1956 to 1969. During that
period, he redesigned the costumes of Green Lantern and Captain Marvel.
</P>
<P>
	   Kane worked extensively for DC Comics and Marvel but also freelanced for
other producers of the genre. He illustrated a variety of DC's lines from
mysteries and westerns to Rex the Wonder Dog and science fiction.
</P>
<P>
	   Moving to Marvel, Kane drew the Hulk, Conan the Barbarian, Captain Marvel,
Spider-Man, Captain America, the Avengers and others.
</P>
<P>
	   In the 1980s, Kane spent about five years in Los Angeles, working on
animation concepts for Hanna-Barbera and Ruby-Spears. But he soon returned to
comics, illustrating the ``Ring'' for writer Roy Thomas in 1990 and drawing new
versions of Superman and illustrating ``The Edge.''
</P>
<P>
	   Kane also drew the ``Starhawks'' comic strip for newspapers for five years.
Sister Madonna Kolbenschlag
</P>
<P>
	   MORGANTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- Sister Madonna Kolbenschlag, an author and former
House of Representatives policy analyst, died Saturday of a stroke in Santiago,
Chile. She was 64.
</P>
<P>
	   She taught American studies and women's studies at the University of Notre
Dame in the 1980s and worked as a legislative aide and research consultant in
the U.S. House of Representatives. She also was involved in human rights
investigations in Central America.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1998, Sister Kolbenschlag became the first woman appointed Ecumenical
Fellow at the National Cathedral in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
	   Her six books include, ``Kiss Sleeping Beauty Goodbye,'' which has been
translated into five languages, and ``Eastward Toward Eve,'' for which she
earned the 1996 Body, Mind, Spirit Award of Excellence.
Dr. James V. Neel
</P>
<P>
	   ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Dr. James V. Neel, professor emeritus of human
genetics and internal medicine at the University of Michigan, died Tuesday of
cancer. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
	   During his 39 years at the University of Michigan Medical School, Neel
established the first academic department of human genetics in the United
States, and one of the first clinics to evaluate and counsel people with
hereditary diseases.
</P>
<P>
	   He was among the first scientists to recognize the genetic basis for sickle
cell anemia. He extensively studied the aftereffects of atomic radiation on
survivors of Hiroshima and Nagasaki and their children.
</P>
<P>
	   Neel's awards and honors included election to the National Academy of
Sciences, the Allen Award from the American Society of Human Genetics, the
National Medal of Science and the Smithsonian Institution Medal.
Alan Pryce-Jones
</P>
<P>
	   GALVESTON, Texas (AP) -- Alan Pryce-Jones, once editor of The Times Literary
Supplement, a prestigious British weekly, died Jan. 22. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
	   Pryce-Jones moved to the New York after his tenure atop The Times Literary
Supplement from 1948-59, writing reviews for several publications, including
Newsday and The New York Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
	   Pryce-Jones also wrote several books, culminating with his memoirs in 1987,
titled ``The Bonus of Laughter.''
</P>
<P>
	   His first literary job was at age 19 as assistant editor at The London
Mercury.
</P>
<P>
	   Pryce-Jones married Therese ``Poppy'' Fould-Springer in 1934, but she died
in 1953. He remarried in 1968 to Mary Jean Thorne, who died a year later.
</P>
<P>
	   He is survived by a son from his first marriage, David Pryce-Jones of
London, and Daniel Thorne, his stepson from his second marriage.
Raymond R. Suskind
</P>
<P>
	   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Raymond R. Suskind, a physician whose work helped advance
skin research and environmental health study, died Monday. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1948, Suskind developed a skin physiology and toxicology research program
at the university's Kettering Laboratory. His work contributed to research that
disclosed the effects of ultraviolet light on skin. In 1962, he established an
environmental medicine research unit at the University of Oregon Medical School.
</P>
<P>
	   Suskind came to Cincinnati General Hospital to complete an internship in
1944 and a residency in dermatology in 1948. He was also a fellow in preventive
medicine and industrial health at Kettering Laboratory from 1948 to 1950.
</P>
<P>
	   He returned to Cincinnati to become director of the Kettering Laboratory in
1969. After retiring as its director in 1986, he continued to do research and
teach at the medical school.
Willie B.
</P>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- Willie B., the Zoo Atlanta gorilla who spent 27 years in
isolation with only a caretaker and a television for company before being
introduced to other gorillas and finally becoming a father, died Wednesday. He
was 41.
</P>
<P>
	   Willie had been sick since early January, when he caught the flu and then
contracted pneumonia, which caused stress on his heart.
</P>
<P>
	   The silverback gorilla, named for former Atlanta Mayor William B.
Hartsfield, was captured in Africa and spent more than two decades in a
concrete-and-steel-bars cage at the former Atlanta-Fulton County Zoo. Besides a
caretaker, his only companion was a TV set on a shelf in the corner of the cage.
He played on a tire swing.
</P>
<P>
	   Willie was one of the first gorillas released into the new habitat in early
1988.
John Yager
</P>
<P>
	   TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) -- John Yager, a former Toledo mayor who fought against a
strong-mayor form of government, died Monday. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
	   He was elected to the Toledo City Council in 1955 and became mayor two years
later.
</P>
<P>
	   At that time, council members selected the mayor, and a city manager was the
top government official. Toledo changed to the direct election strong-mayor
system with the election in 1994 of the current mayor, Democrat Carty
Finkbeiner.
Si Zentner
</P>
<P>
	   LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Si Zentner, the Trombonist who started a highly successful
big band years after the era had passed, died Monday. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
	   Zentner became well-known when he recorded the hit ``Up A Lazy River'' in
1961. He went on to record more than 30 albums and hundreds of songs for Liberty
Records.
</P>
<P>
	   He played with the bands of Les Brown and Jimmy Dorsey before settling in
Los Angeles as a session musician.
</P>
<P>
	   Using a revised version of ``Lazy River,'' Zenter recorded what he called
``the first big-band record you could twist to.'' The song became a Top 40 hit
and a Grammy Award winner.
</P>
<P>
	   Zentner recorded hundreds of songs for Liberty, continuing his knack for
recasting contemporary hits into a big-band sound aimed at older ears. During
the James Bond craze he reworked the movies' themes, and when the Beatles
exploded, he recorded a swinging version of ``I Want to Hold Your Hand.''
Janet C. Zink
</P>
<P>
	   TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- Janet C. Zink, a philanthropist whose volunteer work
ranged from the fine arts to the Girl Scouts, died Monday. She was 60.
</P>
<P>
	   Funeral officials said they did not know the cause of death.
</P>
<P>
	   She devoted her time to her family and her community, serving on boards that
included the Department of Human Services Children's Service, the Gilcrease
Museum, Tulsa Garden Center and Magic Empire Council of Girl Scouts. She was
chairwoman of the 1992 Cinderella Ball in support of the Tulsa Philharmonic and
the 1998 Philbrook Gala.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year she received the Premier Volunteer Award from Volunteers of
America.
</P>
