<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Faces Murder Charges  </HEADLINE>
   By AMY FRANKLIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BARABOO, Wis. (AP) -- A former teacher was charged Wednesday with killing
his cousin, whose dismembered body, skinned beyond recognition, washed up in a
river last summer.
</P>
<P>
	   It took authorities six months to identify the victim as Mwivano Mwambashi
Kupaza, 25, a student from Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
	   A break in the case came when the defendant's ex-wife was questioned by
investigators Jan. 21. She had called police anonymously in November, saying a
victim portrayed in a law-enforcement poster resembled a relative she hadn't
seen in some time.
</P>
<P>
	   When investigators questioned the victim's cousin, Peter Kupaza, 40, on
Monday, he told them Mwivano Kupaza had gone back to Tanzania in April,
according to the criminal complaint filed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Records of a search of Peter Kupaza's apartment in Madison show police found
knives, items belonging to the victim and plastic bags similar to a bag found
with parts of the victim's body.
</P>
<P>
	   He was charged Wednesday with first-degree intentional homicide and
dismembering a corpse with the intent to conceal a crime.
</P>
<P>
	   Mwivano Kupaza had been attending the Wisconsin English Second Language
Institute in Madison on a student visa since 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Her torso was spotted along the Wisconsin River by a couple picnicking last
July. The following day, a head, arms and legs were found in plastic bags
floating along the shore.
</P>
<P>
	   An autopsy could not determine the cause of death. Authorities said the
identification process was difficult because the skin was removed from most of
the woman's body, including her face.
</P>
<P>
	   Peter Kupaza was to appear in court on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2341 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000202.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Drought Continues  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- Seasonal rains were not enough to ease a drought in
large parts of this east African nation, leaving at least 2 million Kenyans in
need of food aid, the U.N. World Food Program said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The WFP appealed to donor nations for $43 million to purchase food for the
needy over the next five months.
</P>
<P>
	   Kenya has a long rainy season between March and May and short rains between
October and December, but for the past several years they have not been enough.
</P>
<P>
	   According to reports compiled by the government and aid agencies, the
situation remains most critical in the north, where inhabitants are suffering
from three successive crop failures as well as drought and floods, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
	   WFP said in parts of eastern Kenya people have eaten seeds meant for
planting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-02-00 2343 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
