<DOCNO> APW20000202.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-02 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Convicted in Argentina Murder  </HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN GRAY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- A tribunal sentenced eight people to life in
prison Wednesday in the death of a crusading journalist, ending a case that
shocked Argentines and drew international outrage.
</P>
<P>
	   A three-judge panel found three former provincial police officers, a former
security guard and four civilians guilty of killing Jose Luis Cabezas, an
investigative photojournalist. A fourth police officer was sentenced to four
years on a fraud charge related to the case.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm comfortable with the decisions handed down by the tribunal,'' Cabezas'
mother, Maria Cristina Robledo, after the verdicts were announced following the
near three-month trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Cabezas was found dead Jan. 25, 1997, in the glitzy Atlantic coast resort of
Pinamar, 250 miles south of Buenos Aires. He had been handcuffed, beaten, shot
in the head and burned.
</P>
<P>
	   To some, the mafia-style murder was eerily reminiscent of the work of
military death squads during Argentina's 1976-83 dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
	   The slaying spurred nationwide rallies, church services and vigils and drew
protest from abroad. Argentine journalists condemned the killing as evidence of
an increasing threat against freedom of the press.
</P>
<P>
	   The 36-year-old photographer had been shadowing Alfredo Yabran, a camera-shy
businessman whose links to government officials and vast business empire had
come under question.
</P>
<P>
	   Before his death, Cabezas had published a few photographs of the reclusive
Yabran.
</P>
<P>
	   The businessman immediately became a prime suspect in Cabezas murder case,
along with his chief security guard -- who was among those sentenced to life in
prison Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Yabran, known to be unnerved by Cabezas' coverage of him, repeatedly denied
allegations he was involved in the photographer's death.
</P>
<P>
	   But last year Yabran, who was wanted for questioning, went on the run and
became the focus of a nationwide man hunt. He shot himself to death as police
closed in on him at his country resort last May. A handwritten note left by his
side professed his innocence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
